<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>C</FONT>onverting <FONT SIZE=+3>C</FONT>lassroom <FONT SIZE=+3>C</FONT>ourses  </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>


<CENTER><H3>A Template for Converting Classroom Courses<BR> to Distributed, Asynchronous Courses</H2>
<A HREF="mailto:lowell_roberts@unc.edu">Lowell H. Roberts</A>, IAT Director (Interim)
<BR>[Latest Version: November 1, 1995]
<P></CENTER>
<HR><P>

<H3>1. What are the objectives of the course?</H3>
<UL>
<LI>NOT what you are teaching; not even what you expect students to do.
<LI>But WHY you are teaching it and why do you expect students to do it.
<LI>I.e., when the course is over, what should the students KNOW (defined as the capacity  to apply what they've learned to untutored situations) and UNDERSTAND (defined as the capacity to apply what they know to untutored abstractions)?
</UL>

<H3>2. Align current content with the objectives.</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Objectives should not need to be altered, but content (at least how it is presented)
              may undergo significant change.
<LI>This may seem simplistic, but the intent is to protect the integrity of the course -- i.e., to insure the distributed, asynchronous version achieves the same outcomes as the classroom version, as measured through the learning objectives.
<LI>Don't be disturbed if some content does not align with an objective.  The art of
             teaching rests as much on how we teach as what we teach; i.e., on stimulating
             interest, promoting understanding, facilitating transfer in a non-situated environment.</UL>

<H3>3. Based on the alignment of content and objectives, address the following questions:</H3>

<P><B>3.1.</B> What can be learned by discovery (constructivism) or peer interaction (collaboration), rather than direct instruction?  I.e., what do you feel you can                      surrender control of?
<UL>
<LI>Asynchronous communication places control of communication process and processing largely with each receiver -- almost the polar opposite of the lecture.
<LI>Teaching becomes facilitating and guiding, rather than instructing.
<LI>If you decide that control over most of the syllabus cannot be surrendered to the students (e.g., the course introduces skills or principles that are not efficaciously learned except by direct instruction), this is probably not an appropriate course for conversion to asynchronous delivery.</UL>

<P><B>3.2.</B> What content doesn't align with objectives?  I.e., what is covered that has little to do with outcome measures, but is included to promote student interest and/or
understanding?
<UL>
<LI>As students take increased control of the learning process (and given the
	   nature of asynchronous communication), there is little need (or time) for
	   content padding.
<LI>Students develop their own tactical approaches to understanding.  
	   [Obviously, this kind of learning is not for every student; nor is this kind
	   of teaching for every instructor.  But neither is the lecture.]
<LI>Rather than providing "the examples," the instructor must provide time 
	   and opportunity for the students to discover and apply "the examples" on
	   their own.</UL>


<H3>4. If you had a fully equipped multimedia classroom with a direct connection to the World Wide  Web and no time constraints, what would you do differently from what you do in the classroom now?  I.e., what learning and instructional activities and resources normally excluded from the standard classroom might you use to enhance interest, understanding and transfer.</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Imagine potential access to any library, database, data bank, publication, or
             individual in the world.	
<LI>Examine off-the-shelf software, CD-ROMs and videos -- think modular.
<P>Now leave the room.
<P><LI>You initiate use of this stuff and make yourself available as a guide or resource,
              but each student will be relatively in charge of her progress and mastery.</UL>

<H3>5. Based on your answers in 3A, 3B, and 4:</H3>

<P><B>5.1.</B> Design a course structure that will replace lectures as the primary means of realizing the course objectives -- e.g., a collaborative or self-paced environment.

<P><B>5.2.</B> Design activities that are appropriate to the environment -- e.g., team exercises or mastery modules; the outcomes of these activities should be measurable in
 terms of one or more objectives.

<P><B>5.3.</B> Design activities that provide direct instruction for those aspects of the course that require it -- e.g., a study guide or hypermediated, connected readings; again, the outcomes should be measurable in terms of the objectives.

<P><B>5.4.</B> Design procedures to help students pace and assess their progress -- e.g., complement self-pacing with electronic discussions or collaboration with
 benchmarks or periodic outputs.

<P><B>5.5.</B> Design methods of evaluation that are appropriate to the medium -- e.g., content-focused exams cannot measure learning outcomes of collaborative
 or constructivist environments.
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=400 SIZE=2 ALIGN=CENTER>

