<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2>The <FONT SIZE=+3>N</FONT>etwork as <FONT SIZE=+3>S</FONT>trategic <FONT SIZE=+3>A</FONT>sset: </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3>The Network as Strategic Asset: 
The Path to Learning Productivity</H3>
<A HREF="mailto:lowell_roberts@unc.edu">Lowell H. Roberts</A>, IAT Director (Interim)</CENTER>

<P>
Let's talk strategic investments in higher education -- where
should we be putting our money?      

<P>
Conventional classroom instruction will always have an important place in higher
education.  Real-time televised distance learning is a viable
and appropriate short-term solution to meeting instructional
demand in an environment of significantly reduced resources. 
But the wisest strategic investment, I believe, is computer
networking. 

<P>
Computer networks have major advantages over television or
conventional educational environments: 
<OL>
<LI>

<LIthey do not require
fixed spaces such as classrooms or studios; literally,
instructors teach and students learn wherever they are; 

<LI>their
use is not limited to fixed times; they are available to
instructors and students 24 hours a day; 
<LI>since
computer-delivered education is not bound by place or time, it
is demand-activated by each user and, therefore, 
consumes virtually no resources except when in use; 

<LI>they
provide a single infrastructure for most, if not all, university
functions and services: instruction, research, communications;

<LI>accordingly, networks can integrate the instructional and
management layers of curriculum delivery; and 

<LI>computer
networks permit individuals access to worldwide resources,
thereby centering the educational process in learning, rather
than teaching;  Of all investments, networks will prove easiest
to modify as future exigencies dictate -- a classroom can be
crowded or empty, but it cannot be expanded or contracted.    

</OL>

<P>
Networks, then, make the processes of education more productive.
 But perhaps their greatest advantage is their potential to make
the processes of learning more productive.  We long ago forgot
that teaching, a medieval invention, provides a virtual learning
experience.  Since students did not have access to primary
sources or resources, teachers created representations
(lectures, texts) to acquaint students with materials they could
not access or manipulate themselves.   Computer networks, on the
other hand, can provide access to primary sources and resources,
making learning experiences direct and real.  But conventional
schooling imposes on all learners and all learning the quality
and access constraints of an artifact of conditions 700 years
ago.  No wonder we are often unhappy with the results and with
the costs.

<P>
Since all the sensory tools of teaching and learning can be
digitized -- text, pictures, sound, moving images -- the
educational capacity of computer networks is probably limitless.
 In addition, education over computer networks can be asynchronous
(i.e., communication among users does not occur at a given
moment in time).  Thus, networks provide an educational
environment of enormous resources and great flexibility at a
fraction of the cost of conventional environments.  Students can
learn while working or caregiving.  Instruction can use multiple
media without special classrooms and draw on resources wherever
they are stored.  The same lesson can be received at home or work or in the dorm -- or
used in the classroom.  Learning can be self-paced or
cohort-paced. The gateway to learning productivity is the
computer network.

<P>

Contrary to popular myth, networked education is neither
expensive nor difficult to use.  A minimum home computer
configuration can be purchased for roughly $1000 and requires
only a standard telephone line for connection to a network. 
Many institutions have developed methods to permit even the most novice students to be fully
participating members of network classes with little or no
formal training.  Those who have tried the increasingly powerful
presentation programs or newer simplified authoring programs 
know that preparing mediated presentations is becoming as easy
as word processing.  Similar tools will permit faculty to
prepare multimedia modules for network delivery as easily as
they write lectures for the classroom.


<P>
Most technology-mediated forms of instruction are extensions of
conventional forms -- interactive television is certainly the
prime example.  Similarly, instructional uses of computing are,
largely, add-ons to traditional instruction.  The educational environment
created by computer networks, however, is a true paradigm shift.
 For this reason, and not for reasons of cost or complexity, the  academy will take longer to adopt networked instruction,
although it is becoming increasingly common.  And because it is
a paradigm shift, computer networking can be the foundation of a
more productive, cost-effective university of the near future.

<P>
Roberts, Lowell H. "The Network as Strategic Asset: the Path to Learning Productivity."  <EM>The NLII Viewpoint</EM> 1, no. 1 (Spring/Summer 1996): 24-25.

<BR>
