<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>PDL: </FONT>Request for Partners </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>





<B>A Request for Partners</B>
<BR>from the
<BR><B>Institute for Academic Technology</B>
<BR>Under the Aegis of
<BR><B>EDUCOM's National Learning Infrastructure Initiative</B>
<P>
[<A HREF="#purpose">Purpose</A> | <A HREF="#educom">EDUCOM & NLII</A> | <A HREF="#work">Work Description</A> | <BR><A HREF="#participate">Who Should Participate</A> | <A HREF="#membership">Membership</A> | <A HREF="#joining">Joining the Partnership</A>]</CENTER>
<HR>

<H3>About the Institute for Academic Technology</H3>

<P>The Institute for Academic Technology (IAT) was conceived and established at 
the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill in 1989 with generous 
support from IBM Higher Education.  Now accounting for approximately 45% of 
the IAT's budget, IBM Higher Education's support continues to provide 
leverage for self-sustaining outreach programs and a variety of research and 
development contracts and grants.  

<P>As a university-operated national R&D 
center designed to foster collaboration between academe and the information 
technology industry, the IAT has helped many educational institutions, 
publishing companies, and instructional software developers strengthen the 
quality of their instructional programs and products by taking advantage of 
multimedia and network technologies.  These successes owe much to the IAT's 
resident technologists and faculty researchers.  Academic backgrounds at the 
IAT are in mathematics and second language acquisition and include extensive 
academic administrative experience, but the IAT's technology-transfer work 
with teachers, scholars, and academic administrators from across the nation 
has cut across the spectrum of disciplines, professions, and institutional 
types.

<H3><A NAME="purpose">Purpose</A> of the Partnership for Distributed Learning</H3>

<P>The Partnership provides an opportunity for institutions, organizations, and 
companies to work closely with the IAT and to benefit from its work and the 
leverage of the resources and expertise provided by IBM and other companies 
and funding agencies now collaborating with the IAT.  In particular, the IAT 
is directing its research and development efforts towards understanding and 
prototyping distributed learning environments.  The Partnership thus offers 
an opportunity for a selected number of Partners to help determine the 
direction of this effort and to benefit from it.  

<P>Because the World Wide Web has become an open standard for 
navigating and publishing on the Internet, the initial effort will be to 
develop requirements for tools that will enrich the Web as a medium for 
delivering courses and curricula.  These tools therefore must: 

<OL>
<LI>support faculty efforts to integrate Web-based learning resources into credit-bearing learning modules and courses, 

<LI>provide students with Web-based access to immersion learning software and related software for assessing learning outcomes, 

<LI>support Web-based asynchronous (time-independent) and real-time communications among learners and their instructors (learner to learner and learner to instructor), 

<LI>help structure and manage the instructional process when students, instructors, 
and learning resources are widely distributed, and 

<LI>support the creation of environments that encourage the social creation of knowledge among learners.</OL> 

<P>The tool suites that we envision must be standards-based and the alternative 
instructional models that they enable must be scalable and sustainable.  
These requirements must guide the effort whether the eventual costs of 
developing high quality distributed learning materials are borne by higher 
education or by the commercial sector.  Our effort accordingly will be 
designed to demonstrate an institutionally affordable and commercially 
viable model for creating and delivering distributed education -- courses 
and curricula.  

<P>Distributed learning environments promise scalable, cost-efficient solutions 
to the pressing, systemic educational problems that are being articulated 
and addressed in a national movement:  EDUCOM's National Learning 
Infrastructure Initiative (NLII).  Indeed, the Partnership is designed to be 
a vertical microcosm of the NLII, an effort to drill deeper into some of the 
concepts and goals that animate the NLII.

<H3><A NAME="educom">Relationship to EDUCOM's National Learning Infrastructure Initiative</A></H3> 

<P>Increasing the quality of instruction is only a partially sufficient 
response to today's educational challenge.  Economic and other external 
forces are pressuring educational institutions, not only to increase the 
quality of learning, but simultaneously to contain the cost of instruction 
and increase access to education.  This systemic challenge can be met only 
if many educational institutions, policy organizations, and companies in the 
educational market synchronize their efforts.  This is the goal of EDUCOM's 
National Learning Infrastructure Initiative.  The chief strategy of the NLII 
is to facilitate "Requests For Partners" as a means to spawn a variety of 
prototype projects designed to foster educational change, both at the level 
of practice and policy and with the goal of increasing quality and access 
while containing costs.  This document, then, is a request for partners 
under the aegis of the NLII.

<P>Institutions, organizations, and companies interested in joining the 
Partnership should consider joining the more comprehensive NLII if they are 
not already members.  Queries are welcome at <A HREF="mailto:nlii@educom.edu">NLII@EDUCOM.EDU</A>.  Participation 
in the IAT's Partnership, however, does not require participation in 
EDUCOM's NLII.

<H3><A NAME="work">Description of the Work</A></H3>

<B>Modus operandi: </B> Meetings of the full Partnership will provide an 
opportunity to 1) review new technologies identified or developed by the IAT 
or a Partner as potentially applicable to Partnership themes, 2) report and 
critique Partnership work in progress, 3) debate and advance the 
requirements for Web-based distributed instruction and learning, and 4) 
propose new projects and, when such proposals carry a price, determine 
whether enough Partners are willing to invest in the project to undertake 
it.  For example, the IAT might propose to port <A HREF="http://ike.engr.washington.edu/iat/software/express/index.html">Express Author</A>, its 
Windows-based multimedia authoring tool, to a networked cross-platform 
environment, such as Kaleida's ScriptX.   By virtue of its seat at the 
table, any Partner could choose to invest in this effort.  The porting 
project would proceed if enough investors stepped forward, and then these 
investors would determine, for example, issues of ownership and 
distribution.  Any Partner would have the same rights as the IAT to propose 
new projects, but the Partners can expect the IAT to develop agendas for the 
meetings and to propose well researched projects as part of the IAT's 
contribution to the Partnership.

<P><B>Electronic forum:</B>  Partners also will have the opportunity to participate in 
a closed electronic forum on the themes and work of the Partnership.  The 
IAT will organize some part of the discourse and Partners will be expected 
to organize other parts.  The forum itself first will be a listserv but will 
evolve into a distributed learning environment for the Partners' benefit.

<P><B>Participation in other IAT projects and programs:</B>  One of the benefits of 
participation in the Partnership is a close working relationship with the 
IAT.  The IAT will consider the Partners as potential collaborators in all 
of its projects.  This might include, for example, 1) "beta" access to new 
technologies, 2) various forms of participation in a project to develop 
distributed learning modules in college algebra and pre-calculus 
mathematics, 3) collaboration with a publishing company now working with the 
IAT to define and possibly undertake an English-as-a-Second-Language 
project, and 4) prototyping distributed learning environments in other 
curricular areas using tools identified or developed by the IAT.  
Participation in such efforts would be subject to the approval of their 
sponsors.  The IAT also will extend a 10% discount to qualifying Partners 
for its Affiliate Program.  (The <A HREF="../affiliate/affiliate.html">Affiliate Program</A> trains trainers to offer 
IAT-developed workshops on a regional basis at their institutions.  More 
information is available on request through <A HREF="mailto:mary_edeburn@unc.edu">Mary_Edeburn@unc.edu</A>.)

<P><B>Frequency and location of business meetings:</B>  The IAT will organize at least 
two meetings per year of the full Partnership.  At least one of these 
meetings will be held at the IAT.  If a site with appropriate infrastructure 
can be located, one meeting might be located closer to the west coast.  In 
addition, the IAT will report the progress of the Partnership at meetings of 
the NLII.  If there is reason to convene the full Partnership at any NLII 
meeting, all Partners will be welcome to participate in other NLII sessions 
as well, whether or not they are members of the NLII.  Up to four 
participants from each participating Partner may attend the business 
meetings.  Some Partners may choose to participate in specific development 
activities, and any related working meetings will be scheduled as needed and 
as conveniently as possible.  (Participants will pay their own travel 
expenses to participate in Partnership meetings.)  

<P><B>The work philosophy:</B>  The IAT's plan to research and prototype distributed 
learning environments will draw on 1) existing products and work at the IAT, 
2) any synergistic work that other Partners can bring to the table, and 3) 
emerging standards-based, commercial Internet/Web tools.  The long-term 
technical strategy is to design toward, and port tools and applications to, 
an object-oriented framework as independent of hardware and operating system 
as is possible.  Meanwhile, the IAT has several successful products to 
deploy in the effort:  WebApp, Express Author, MathKit, and a host of 
interlingual tools.  The IAT's plan to develop a distributed learning 
environment accordingly will draw on these products and will be focused by 
those content areas in which the IAT has faculty expertise:  mathematics and 
second language acquisition.  There is no requirement, however, that 
participating partners be interested in these products and content areas -- 
although some may be.  

<P><B>WebApp:</B>  The IAT has developed <A HREF="http://ike.engr.washington.edu/iat/software/webapp/index.html">WebApp</A> as a helper application for Web 
browsers that automates the downloading and running of application software 
into a single mouse click.  For example, until and if powerful application 
development tools are integrated into the Web environment, WebApp makes it 
possible to run immersion learning software from within a Web page in a way 
that is independent of the location of the learning software.  A Windows 
version of WebApp is already accessible through the IAT's Web site, and a Macintosh version is under development.  

<P><B>Express Author:</B>  <A HREF="http://ike.engr.washington.edu/iat/software/express/index.html">Express Author</A> is a tested set of point-and-click 
tools for creating interactive, multimedia ToolBook "books" in the Windows 
environment.  It was created with extensive input from academic authors, and 
the IAT offers training in its use.  Through Express Author, the IAT has become very 
familiar with ease-of-use features and with the issues involved in 
commercializing and distributing software.  The immediate opportunity is to 
utilize Express Author and WebApp in combination to create distributed, Web-based 
libraries of immersion learning materials.  The longer-term opportunity is 
to port Express Author to a networked cross-platform environment, such as that 
potentially provided by Kaleida's ScriptX.

<P><B>MathKit:</B>  <A HREF="http://ike.engr.washington.edu/iat/software/mathkit/index.html">MathKit</A> provides object-oriented mathematical functionality to any 
Windows software development environment, such as ToolBook or Visual Basic. 
 The result is a development environment giving authors access to reusable 
mathematical objects, such as 2- and 3-dimensional graphing windows and a 
scripting language with numeric and symbolic capacities.  Unlike 
self-contained computer algebra systems, MathKit is highly modular and 
extensible and was designed for creating mathematical learning materials.  
It has been extensively tested in K-12 and in higher education as the core 
engine of a commercial product, EduQuest's ToolKit for Interactive 
Mathematics, which recently was named by Technology & Learning as one of the 
"Top Six Products of the Year."  Additional MathKit-based authoring products 
will be released soon.  One of these products links MathKit into Express 
Author and Multimedia ToolBook 3.0.  MathKit has already been deployed in 
conjunction with WebApp to develop a prototype Web-based library of 
immersion learning modules in mathematics accessible through the IAT's Web 
site cited above.

<P><B>Interlingual tools:</B>  A team of authors at the IAT has produced writing 
assistant software for language study.  Language databases supply lexical 
and grammatical information, along with pronunciation assistance and 
culturally appropriate multimedia material for listening comprehension.  
These products, specializing in foreign language support for speakers of 
American English, demonstrate feasibility for network implementation and 
indicate that the model can be generalized for any pair of source and target 
languages.  The IAT hopes to prototype this generalization in the 
Internet/Web context, and this work will help inform the Partners' work in 
developing requirements for creating distributed learning environments.

<H3><A NAME="participate">Which Institutions and Companies Should Participate</A></H3>

<P><B>Higher education:</B>  Participating colleges and universities should be 
prepared to 1) send representatives to the Partnership's business meetings, 
2) participate in the Partnership's electronic forum, and 3) possibly invest 
in projects that will advance the development of distributed learning 
environments.  They will have additional in-kind opportunities to become 
involved in 1) the development or evaluation of content and assessment 
materials, 2) the development of technologies to organize and manage 
distributed instruction, and 3) the development of alternative course 
models.

<P><B>Commercial sector:</B>  Creating an affordable and sustainable distributed 
instructional environment will require the utilization of object 
technologies along with the quality assurance of collaborative institutional 
commitments and/or commercially produced materials and standards-based 
assessment vehicles.  This argues for the participation of companies hoping 
to develop markets in higher education as the "National Information 
Infrastructure" (NII) develops into an open, scalable system during the 
years ahead.  The IAT therefore hopes to attract companies from the content, 
testing, telecommunications, and hardware/software industries to participate 
directly or indirectly in the Partnership in ways that will enhance the 
development of their markets.  Indeed, the IAT's corporate partner, IBM 
Higher Education, views the Partnership as a vehicle to develop expertise, 
technologies, and business relationships as the foundation for doing 
business in a new era in the higher education market.  IBM Higher Education 
therefore will help the Partnership locate pertinent expertise and 
technologies, both within IBM's extended family of labs and product 
divisions and within its circle of potential business collaborators from the 
NII industry at large.  For example, some of the keystone tools for IAT's 
experiments in second language acquisition in a distributed environment were 
the result of years of work in an IBM research lab.  Moreover, IBM's K-12 
group, EduQuest, licensed MathKit from the IAT as the core engine for 
ToolKit for Interactive Mathematics, which was successfully introduced into 
the K-12 market early this year as an award-winning authoring and 
exploratory mathematical environment for students and teachers.  

<P><B>Other non-profit organizations:</B>  Foundations and government agencies are 
welcome to participate in a manner that contributes to their mission and to 
the work of the Partnership.

<H3><A NAME="membership">Resource and Membership Strategy</A></H3>

<P>The resource strategy has three primary thrusts:
<OL>
<LI>Each Partner will pay $5,000 annually for a seat at the table.  This 
fee will help defray the IAT's costs in organizing and managing the 
Partnership and will allow all involved to advance their generic 
understanding of distributed learning in a systematic way that relies on 
on-going work at the IAT and at participating institutions, organizations, 
and companies.  The IAT reserves the right to limit membership to 
approximately 25 Partners to ensure a meaningful experience for all 
participants.

<LI>Projects requiring additional investment will be proposed through 
the Partnership's business meetings and electronic forum.  Project proposals 
will include a business plan and a work plan.  The Partners will have an 
opportunity to discuss, shape, and invest in these projects at the 
Partnership's business meetings.  No project will proceed as a Partnership 
activity unless it gains enough investors for implementation.  These 
investors will then determine the particulars of the project.  Such projects 
may be proposed and sponsored by the IAT or by any Partner.

<LI>The IAT will inform the Partners of opportunities to participate in 
other projects and programs that have been organized and sponsored outside 
of the Partnership.  Some of these, such as developing immersion learning 
materials for ESL, college algebra, and pre-calculus mathematics, may 
contribute directly to the goals of the Partnership while requiring no more 
than in-kind investments from interested Partners.  Others, such as the IAT 
Affiliate Program, provide an additional opportunity for interested Partners 
to advance their institutional missions in close collaboration with the IAT 
by delivering IAT-developed workshops in their area of the country.   </OL>

<H3><A NAME="joining">Joining the Partnership</A></H3>

<P>The IAT welcomes immediate interest in the Partnership.  Members will be 
invoiced $5,000 in the fall of each year.  Any institution, organization, or 
company failing to pay its first invoice no later than 30 days after the 
fall meeting of the Partnership will be assumed to have decided against 
participation.  This fall's meeting is tentatively scheduled at the IAT for 
October 16-17.  Meanwhile, the current listserv, partners@unc.edu, will 
remain open to all interested parties.  If you want to be added to the list, 
please contact <A HREF="mailto:partners@unc.edu">partners@unc.edu</A>. 

<P>Your institution, organization, or company can join the Partnership by 
designating, in a letter or e-mail message, a representative to be the point 
of contact with the IAT.  Write to the IAT:	
	
<P><DD>Mary Edeburn
<DD>Institute for Academic Technology, Suite 400
<DD>2525 Meridian Parkway
<DD>Durham, NC  27713
<DD>E-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:mary_edeburn@unc.edu">Mary_Edeburn@unc.edu</A><P>


<BR>
