<P>
<A HREF="#grant">Grant Activities to Date</A> | <A HREF="#deliv">Delivery Tools</A> | <A HREF="#inter">Interaction Management Tools</A> | <A HREF="#course">Course Management Tools</A> | <A HREF="#net">Networks</A> | <A HREF="#meaning">Creating Meaning from the Asynchronous Learning Experience</A> | <A HREF="#iat">IAT’s Leadership Experience</A> | <A HREF="#conc">Conclusion</A>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="grant">Grant Activities to Date</A></H3>
<P>The <A HREF="http://www.sloan.org/">Alfred P. Sloan Foundation</A> awarded a $30,000 planning grant to the Institute for Academic Technology (IAT) in June 1995. This planning grant funded IAT efforts to explore and define the requirements for using the World Wide Web as a means for creating distributed learning environments. Some of the funds in the planning grant were earmarked for convening several groups interested and/or involved in developing asynchronous learning environments, specifically the Partnership for Distributed Learning and selected Sloan Foundation Asynchronous Learning Network participants. Since then we have convened a meeting of the Partnership for Distributed Learning (PDL) in Keystone, Colorado. The Keystone meeting with the Partnership was held in conjunction with <A HREF="http://educom.edu/">EDUCOM</A>’s National Learning Infrastructure Initiative <A HREF="http://educom.edu/program/nlii/.index.html">(NLII)</A>. This meeting gave the IAT and prospective Partnership members the opportunity to explore issues related to using and evaluating the Internet and World Wide Web as a viable means to create and use distributed learning environments to deliver instruction.

<P>Several members of the IAT also visited the Sloan Center for Asynchronous Learning Environments <A HREF="http://w3.scale.uiuc.edu/scale/">(SCALE)</A> at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign (UIUC). Various faculty involved with the SCALE project demonstrated the way they used computer conferencing and Web technologies to conduct parts of their courses asynchronously. Discussions with SCALE participants presented some "real-life" experience using asynchronous tools to teach.

<P>Both groups (the SCALE project faculty and prospective PDL members) expressed similar interest in exploring all possible asynchronous tools and ways of using them in both on- and off-campus learning environments. A catalog of tools and capabilities mentioned included:  

<UL>
<LI>Conferencing over networks, both asynchronous and synchronous. Interests included text, audio, desktop video, whiteboard, data standards and language standards.
<LI>Multiple User Dimensions (MUDs) and MUDs-Object Oriented (MOOs).
<LI>Real Audio and Video (on-demand, streaming audio and/or video).
<LI>Multiple media windows.
<LI>Assessment tools.
</UL>

<P>The Partnership discussions also yielded a list of issues associated with the use of the Internet and the World Wide Web for not only delivering, but also managing learning environments. These included:

<UL>
<LI>Publishing standards:
	<DD>Authoring tools,
	<DD>Reading tools, and
	<DD>Multiple delivery formats. 
<LI>Registration.
<LI>Authentication.
<LI>Crediting.
<LI>Mapping available and new tools to appropriate functionalities in a learning environment.
<LI>Mapping learning objectives to appropriate resources, such as applications for learning and assessment.
<LI>Acquiring or developing templates from which to construct application prototypes.  
</UL>

<P>Many similar interests have been discussed on the Sloan Foundation listserv for the Asynchronous Learning Network <A HREF="http://www.sloan.org/education/aln/new.html">(ALN)</A> project sites. Participants expressed  the need for: finding a coherent approach to using Web-based delivery tools; defining the functionality for course management elements such as planning and implementing courses in a distributed learning environment; and developing an integrated system for registration, credit allocation and assessment.

<H3><A NAME="deliv">Delivery Tools</A></H3>

<P>The above list of Web and Internet tools demonstrates both the range of interest and the range of functionality already available for delivering content on the Web. Every week prototypes of promising new delivery tools appear.  

<P>Worlds, Inc. has debuted an intriguing multi-user environment that is a combination of a MOO and 3-dimensional modeling. Called <A HREF="http://www.worlds.net">Worlds Chat</A>, this application allows multiple synchronous users to join several types of 3-dimensional environments and chat with individuals or groups of up to six people within the environment. Individuals select "avatars" to represent themselves graphically as they move about the environment and interact with others through text-based dialogue. Tools such as this foreshadow the ability to create much more sophisticated virtual learning environments on the Web. In these learning environments participants could act individually or collaboratively, interacting with other individuals, with smart objects, or simulations. Interactive functions could go beyond text-driven dialogue to allow users to access and "use" objects in the environment, manipulating and changing the information attached to the object.

<P>Xing Technology Corporation recently announced the introduction of real-time television transmission over the Web. Its product, StreamWorks, will enable real-time radio networks, and soon thereafter, television networks over the Internet.

<P>Although interesting in themselves, these new products are more interesting because they confirm the advent of the all-digital multimedia communications world, the convergence of every existing analog medium over a digital network, accessible to individuals through their own computers. These emerging digital tools will be more powerful because they bring interactivity at every level, between individuals, among members of groups and with information itself. They also provide the means for individuals to analyze, manipulate, revise and redistribute information.

<P>These new delivery capabilities, and many more innovative ones, will continue to appear faster than we can imagine them. Although the commercial and entertainment industries usually drive the creation of these tools, most of them have basic utility for educational purposes. The challenge for educators interested in using the Web and the Internet for instructional delivery is not so much in creating these tools, but in understanding the functionality, the technical requirements for implementation and support, and the pedagogical advantages and disadvantages of the tools. This is especially true when new technologies are announced every day, each heralding new possibilities that we must analyze and assimilate into the existing repertoire.

<H3><A NAME="inter">Interaction Management Tools</A></H3>

<P>The Web itself does not provide sufficient ways for individuals and groups to interact among themselves. There are a few tools such as <A HREF="http://webnotes.ostech.com/">WebNotes</A>, Ubique’s <A HREF="http://www.vplaces.com/index2.htm">Virtual Places</A> and the aforementioned World Chat that provide relative degrees of interactivity. But they still do not support either the quantity or quality of interaction among students and teachers that is requisite for quality education. To solve this problem, many teachers have turned to Internet tools such as email, news groups and listserves to address the need for student interactivity. These tools can be helpful in many situations, but they are not inherently tailored to the demands of teaching. Teaching a course over the network via these basic Internet tools requires a lot of "overhead" for the teacher. He or she has to do background work to separate all the students' comments and arrange them according to the threads (topics) of discussion instead of the chronological and time-stamped order in which email and listserves typically handle comments. Otherwise, the multiple discussions may be too difficult to follow. Student comments also will not be appropriately referenced to the topic or individual respondent which the student is addressing.  

<P>Increasingly faculty are turning to specialized software which incorporates these features into a self-standing environment which can operate over the Internet or dial-up lines. To paraphrase Varrki George's comment during our visit to the SCALE center at UIUC: "The Web provides the means for delivering information; computer conferencing provides the means for student interaction." George uses computer conferencing software, along with Web-based communications tools, to teach his Urban Planning courses on campus. Other faculty in the ALN projects, as well as at other sites across the country, are using computer conferencing applications such as Lotus Notes, First Class, PacerFORUM, to deliver instruction on campus and/or off campus. These applications typically offer means for information delivery, interaction and archiving the information and interactions. They also address some security issues for the user and network. However, they do not address all the requirements for course management, especially when these applications are mixed with other Web or Internet applications.

<H3><A NAME="course">Course Management Tools</A></H3>

<P>Since the creation of communications tools is generally driven by industries other than education, course management tools are not available on the Internet; there is currently not a commercial market sufficient to justify their creation by the private sector. As mentioned above, there is a plethora of means for delivering content, but credit-bearing instruction requires more than individual access to content and interaction. It requires standards-based means to author and develop materials, and secure means to register, counsel and support students, as well as to assess their work. Issues of network security include authentication of the user (student input), confidentiality and integrity of the student’s work product. If the educational community cannot adequately address these issues, then the Web and its associated delivery tools will be limited to recreational learning and "edutainment”"

<H3><A NAME="net">Networks</A></H3>

<P>To this point we (the ALN and PDL communities) have discussed network access from the perspective of the Internet and dial-up lines into a server for a particular application such as computer conferencing. We should widen the scope of our investigations to examine the commercial online services and network providers. Online services such as America Online have established themselves as viable network services. Recent mergers, acquisitions and competitive entries in the industry indicate that the viability of these services has been accepted. New players such as Microsoft Network and the regional Bell services bring with them new technologies for development, delivery and interaction as well as the means to bundle applications with access. And, of course, they also provide entry to the Internet. Perhaps the most salient aspect of online services for education is that they are targeted to the home market. If access from the home is provided at a "reasonable" rate it could open up the market of home-based learners for education. Reaching these learners is presently problematic because network access and the availability of simple interfaces and software for instructional delivery is limited.

<P>However, online services operate differently from the Internet in several ways. The most obvious difference is that online services are commercial and that they offer a turnkey solution to users. They bundle access, interface, applications and content in one package. This is convenient for the user, but presents different obstacles to institutions wanting to use online services for the delivery of instruction. The financial plan must include payment to the service provider as well as the cost of content development which utilizes or is compatible with the online company’s own authoring environment. Similarly to the Internet, there are currently no means for handling course management. The point here is not that this type of network access is better or worse, but that it is different. It has some interesting potential advantages, but it also entails different requirements to utilize it. The final and primary point is that this type of network should not be ignored by education. We should analyze the possible benefits, the requirements for participating and the gaps in functionality within these services. They provide a resource for extending distributed learning environments to the home and we in the educational community need to understand this potential.

<H3><A NAME="meaning">Creating Meaning from the Asynchronous Learning Experience</A></H3>

<P>The IAT and the Sloan Foundation ALN participants are nationally positioned to explore the issues inherent in providing distributed instruction. By using the term "distributed instruction," we differentiate between the requirements for delivering content for casual learning and the more rigorous requirements for delivering credit-based degree programs. Within the combined collective of the Sloan Foundation's ALN project institutions and the IAT’s partnership institutions, we have a motivated, self-initiating group of faculty who are enthusiastic about exploring distributed and asynchronous solutions to their own and their institutions' instructional challenges. These faculty are dedicated to the quality of their teaching and their students' learning.  

<P>In order to make their experience meaningful to the broader educational community, we need to compare previous efforts to use asynchronous technology for teaching and learning, to develop case studies, and to understand and define the requirements for assessing student performance in asynchronous learning environments. Finally, from this combination of analyzing previous efforts and prototypes of new distributed learning environments which utilize an array of network-based technologies, we need to distill the functional capabilities necessary to provide distributed instruction. The basic modules of functionality will need to be delineated within and among the areas of content development, content delivery, interaction management, assessment and course management.  

<P>The Sloan Foundation had the foresight to seed ALN projects on many campuses. Its leadership in promoting the advantages of asynchronous technologies for education has provided the means to explore key issues challenging educational institutions today. But without the means to track these projects from planning through assessment, much of that information could be lost or obscured. The projects need to be studied both individually and collectively to determine what their experience means: What have we learned? What makes the use of these technologies viable, scaleable, replicable? What are the challenges and benefits from using them on campus and off campus? How can we use them to create new learning opportunities for students not currently in the educational market - those who cannot participate in classroom and campus-based instruction? To reap the full benefits of the Sloan Foundation grants requires a systematic effort to assist, analyze and evaluate the project outcomes. The IAT can do this. 

<H3><A NAME="iat">IAT's Leadership Experience</A></H3>

<P>Because of its national scope and particular focus on distributed instruction, the IAT provides a logical forum for the exchange and analysis of distributed instruction outcomes, as well as a fulcrum for leveraging the individual inquiries of many institutions beyond the scope of their own efforts. The IAT can collect the data from these various projects, and analyze and aggregate them. From this broad experiential base, the IAT can then devote the efforts of its faculty and staff to evaluate the work to date and further refine the functional requirements for distributed instruction.

<P>Unlike most educational institutions, the IAT has faculty and staff whose time is completely dedicated to researching and analyzing both the pedagogical and the technological aspects of distributed learning environments. Functioning as an "applied think tank," we focus on the strategic use of information technology to address critical issues in instruction and education. In the past we have demonstrated how existing multimedia development tools can be enhanced to provide different capabilities which ease the challenges of authoring while simultaneously creating more learner-centered applications. In particular, the prototyping of tools such as <A HREF="../../technology/software/express/index.html">Express Author</A> and <A HREF="../../technology/software/mathkit/index.html">MathKit</A> exemplifies what we learned from the process of analyzing the technological and pedagogical requirements for using multimedia tools to develop course content. To address the inadequacies of the Web for providing access to sophisticated multimedia courseware, we developed <A HREF="../../technology/software/webapp/index.html">WebApp</A> to automatically download and install these applications to a student’s computer. We have not pursued developing these prototypes from a desire to develop marketable products, but as a learning experience and as a means to prove and demonstrate our concepts. In this regard we are not only analysts and reflective learners, but also "hands-on" learners.

<P>For the past two years we have turned our focus from networked multimedia applications to the broader topic of distributed learning environments and the instructional and technological systems which enable them. In keeping with our national mission, we have initiated efforts to influence the national dialogue within the educational community concerning the issues of quality, cost and access. We feel that our ability to address these issues is strategically tied to our understanding and deployment of distributed technologies and learning environments. In particular, many of the asynchronous technologies provide new strategies for dealing with quality, access and cost.

<H3>New Joint National Learning Infrastructure Inititative</H3>
<P>One example of the IAT’s contribution to the national dialogue is its seminal role and continuing leadership in EDUCOM's NLII. As an example, the IAT recently brought together the principals from three other NLII projects to explore leveraging their individual efforts into a collaborative one to define functional modules for course management in a distributed environment. Representatives from the NLII projects at the University of Michigan, Miami-Dade Community College and California State University met with the IAT representatives to review their individual project goals and determine any common goals. After reviewing Miami-Dade's LAN-based Project Synergy Integrator (PSI), the group decided to form a technical task force immediately to investigate re-purposing some of the PSI code to develop a course management platform. The second stage of work will leverage the University of Michigan's plan to create an object-oriented system for developing application modules ("applets") with which faculty can construct their courses.

<H3><A NAME="conc">Conclusion</A></H3>

<P>Through this report we have illustrated the kind of supportive and synergistic function the IAT can provide to the Sloan Foundation's ALN project participants. We are continuing to meet members of this community and discuss their interests and goals. Through our ongoing participation with ALN faculty and projects we hope to deepen our own understanding of distributed learning and provide reciprocal value to the ALN community as well. Through our outreach services such as satellite-delivered programs, workshops and electronic media we can share the ALN experience with the larger educational community. By these means we can bring the collective experience of the ALN community to bear in the national dialogue on the strategic use of information technology in education.
<P>

<BR>
