<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>PDL</FONT>: Summary of the Meeting of October 16-17, 1995 </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>



<P>The Partnership for Distributed Learning, (PDL) held its first
business meeting at the Institute for Academic Technology on
October 16 and 17, 1995. A <A HREF="partrfp.html">Request for Partners</A> was issued by
the IAT at the January 1995 NLII meeting in New Orleans, and the
Partnership was organized in subsequent meetings in March and
June 1995. This meeting initiated the PDL as a national
consortium for research and development of Web-based tools for
distributed education.

<P>The following institutions and organizations attended the
inaugural meeting:

<UL>
<LI>California State University/California Polytechnic State University - San Luis Obispo
<LI>Florida Community College at Jacksonville
<LI>Indiana University
<LI>Kent State University
<LI>Montgomery County Community College
<LI>Prentice-Hall/Simon & Schuster
<LI>San Mateo Community College District
<LI>Sinclair Community College
<LI>University of Colorado at Boulder
<LI>University of North Carolina - Chapel Hill/Institute for Academic Technology
<LI>University of Pittsburgh
<LI>Utah State University
<LI>Virginia Commonwealth University
</UL>

<P>Based on agreements worked out in the organizing meetings,
general business meetings of the Partnership are to have three
foci: 1) information about distributed education best practices,
state-of-the-art and next-generation innovations;  2) project
planning and management; and  3) PDL business affairs. This meeting was organized accordingly.

<H3>Information</H3>  

<P>Steve Griffin of the IAT presented an overview of the NLII
meta-consortium to develop standards for distributed course
management (DCMS). The genesis of this meta-project is the
exemplary <A HREF="http://www.mdcc.edu/synergy/psi.html">Project Synergy Integrator</A> (PSI) system developed by
Miami-Dade Community College, and its goal is to componentize
and scale the best features of MDCC's LAN-based system to the
Internet. The meta-consortium consists of MDCC, UNC-CH,
California State University, and the University of Michigan. The outcome of a meeting of technical representatives from these
institutions was a system definition providing for learning and
instructional flexibility, asynchronous use, support for legacy
courseware, mixed vendor compatibility, and compatibility with
emerging Internet standards for commerce and authentication. The Partners agreed that advanced knowledge of this long-term
project was extremely valuable and that, while it should not
postpone development of interim distributed course management
solutions, these solutions must adhere to the standards and
architecture evolving from the meta-project.  

<P>Best practice and state-of-the-art demonstrations were 
provided by:
<UL>
<LI>Virginia Commonwealth University: <A HREF="http://www.vcu.edu/mdcweb/demo.html">Web-based course delivery of
English, German, and health administration courses</A>.  
<LI>Kent State University: Multimedia Distributed Learning
Initiative incorporating live and taped video, sound, graphics,
and text.
<LI>California Polytechnic State University - San Luis Obispo:
multimedia applications.  
</UL>

<P>A next-generation technologies demonstration was provided by the
IAT showing Java applications, three-dimensional chat
conferencing, and streaming video and audio. This demonstration
included a discussion of Sun's Java and the new features
incorporated into Netscape Navigator 2.0, Navigator 2.0 Gold,
Live Wire, and several other Netscape products. The
implications for standards-based distributed instruction were of
interest to all.

<H3>Projects</H3>

<H4>Projects were proposed by:</H4> 
<OL>
<P><B>Indiana University . . .</B>
<P><LI>Development of modules and tools to improve students'
mathematical thinking and reasoning and to improve problem
solving ability. While intended primarily for preparing
elementary teachers, the modules and tools will be appropriate
for the general developmental math curriculum.
<LI>Development of Web-based interactive tools for mathematics
across the curriculum.

<P><B>Virginia Commonwealth University . . .</B>
<P><LI>Instructional Web: A Server in a Box - Cross-platform
software permitting instructors easily to set up courses
on-line, deliver content, control user access, and handle course
administration functions.
<LI>Web Presentation Software - A toolkit to permit live full
media instructional presentations on the Web.

<P><B>Institute for Academic Technology . . .</B>
<P><LI>Development of JAVA-based mathematical graphing applets.
</OL>

<H4>Decisions on the proposals:</H4>

<P>The Partners agreed to begin work immediately on 3 of the 5
proposals, designated below as Projects 1, 2, and 3. The
initial phase of each of these projects will include defining
specific outcomes and developing work and business plans. Indications of Partner interest in participating in projects are
preliminary and identify, primarily, those that wish to be
involved in this first phase. Final decisions to participate in
a project will be based on the work and business plans. The
Partners also agreed to undertake a fourth, longer term, project
that would be built on the results of Projects 2 and 3.

<P><B>Project 1</B> - Proposal 3 (VCU) : Immediate priority as an interim solution
building toward the DCMS. Estimated time to complete: 6-8
months from start. VCU will take the lead. IAT will seek      
 third-party funding. Preliminary Partner interest: Technical: Colorado, Prentice-Hall, UNC/IAT, Utah State and Kent State. Instructional design/functionality: Montgomery County CC, Pittsburgh, San Mateo, UNC/IAT, Sinclair CC, Florida CC at Jacksonville and Cal Poly.

<P><B>Project 2</B> - Proposal 1 (Indiana): Immediate priority. Indiana will take the
lead and work with IAT to prototype content in MathKit. Preliminary Partner interest: Content: IAT, Montgomery County
CC, Pittsburgh, Prentice-Hall, and possibly Colorado.

<P><B>Project 3</B> - Proposal 5 (IAT): Immediate priority. IAT will take the lead
and work with Indiana and other Project 2 institutions on
content. Develop prototype modules for 2D and 3D graphing and
maybe 1-2 additional prototype modules in JAVA. Develop plan
for making MathKit JAVA-based and for porting initial Project 2
modules to JAVA. Preliminary Partner interest: Colorado,
Pittsburgh, Prentice-Hall, and possibly Indiana. 

<P><B>Project 4</B> - Based on the outcomes of Project 2 and 3, build JAVA-based
MathKit and JAVA-based MathKit modules (content identified in
Project 2). IAT will take the lead. Estimated time to
complete: 1 year. Major funding will be required; those
contributing to cost will share license; third-party funding
will also be sought.   

<P>Proposal 2 (Indiana): Tabled by Indiana pending outcomes of
Projects 2, 3, and 4. 

<P>Proposal 4 (VCU): Based on the demonstrations of next-generation
Web streaming tools, VCU withdrew the original proposal and
suggested, instead, that the Partners consider developing the
means for CD-ROM access from within the Web -- i.e., making it
possible to launch CD-ROM based materials from Web-based
instruction and learning environments. Steve Griffin and Bill
Pet of the IAT developed and demonstrated a prototype during the
meeting.  

<H3>PDL Business</H3>

The membership fee has three purposes. First, it is intended to
ensure commitment to the work of the Partnership and to
encourage each member to be an active participant. Second, it
is to provide for the management of the Partnership, meetings
and coordination of projects. Third, these funds will be used
to leverage additional funds.  

<P>Some projects will require additional financial investment,
although others may be accomplished through in-kind
contributions, such as content or programming. Most will
probably require both. When a project is proposed, Partners
will indicate their interest. The proposing institution will
convene the interested parties to develop work and business
plans. If necessary, these plans will be brought back to the
full Partnership for additional consideration. It was agreed
that all proposals deserve a chance to advance, but a process
must be in place to establish priorities and even to winnow out
some ideas. Issues such as ownership of content and royalties
will be worked out in the business plan. Institutions that
elect not to invest in a particular project cannot benefit from
its revenues, if any, but all Partners may receive some
benefits, such as beta products.  

<P>The Partners agreed that, besides providing capacity to leverage
individual institutional resources for larger and more rapid
research and development, the PDL has added value in
centralizing consortium management, project coordination,
analysis and evaluation, and information dissemination. As
Robert Pack said, institutionally we must have a base from which
to make choices and "this enterprise is a lot cheaper than
hiring the expertise to go it alone."    

<P>There was some discussion of increasing membership, with a
consensus that about 25 partners would probably provide a good
mix of institutions and organizations without diminishing the
value of each member's seat at the table. Greater
representation of the commercial sector is needed, particularly
from the telecommunications and software industries. There was
also agreement that close articulation with the ALN projects
funded by the Sloan Foundation would be valuable.

<P>The Partners agreed to hold 2-3 full membership meetings a year,
in addition to project-specific meetings. The next general
meeting will be held approximately one month after the January
NLII meeting. However, meetings of the project groups will be
held in conjunction with the NLII in New Orleans on January 21. Members felt that the NLII sessions should be used to
familiarize others with the work of the PDL and to familiarize
ourselves with what others are doing.
<P><HR>
Lowell H. Roberts
<BR>Research Fellow
<BR>Institute for Academic Technology
<BR>University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill
<BR>Email: <A HREF="mailto:lowell_roberts@unc.edu">lowell_roberts@ unc.edu</A>
<BR>Voice: 919 405 1928  Fax: 919 560 5047
<P>


