<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>PDL P</FONT>rogress <FONT SIZE=+3>R</FONT>eport to the Educom NLII, January 1996</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<P><B>Sponsor:</B> Institute for Academic Technology, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill

<P>The Partnership for Distributed Learning (PDL)  held its first business meeting at the Institute for Academic Technology on October 16 and 17, 1995.  A Request for Partners was issued by the IAT at the January 1995 National Learning Infrastructure Initiative (NLII) meeting in New Orleans, and the Partnership was organized in subsequent  meetings in March and June 1995.  The October meeting initiated the PDL as a national consortium for research and development of tools for distributed learning environments.

<P><DT>Charter members of the Partnership for Distributed Learning:
	<DD>California State University/California Polytechnic State University - San Luis Obispo
	<DD>Florida Community College at Jacksonville
	<DD>IBM Higher Education
	<DD>Indiana University
	<DD>Kent State University
	<DD>Montgomery County Community College
	<DD>Prentice-Hall/Simon & Schuster
	<DD>San Mateo Community College District
	<DD>Sinclair Community College
	<DD>University of North Carolina - Chapel Hill/Institute for Academic Technology
	<DD>University of Pittsburgh
	<DD>Utah State University
	<DD>Virginia Commonwealth University

<P>The PDL is a leveraging organization through which the members extend their individual capacities to develop and implement distributed learning environments.  Partners get smart together by sharing information about best practices, state-of-the-art applications, and next generation innovations; share risk (and reward) in advancing distributed learning technologies through PDL-managed joint-venture projects; and mutually finance projects through in-kind resourcing and leveraged third-party funding.  PDL members pay an annual membership fee of $5000, the purpose of which is to encourage each Partner to be an active and committed member; fund PDL management, meetings and project coordination; and leverage additional funds.  

<P>Currently, the PDL has two projects underway.  One led by Indiana University will result in the development of modules and tools to improve students' mathematical thinking, reasoning and problem-solving ability.  While intended primarily for preparing elementary teachers, the modules and tools will be appropriate for the general developmental math curriculum.  The second project, Web Course in a Box, is led by Virginia Commonwealth University and will result in cross-platform software permitting instructors easily to set up courses on-line, deliver content, control user access, and handle course administration functions.  Two long-range projects are in the conceptual stage: Web-based interactive mathematics modules and tools and a platform-independent distributed course management system.

<P>The next business meeting of the Partnership will be February 19-20, 1996.
<P>

<BR>
