<H3><A NAME="attend">Attendees</A></H3>
<P><H4>Representatives of the following Partner institutions and
organizations:</H4>

<UL>
<LI>California Polytechnic State University/CSU
<LI>Florida Community College at Jacksonville
<LI>Indiana University
<LI>Kent State University
<LI>Montgomery County Community College
<LI>Simon and Schuster/Prentice Hall
<LI>Sinclair Community College
<LI>University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill/IAT
<LI>University of Pittsburgh
<LI>Utah State University
<LI>Virginia Commonwealth University
</UL>

<H4>Representatives of the following guest institutions and
organizations:</H4>

<UL>
<LI>Acadia University
<LI>Addison Wesley Longman
<LI>Lotus Institute
<LI>Mathematics Association of America
<LI>Sam Houston State University
<LI>University of Alberta
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="wcbu">Update on Existing Projects</A></H3>

<H4>Web Course in a Box (Virginia Commonwealth University)</H4>

<P>Robert Godwin-Jones demonstrated the Web Course in a Box
prototype-in-development. The WCB prototype includes templates
for: 1) setting preferences; 2) course home pages; 3) Message Box for student interactivity (e.g., discussions); 4) class lists; 5) student home pages; and 6)
faculty home pages. The prototype can be accessed at
<A HREF="http://www.mmd.vcu.edu/wcb/wcb.html">http://www.mmd.vcu.edu/wcb/wcb.html</A>.

<P>Lyle Barton (KSU) demonstrated an intelligent quiz software that
Kent State has developed that will serve as a model of the drill
and practice component of WCB.

<P>Godwin-Jones raised two questions about the design of WCB: 1) To
what extent should WCB be specific to Netscape 2.0, which has
desirable features, but may limit universal usability?  2) To
what extent should WCB be modular, thereby permitting faculty to
use and update components, rather than the entire package. The
prototype is not modular, but the Partners agreed that
modularity is preferred. Steve Saltzberg raised the issue of
multimedia. Right now WCB works just with media available via
the Web. The Partners felt that WCB, in this phase at least, is
for faculty just beginning to use the Web for instruction and
learning. Their consensus was to keep WCB as simple as possible
to maximize its utility for faculty; more sophisticated
instructors can write their own html media plug-ins. The PDL
applauded the development team for the WCB's basic structure,
especially its feedback and interactive functions, and the fact
that the design will work for add-ons to classroom instruction
and televised distance learning, as well as Web-based courses.

<P>Steve Saltzberg presented a business plan for Alpha development,
and nine members agreed to put up $1000 each to complete the
Alpha phase and to serve as unsupported Alpha test sites.

<H4><A NAME="mathu">Math Tools for Teachers</A> (Indiana University)</H4>

<P>Gary Wittlich distributed a revised development plan, Web-Based
Modules on Mathematics for Elementary Teachers, prepared by
Gary, Enrique Galindo and Frank Lester. The revised plan
specifies 14 modules and a timeline for development beginning
fall 1996, with testing beginning a year later. Discussion was
deferred to the project meeting.

<H4><A NAME="dcmsu">Distributed Course Management Standards</A></H4>

<P>Steve Griffin (UNC-CH/IAT) updated the PDL on the status of the
Educom initiative to specify a standard for distributed course
management and develop a proof-of-concept prototype system. The
DCMS standard is now essentially defined, following a meeting of
the technical group at the NLII in January. Educom is calling a
meeting of interested technology companies (publishing,
telecommunications, software) to explore a business plan for
developing the prototype. Three proposed approaches are
currently under consideration: 1) Vendors put money into a
general development fund in exchange for a seat at the design
table and universities get compensated for developing the core
code; 2) The vendor development fund compensates universities
for both core code and proof-of-concept prototype; and 3)
Universities develop core code without vendor support--say,
with grant funding--and put it on the market free.

<H3><A NAME="wglm">New Proposal</A></H3>

<H4>Working Group on Learning and Motivation (Florida Community
College at Jacksonville)</H4>

<P>Jack Chambers proposed that PDL members form a working group to
examine academic technology from a pedagogical perspective,
specifically learning and motivation. Areas of potential study
are motivation of lower-level students as their instruction is
off-loaded to technology; appropriate mix of technology and
traditional modalities; how does technology promote good
teaching; what works for whom. The group may use PDL projects
as research testbeds, and its findings will inform future PDL
projects. Representatives of five member institutions agreed to
form the working group.

<H3><A NAME="smart">Getting Smart</A></H3>

<P>A key purpose of the Partnership is to be exposed to and
understand the latest developments in academic technology. Thus, attendees receive demonstrations of and discuss new
applications of technologies by member institutions and
state-of-the-art developments within the academic technology
industry. These demonstrations inform PDL and individual member
activities and projects, provide feedback to developers, and
create a dialog between the academic and commercial sectors that
promotes more useful and scalable products. The Partners thank
the following for their presentations:

<UL><LI>Anna Seu and Tom Fowler (Cal Poly): Shockwave animations and a
Web Chat learning and instruction environment that permits
discussion, collaboration, links to fixed media, and the
capacity for students to create portfolios that can be evaluated
by off-campus experts. URL: <A HREF="http://www.fmdc.calpoly.edu">http://www.fmdc.calpoly.edu</A>

<LI>Susan L'Heureux (Sinclair CC): Question Mark, a testing and
surveying system that can be used via the Web or stand-alone,
that Sinclair is currently implementing. URL:
<A HREF="http://www.qmark.com">http://www.qmark.com</A>

<LI>Marla Capozzi (Lotus Institute): Lotus Notes 4.0 and the Lotus
Institute's prototype Distributed Learning Network for
instruction and training. URL: <A HREF="http://www.lotus.com">http://www.lotus.com</A>

<LI>Tim Spaid (Addison Wesley Longman): Hybrid CD-ROM/Web learning
materials for physics, geology (virtual reality field trips) and
calculus. URL: <A HREF="http://www.aw.com">http://www.aw.com</A>

<LI>Kevin Johnson (Simon & Schuster): JAVA-based online study guides
in psychology, astronomy, and political science (representative
of eight subjects that will be available fall 1996). URLs: 
<UL>
<LI>Simon & Schuster's Guide to Online Projects<BR><A HREF="http://www.prenhall.com/pubguide/">http://www.prenhall.com/pubguide/</A>
<LI>Chaisson - Astronomy
<BR><A HREF="http://www.prenhall.com/~chaisson">http://www.prenhall.com/~chaisson</A>
<LI>Morris - Psychology
<BR><A HREF="http://www.prenhall.com/~morris">http://www.prenhall.com/~morris</A>   
<LI>McKnight - Physical Geography
<BR><A HREF="http://www.prenhall.com/~mcknight">http://www.prenhall.com/~mcknight</A> 
<LI>Audesirk - Life On Earth - Biology
<BR><A HREF="http://www.prenhall.com/~audesirk">http://www.prenhal.com/~audesirk</A>   
<LI>Laudon - Management Information Systems
<BR><A HREF="http://www.prenhall.com/~laudon">http://www.prenhall.com/~laudon</A>    
<LI>Carter - Keys to Success
<BR><A HREF="http://www.prenhall.com/~success">http://www.prenhall.com/~success</A>
<LI>Berman - Approaching Democracy - American Government
<BR><A HREF="http://www.moby.ucdavis.edu/ApproachingDemocracy/">http://www.moby.ucdavis.edu/ApproachingDemocracy/</A>
</UL></UL>

<P>Much of the discussion that followed the Addison Wesley Longman
and Simon & Schuster demonstrations focused on the business
models for developing and distributing products such as those
shown. Concerns such as return-on-investment, traffic to linked
Web sites, billing models, institutional support costs, and
local customization were raised. As a result of this
discussion, Kevin Johnson agreed to convene a working group on
business models, and all member institutions indicated they
would join. Initially, Simon & Schuster will propose models for
PDL reaction via the Partners List. The List discussions,
moderated by Kevin, will inform face-to-face discussions at PDL
meetings. Kevin and Bill Graves, convener of the Economics of
Electronic Publishing RFP group of the NLII, will coordinate the
work of the two groups.

<H3><A NAME="wcbr">Reports of the Project and Working Group Meetings</A></H3>

<H4>Web Course in a Box</H4>

<P>The WCB project meeting included eighteen people representing a
dozen institutions or businesses.  The meeting focused on two
topics: an implementation strategy and a business plan.

<P>I. Implementation Strategy

<P>The development partners (VCU and Kent State) agreed to develop
an "alpha" version of the WCB by June 1 so that our design
partners can deploy and evaluate the product during the summer
(several institutions wanted to use this as part of faculty
development efforts this summer). The alpha release will
contain the following elements:

<OL>
<LI>Class web pages (create and edit)
<LI>Faculty web pages (create and edit)
<LI>Student web pages (create and edit)
<LI>Asynchronous Discussion Group
<LI>Account ID/password access restriction
<LI>Syllabus
</OL>

<P>We will attempt to add the ability to create pointers to
instructional content and an online evaluation of the WCB
process.

<P>Ten institutions, aside from Kent State and VCU, made an initial
agreement to be a test site for the WCB alpha version, and
indicated a willingness to pay the development partners to be an
early test site. Several institutions need to get final
budgetary approval. The preliminary list of
test sites include IAT, Sinclair CC, University of Pittsburgh,
Acadia University, University of Alberta, UNC Chapel Hill, Utah
State, Cal Poly, and Prentice Hall.

<P>II. Business Plan

<P>The discussion centered around defining the copyright and
ownership issues for the WCB software and the equity of the
development and design partners. The business plan also needs to
address the "life of the project" and identify possible funding
strategies if the WCB is to become more than a prototype. Other
business plan issues were commercialization of project,
bring product to market in a rapidly changing environment, role
of publishers, market analysis, and resale options. Kent State
will make a first run at this business plan. (Steve Saltzberg)

<H4><A NAME="mathr">Math Tools for Teachers</A></H4>

<P>On Monday, Feb. 19, a group of persons interested in the math
project met to discuss how the partners might proceed. Attending
were Ladnor Geissinger and Jurgen Sladeczek (IAT), Jeff Cepull
(Pitt), Milt Petruk (U Alberta), Geneva Taylor (Sam Houston SU),
and Gary Wittlich (IU). Also expressing interest but not in
attendance was John Mastroni (Montgomery CC). 

<P>Enrique Galindo responded from Bloomington via telephone to
questions raised about the project description distributed at
the meeting. Of particular concern were which modules to focus
on and especially which tools to try to develop among those
Enrique listed in the proposal (2-D graphing, scientific
calculator, table generator, math notation editor, and a white
board to support both synchronous and asynchronous student
collaboration). Milt Petruk raised the question of whether it
might be better to distribute the tools by CD than to try to
integrate them with a web browser. (Milt later demonstrated
visual graphing tools developed at the University of Alberta and
available for campus license). The group also discussed problems
of porting MathWright tools to Java vs. creating the tools anew.
It was decided that if web integration remains the goal for the
tools, then creating them anew for the project is probably
advisable due to the complexities involved in a port.

<P>No conclusions were reached at the meeting about starting points
for tool development. Gary Wittlich will distribute materials
pertinent to two of the modules to members who have not seen
them. In the meantime, Ladnor will contact Maple developers to
determine whether it might be 
possible to license or otherwise use some of the Maple tools in
the project. Gary has created a majordomo list for the math
group and will use it to discuss project details, including the
possibility of submitting a partnership grant proposal to NSF to
support development of the tools. 

<P>Given that the modules for T104 were developed originally under
NSF support, and given the breadth of the partnership, some of
the members think that a proposal to support at least the
development of some prototype tools might be favorably viewed by
NSF, or perhaps by FIPSE. (Gary Wittlich)

<H4><A NAME="wglmr">Working Group on Learning and Motivation</A></H4>

<P>The following persons attended the meeting:

<UL>
<LI>Jack Chambers, Fl CC at Jacksonville (co-Chair)
<LI>John Mastroni, Montgomery Co. CC (co-Chair)
<LI>Byron Burnham, Utah State University
<LI>Katy Neff, Sinclair CC
<LI>Lowell Roberts, IAT
</UL>

<P>The group brainstormed on the overall problems concerned with
the application of research findings in the areas of learning
and motivation to higher education distributed learning.
Agreement was reached to attempt to identify the groups most
concerned, the most relevant research in the areas, and suggest
"best and worst" practices in applying research findings to
higher education distributed learning. Unanimous agreement was
reached that current practices
in higher education classrooms would not be used as a model
unless they conformed to research findings in learning and
motivation. Finally, it was agreed to develop a white paper on
the topic for distribution to the Partnership and elsewhere.

<P>The first step was taken, in identifying the most relevant
concerned groups. They were identified as faculty, students,
administration, professional staff, Boards of Trustees,
accreditation agencies, professional associations, and last but
not least, textbook and software publishers.

<P>These discussions will continue via a Work Group Bulletin Board. (Jack Chambers)

<H3><A NAME="meeting">Upcoming Meetings</A></H3>
The next meeting of the Partnership for Distributed Learning
will be July 15-16, 1996. 
<P><B>Questions?</B> Contact <A HREF="mailto:lowell_roberts@unc.edu">Lowell Roberts</A>.
<P>

