<HEAD>
<TITLE>Educom 1995 - Networked Multimedia Update </TITLE>
<!-- Created: November 1995 by Steve Griffin, IAT-->
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME="page1">
</A>
<FONT SIZE=+3 ><STRONG><CENTER>3rd Annual Networked Multimedia Update</CENTER></STRONG></FONT>
<FONT SIZE=+2><P>
<CENTER>Steve Griffin</FONT><BR>Director of Technical Services<BR>Institute for Academic Technology
<BR><A HREF="mailto:steve_griffin@unc.edu">steve_griffin@unc.edu</A><P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="#David">David Luttrell</A></FONT><BR>Mgr. Network Integration Services<BR>Institute for Academic Technology<BR><A HREF="mailto:david_luttrell@unc.edu">david_luttrell@unc.edu</A><P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><A HREF="#Jim">Jim Gogan</A></FONT><BR>Dir. Networking Systems<BR>University of North Carolina<BR><A HREF="mailto:jim_gogan@unc.edu">jim_gogan@unc.edu</A><P>
</FONT></CENTER>
<HR>
This information was first presented at Educom 1995 in Portland, Oregon on November 2nd.  This presentation is located at http://www.iat.unc.edu/technote/teknote7.html
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER>Program</CENTER></STRONG>

<UL>
<STRONG><LH>Overview (Griffin)</LH></STRONG>
<LI>Opportunities
<LI>Challenges
<LI>Terms
</UL>
<UL>
<LH><STRONG>Local Area Network (Dept.) Challenges & Solutions (<A HREF="#David">Luttrell</A>)</LH></STRONG>
<LI>Limitations of Current Networks
<LI>New Networking Standards
<LI>Future Standards
<LI>Strategies/Solutions </FONT>
</UL>


<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<UL>
<LH><STRONG>Campus/Wide Area/Internet Challenges & Solutions (<A HREF="#Jim">Gogan</A>)</LH></STRONG>
<LI>Scalability Issues
<LI>ATM Networking Update
<LI>Other Alternatives
<LI>Demonstrations
</UL>
</FONT>
<UL>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<LH><STRONG>Questions and Answers (15 min.)</LH></STRONG><P>
<LH><STRONG>Plus, the URL to this presentation and associated links</LH></STRONG>
</UL>
</FONT>
<HR>

<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER>Overview</CENTER></STRONG>
<UL>
<STRONG><LH>What we are talking about?</LH></STRONG>
<LI>color video that contains audio
<LI>accessing video across the same computer network that we send and retrieve data
<LI>video that can be stored on and accessed from a computer mass storage device
</UL>


<UL>
<STRONG><LH>What we are not talking about?</LH></STRONG>
<LI>extremely slow and jerky B&W video
<LI>dedicated video networks (distance education)
<LI>always live video
</UL>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=+2 >
<UL>
<STRONG><LH>Why?</LH></STRONG>
<LI>Video brings compelling content to the TV generation
<LI>Technology must scale so that access to education increases and costs are controlled
<LI>Stored data enables asynchronous learning
</UL>


<UL>
<STRONG><LH>Who's already doing it in Higher Education?</LH></STRONG>
<LI>
<LI>Kent State, RPI, Indiana, Utah State, Univ. of Utah, Cal Poly, Stanford, NYU, Hudson Valley Community College
</UL>
<UL>
<STRONG><LH>Who will be doing it?</LH></STRONG>
<LI>Microsoft - 1997, first ATM-based network roll-out
<LI>AT&T, your local cable and telephone companies
</UL>
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER>Challenges</CENTER></STRONG></FONT>
<FONT SIZE=+2><BR><BR>
<EM><STRONG><CENTER>Storage<P>
Access<P>
Transmission<P>
Local Display<P>
Copyright</CENTER></STRONG></EM>
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER>Storage and Transmission Challenges</CENTER></STRONG>
<BR><BR>
<A HREF="tek7fig1.jpg"><IMG SRC="tek7fig1.gif"></A>
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER>Video Servers</CENTER></STRONG>


<UL>
<LH><STRONG>Supports 40 or Less Workstations</STRONG></LH>
<LI><A HREF="http://webster.ibmlink.ibm.com/pcdirect/p96f8520.htm">IBM Lan Server Ultimedia</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.starlight.com/">Startlight Networks</A> - Starware, Starworks
<LI>Novell -<A HREF="http://corp.novell.com/bg/english/bg000024.htm"> Video 1.0</A><BR>
<LH><STRONG>Supports More than 40 Workstations</STRONG></LH>
<LI>The Network Connection - M2V
<LI>Oracle - <A HREF="http://www.oracle.com/info/products/newMedia/">Media Server</A>
<LI>Microsoft - Tiger
<LI>First Virtual - Media Server & Switch
<LI>HP - <A HREF="http://hpcc998.external.hp.com:80/pressrel/13nov95b.html">Video Server</A>
<LI>Sun - <A HREF="http://www.Sun.COM/cgi-bin/show?951001/isg_press1.html">MediaCenter</A>
</UL>
</FONT>

<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER>Terms</CENTER></STRONG>

<P>
<DL>
<LH></LH>
<DT><STRONG>ATM</STRONG><DD>Asynchronous Transfer Mode is a data networking standard adopted
by telephone and computer networking companies internationally.
 ATM has many advantages with respect to transporting digital
video.  It can support a variety of connection speeds.  It can
provide a dedicated amount of bandwidth between network devices,
and it introduces only small amounts of delay across network switching
devices.<P>
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<DT><STRONG>AVI File</STRONG><DD>A video file format defined by Microsoft.  It can contain
digital video in an uncompressed format or in one of many compressed
formats.<P>
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<DT><STRONG>Bandwidth</STRONG><DD>Bandwidth from a general data perspective is the maximum
number of bits per second that can be reliably transmitted at
any given time between two devices.  The devices could be connected
via a network or could be in the same machine as is the case of
a CD-ROM drive and a computer's processor.  <BR>
<BR>
From a digital video perspective, bandwidth is often referred
to as the minimum number of bits per second required during playback
such that no video or audio is lost.  In general, the higher the
bandwidth of a digital video file, the higher the perceived quality
of the video when it is played back.<BR>
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
However, people who create
digital video files must often sacrifice video quality by compressing
the video in order to achieve a bandwidth low enough that it can
be supported by the delivery device, such as a CD-ROM drive.<P>
<DT><STRONG>CODEC</STRONG><DD>(COmpressor/DECompressor) generally a program that may or
may not interface with specialized video hardware to compress and
playback digital video in a particular digital video format. 
Common digital video formats are MPEG, INDEO, Quicktime, and CINEPAK.<P>

</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<DT><STRONG>Compression</STRONG><DD>When video is converted into a digital format, it
consumes large amounts of space - too large for most storage and
delivery devices.  Therefore, the raw digital data is reduced
(compressed) by various techniques including eliminating redundant
information in the video such as unchanging background images,
reducing the number of frames, or reducing the resolution.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Decoder</STRONG><DD>Digital video decoders convert digital video data back
into moving video and audio on the computer screen.  Decoders
can be hardware or software-based. 
</FONT>
<HR><FONT SIZE=+2>
Software decoders can be differentiated
by their scalability, or in other words their ability to provide
an optimized playback quality based on the performance capabilities
of the host computer.  Indeo from Intel is one of the better scaleable
decoders.  Software-only MPEG decoders currently do not provide
a great deal of scalability. High end Pentium class computers
are often times fast enough such that a software-only decoder
can display full-screen video at 30 frames per second.  As prices
for MPEG decoder chips fall, one can expect to find them more
frequently as standard elements of computers, as they are now
in IBM's Aptiva line of computers.

</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<DT><STRONG>Delta Frames</STRONG><DD> Visual information that has changed between two points
in time in video.  Delta frames are one technique to compress
digital video by storing only the information that changes.  If
a digital video file contained a segment of someone talking into
the camera, then delta frames might include only the lips and
other facial elements that move during the segment.
<P>

<DT><STRONG>Encoder</STRONG><DD>Encoders convert video from a traditional analog format
used in broadcast TV or output by VCR's etc. into a digital format.
 Encoders always include some hardware element that converts the
analog signal to a digital signal.  
</FONT>
<BR><HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Some encoders, such as the
Intel Smart Video Recorder Pro, also contain specialized hardware
that will compress the digital video at the same time.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Frame Rate</STRONG><DD>The number of times per second that the original video
is sampled and converted into a digital format.  Frequently CD-ROM-based
video is created at 15 frames per second.  Normal TV is displayed
at 30 frames per second and theater movies are filmed at 24 frames
per second.  Digital video frames can be a combination of key
frames and delta frames.
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<DT><STRONG>Jitter</STRONG><DD>The variation in the delay in receiving data across a
network.  
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Key Frames</STRONG><DD>A frame of digital video information that has a complete
representation of the video at the moment in time when the frame
was encoded.  A key frame can be thought of as a snapshot of the
video at a moment in time, whereas a delta frame only stores data
that has changed over time.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Latency</STRONG><DD>The delay in receiving data across a network.
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<DT><STRONG>Quality of Service</STRONG><DD>Generally used in referring to the ability
of some networks, such as ATM, that can guarantee a minimum amount
of dedicated bandwidth from one device to another on a network.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Quicktime</STRONG><DD>Digital video services and digital video programming
interfaces defined by Apple computer and built-in to the Mac operating system.
</FONT>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>
<DT><STRONG>Resolution</STRONG><DD>The number of pixels or dots horizontally and vertically
represented in each frame of digital video.  When video is captured
the resolution can be reduced to decrease the size of the digital
video file.  The lower the resolution, the more detail from the
original video is lost.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Video for Windows</STRONG><DD>Digital video services and digital video programming
interfaces defined by Microsoft and built-in to Windows.
</DL>
</FONT>
<HR><A NAME="David"></A>
<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER><A HREF="tek7lnk1.html">David Luttrell</A></CENTER></STRONG></FONT>
<HR><A NAME="Jim"></A>

<FONT SIZE=+2 ><STRONG><CENTER><A HREF="http://www.unc.edu/~gogan/netmm.html">Jim Gogan</A></CENTER></STRONG></FONT>
