<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>W</FONT>ebApp (32-bit)<FONT SIZE=+3>D</FONT>ownloading and <FONT SIZE=+3>I</FONT>nstallation <FONT SIZE=+3>I</FONT>nstructions </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>


<P>The following instructions tell you how to install the 32-bit
30-day trial version of WebApp. This version runs on Windows 95
and Windows NT. It is fully functional.

<OL>
<LI>WebApp 32-bit version requires either Windows 95 or Windows
NT. It will not work with Win 32s under Windows 3.1.
<LI><A HREF="wanote32.html">Download WebApp</A> (1.1MB). When your browser asks 
you where to save the file "wa32demo.zip", put it in a new empty temporary 
directory (e.g. C:\TEMPDIR\).
<LI>Unzip the file (wa32demo.zip) into the same directory using WinZip or PKUNZIP.EXE.
<LI>Run the self-extracting archive, "wa32demo.exe".
This will place all of the files needed to run the custom setup
program for WebApp on your machine in the temporary directory.
<LI>Before running the extracted "setup.exe", you should
save a bookmark to this page and close your web browser because
the setup program will modify the configuration settings of the browser.
If you close the browser after WebApp makes these changes, then
the changes may be overwritten when the browser closes. 
<LI>Run the "setup.exe" program. This program is the
WebApp custom setup program and will install WebApp on your machine
in a new directory (default C:\WEBAPPS\). After it installs webapp,
then you will see a message indicating if it was successful in
configuring your browser.
<LI>You may now delete the temporary directory you created in
step 2.
<LI>If your browser was configured successfully in step 5, then
you are ready to try out WebApp. If WebApp could not configure
your browser, then you must configure it yourself. Do this by
adding "webapp32.exe" as a helper application (or external
viewer) for the MIME type "application/webapp." This can
be as easy as downloading this sample <A HREF="waxman.wai">chess program</A>
and supplying the location of "webapp32.exe" when prompted
by your browser. See WebApp's on-line help for more information
on how to do this with your web browser.
<LI>Now that you have WebApp installed and your Web browser is
properly configured, you are ready to visit the <A HREF = "wa_arch.html">software archives</A> to begin experiencing the dramatic difference that WebApp can
make in browsing software on the Web.
<LI>Create your own <A HREF="author.html">WebApp archives</A>.
</OL>

