<BR><BR>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>M</FONT>ac<FONT SIZE=+3>W</FONT>eb<FONT SIZE=+3>A</FONT>pp (v1.0)</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<P>
Use the following instructions to install and test MacWebApp.
This is a fully functional version, but will expire 30 days after
installation. Please send any comments to <A HREF="mailto:webapp@unc.edu">webapp@unc.edu</A>.
You must abide by the terms of the <A HREF="lic_info.html">license agreement</A>
when using this software. 
<OL>
<LI>MacWebApp requires that you use 
<UL>
<LI>A system version <I>later</I> than 7.1.1, OR 
<LI>System 7.0 or later with a scriptable version of the Finder
installed (typically Finder version 7.1.3 or later) and the extensions
<I>AppleScript</I> and <I>Finder Scripting Extensions</I> installed.

</UL>

<LI>MacWebApp requires Stuffit Expander to be installed on your
system. If you already have a copy, then skip to step 3. Otherwise,
you can get Stuffit Expander from most Mac software repositories.
Get it from the <A HREF="http://hyperarchive.lcs.mit.edu/HyperArchive/Abstracts/cmp/HyperArchive.html">Info-Mac HyperArchive</A>
or see <A HREF="http://www.apple.com/documents/sharewaresites.html">FTP sites for Apple-related shareware</A>
for other software repositories. 
<LI><A HREF="mwanote.html">Download MacWebApp</A> (212 K). Many
Web browsers, such as Netscape, will automatically extract the
application <I>MacWebApp 1.0 </I>from the file you download. If
your browser does not perform the extraction, use Stuffit Expander
to extract MacWebApp. 
<LI>Configure Netscape to use MacWebApp as a helper application
for MacWebApp archives: 
</OL>

<UL>
<LI>Choose menu item <B>Options | Preferences</B> (or <B>Options
| General Preferences</B> in Netscape 2). 
<LI>Select <B>Helper Applications</B> from the drop-down list
(or the <B>Helpers</B> tab in Netscape 2). 
<LI>Press the <B>New</B> button and enter <I>application</I> for
the Mime type and <I>macwebapp</I> for the Mime subtype. 
<LI>Select <B>Launch Application</B> under <B>Action</B>. 
<LI>Press <B>Browse</B> and select the application MacWebApp.

</UL>

<OL>
<LI>You may also wish to configure Netscape to use MacWebApp for
other Mime types. Use the same procedure as in step 3 except that
instead of pressing the <B>New</B> button, you should scroll the
list of types and select the type that you wish to change. MacWebApp
can be used with the following types and associated extensions:

</OL>

<UL>
<LI>application/x-stuffit sit 
<LI>application/mac-binhex40 hqx 
<LI>application/x-macbinary bin 
</UL>

<OL>
<LI>Try out MacWebApp with the following apps and use it while
browsing the web. 
</OL>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="slime.mwa">slime.mwa</A> (262 K) Arcade-style action
game 
<LI><A HREF="canit.sit.mwa">canit.sit.mwa</A> (59 K) Startup with
a different trashcan icon 
<LI><A HREF="class-record-book.hqx">class-record-book.hqx</A>
(52 K) Keep track of student information 
<LI><A HREF="flea-circus.hqx">flea-circus.hqx</A> (27 K) Watch
fleas attempt circus tricks 
<LI><A HREF="anti-times-tables.hqx">anti-times-tables.hqx</A>
(25 K) Practice multiplication skills 
<LI><A HREF="http://www.apple.com/documents/sharewaresites.html">FTP sites for Apple-related shareware...</A>

</UL>

<OL>
<LI>Create your own <A HREF="create.html">MacWebApp archives</A>.

</OL>

<H2>Documentation</H2>

<P>
<A NAME="documentation">MacWebApp has several settings that you
can change by choosing <B>File | Preferences</B>: </A>
<P>
<B>Choose install folder manually</B> <BR>
When you select this option, MacWebApp will ask you where to put
the program files each time you use MacWebApp to install and run
a program. 
<P>
<B>Always install in Auto-install folder</B> <BR>
When you select this option, MacWebApp puts the program files
or folders into the specified folder automatically. 
<P>
<B>Alias to Apple Menu</B> <BR>
This option directs MacWebApp to place an alias to the program
in the Apple menu. 
<P>
<B>Alias to Desktop</B> <BR>
This option directs MacWebApp to place an alias to the program
on the Desktop. 
<P>
<B>Move to Desktop</B> <BR>
This option directs MacWebApp to place the program file on the
Desktop. 
<P>
<B>Prompt before running program</B> <BR>
After the program is installed a dialog box comes up which allows
you to read the readme file, run the program and/or uninstall
it. 
<P>
<B>Uninstall after running program</B> <BR>
Disabled when Prompt before running program is on. This option
tells MacWebApp to ask you if you want to remove the program after
you close it. 
<P>
See the <A href="faq.html">MacWebApp FAQ</A> for answers to commonly
asked questions. 
