<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="58,2,99,22" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/general/new.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="102,0,160,23" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/search/search.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="162,0,239,22" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/feedback/feedback.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="241,1,293,23" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/general/about.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="294,1,374,23" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/cybrary/cybrary.html">
</MAP>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<BR><BR>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>W</FONT>eb<FONT SIZE=+3>A</FONT>pp <FONT SIZE=+3>B</FONT>ackgrounder</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<H3>Overview</H3>
<P>The Institute for Academic Technology (IAT), the developer of WebApp, is part of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and funded in part by IBM to advocate and facilitate at a national level the use of technology for learning.  The IAT has been working on a variety of fronts to utilize the WWW as a front end to distributed learning environments, where desktop computers and networks facilitate communication between users and provide access to all types of educational resources, including software applications.
<P>One of the problems in distributing educational software today via the Internet is the multi-step process required to get an application composed of multiple files off the net and run it.  Because the WWW transmits a single file when a link is selected, authors of software usually compress all of an application's files, such as multimedia resources, databases, etc., into a single file -- often referred to as a ZIP file.  
<P>When the end user clicks on a reference to an application in a WWW page, the file is retrieved from the WWW server.  Then the end user must do the following in order to run the application.
<OL>
<LI>Create a new directory.
<LI>Move the single compressed file into the new directory.
<LI>Uncompress the file.
<LI>Read an installation instruction file.
<LI>Run the installation program or manually install the application based on the installation instructions.
<LI>Run the program.
<LI>Create a desktop icon for subsequent uses of the application.
</OL>
<P>The steps outlined above are a time consuming distraction for the sophisticated user and are clearly too difficult for the less technical user. The IAT appreciates the level of simplification that must be reached in order to open the Internet up for distributed learning to the broad base of current and future Internet users who lack sophisticated technical skills.
<P>For this reason, the design goal for WebApp was to reduce the software installation and execution process to a single mouse click on a WWW page.
<H3>How WebApp Works</H3>
<P>After WebApp is installed with its custom setup program, the user must configure his/her WWW browser to recognize the MIME type "application/webapp."  This will allow the browser to run WebApp when the user retrieves a file stored in WebApp format.  WebApp will automatically configure the Mosaic browser from NCSA and the Netscape browser from Netscape Communications.
<P>The user then displays a WWW page that includes a reference to an application that is stored on the WWW server in WebApp format.
<P>After the user clicks on the reference in the WWW page, the file is retrieved by the browser to the local machine.  When the file has been received, the browser launches WebApp.
<P>WebApp then performs the follows actions:
<OL>
<LI>Creates a subdirectory.
<LI>If virus protection software is available, virus checks the file before and after dearchiving files.
<LI>Dearchives the file into its component files.
<LI>Runs the application's setup program, if applicable.
<LI>Creates a program manager icon for the application in a program manager group of the user's choice.
<LI>Establishes entries in the MS Windows registration database -- also known as setting an "association" -- if applicable.
<LI>Runs the application.
<LI>After the user exits the application for the first time, WebApp will prompt to uninstall the application.
</OL>
<P>There are a number of other options that allow the user to control various aspects of this process.  However, if the default settings are used, then no interaction is required from the user.
<P>The end user can configure WebApp to use whatever virus scanning software is available as long as the software accepts command line parameters.  WebApp's online help includes Internet addresses where freeware or shareware virus scanning software can be downloaded.
<H3>Other Uses for WebApp</H3>
<P>WebApp is applicable for much more than distributing educational 
software and updates.  Besides automatically downloading and playing 
multimedia scripts on client machines, Web users can take advantage of 
WebApp to download software demos and then automatically uninstall them 
after examination.
<H3>WebApp Archives Format</H3>
<P>Creating files in WebApp format is simple.  No fees or royalties are 
required.  WebApp was designed to work with whatever archiving software an 
author wishes to use.  WebApp's online documentation includes Internet 
locations where shareware or freeware archiving software can be found.  

<P>The basic steps in creating a WebApp archive file are:
<OL>
<LI>Create a WebApp archive configuration file.  Online instructions and examples are provided with WebApp.
<LI>Create an archive file that includes all of the application's files and the WebApp archive configuration file.
<LI>Create a self-extracting version of the archive file.
<LI>Rename the self-extracting archive file's extension from EXE to WAI.
<LI>Place the file on a WWW server
</OL>
<P>[One of the server's configuration files must be updated to include the "application/webapp wai" MIME type.  This change is very simple and is only necessary the first time a WebApp archive file is placed on the server.]
<P>Steps 2-4 are done automatically with tools provided with WebApp.
<H3>Distribution of WebApp</H3>
<P>30-day trial versions of WebApp are available <a href="index.html">online</a>.  Registered copies of WebApp are available from the <A HREF="index.html#distributor">distributor</A>:
<P><DT>Site license and bundling licenses are available from:
<DD>Institute for Academic Technology
<DD>2525 Meridian Parkway, Suite 400
<DD>Durham, NC 27713
<DD>919-405-1927
<DD><A HREF="mailto:webapp@unc.edu">webapp@unc.edu</A>

<BR>
