<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>VRML: L</FONT>inks to <FONT SIZE=+3>R</FONT>esources</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=10 CELLPADDING=10>

<TR><TH VALIGN=TOP><STRONG>Selected Documents</STRONG></TH><TH VALIGN=TOP><STRONG>Annotation and Comments</STRONG></TH></TR>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.sdsc.edu/vrml/">The VRML Repository</A></TD>
<TD  VALIGN=TOP>The <STRONG>first</STRONG> place anyone should go to find out what is most current in the VRML project and community.  Produced and maintained by the San Diego Supercomputer Center, this site has links to documentation, browsers, archives, etc.  The site is regularly updated.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><a href="http://www.aereal.com">Aereal Inc.</a> <IMG SRC="../../media/gifs/new.gif" BORDER=0></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>Aereal Inc., with their own <a href="http://www.aereal.com/home.wrl.gz">home world</a> comes online with a vast array of links and VRML services, including the <a href="http://www.aereal.com/instant/">instant VRML home world</a> option off their front page.  They also offer links to more than <A HREF="http://www.aereal.com/boom/"> 1000 VRML URLs</A> (yes, seeing is believing).  Overall, this site rivals the Repository as a central clearing house for links to VRML worlds. 
</TR>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.zdnet.com/~zdi/vrml">Ziff-Davis 
Publishing</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>Ziff-Davis 
Publishing</A> teams up with Black Sun to extend the functionality of its <A HREF=http://www.zdnet.com/zdi/vrml/content/vrmlsite/outside.wrl>Terminal Reality</A>  VRML site.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.vrmlsite.com">VRMLSite Magazine</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>VRMLSite Magazine looks to be a valuable site for information on VRML 2.0 and sites being developed with the new standard.  In particular, this site has a strong system of links and information on a range of topics related to VRML.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://gnn.com/gnn/wr/sept29/features/vrml/">VR for the People</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>GNN's feature article on VRML--a <STRONG>MUST</STRONG> read.   GNN offers an important layman's perspective on distributing VRML and VR through the Internet.  Beware of the "hype-factor" and salty prose.  (September 1995)</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://vag.vrml.org/VRML_FAQ.html">VRML FAQ</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>The VRML FAQlooks fairly up to date.  As with most FAQs, it's a smart place to start looking.<BR>This FAQ is hyperlinked and relatively extensive. (Monthly updates.)</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.hyperreal.com/~mpesce/vrml/vrml.tech/vrml10-3.html">VRML 1.0 Specification</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>This is the initial VRML specification authored by Gavin Bell, Anthony Parisi, and Mark Pesce.(May 26, 1995)</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://vrml.sgi.com/moving-worlds/">Moving Worlds Specification (VRML 2.0)</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>The approved (by VAG--VRML Architecture Group) specification for VRML 2.0.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.oki.com/vrml/timeline.txt">A VRML Timeline</A></TD><BR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>A short chronology of the development of VRML taken from the VRML FAQ.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://vrml.wired.com/future/jch.txt">The VRML of Babel</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>Jan C. Hardenbergh's (brief) white paper looking forward beyond VRML 1.0  (August 18, 1995)</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.lysator.liu.se/~zap/vr_prop1.html">VRML Behaviour - a proposal</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>Håkan "Zap" Andersson's paper on the direction of behavior development in VRML (October 1995).</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://hyperreal.com/~wlm/vrsl.html">VRML Audio Extentions</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>William Martens' "draft of a document describing how spatialized sound might be added to VRML (August 19, 1995).</TD> </TR>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://vrml.wired.com/future/scale.html">Scale</a></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.hyperreal.com/~mpesce/">Mark Pesce's</A> Discussion of Scale (August 19, 1995).</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.oki.com/vrml/VRML_S95.HTM">VRML: Using 3D to Surf the Web</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>Advanced Presentation for Course #12 at SIGGRAPH 95</TD></TR>


<TR><TH VALIGN=TOP><STRONG>Sites to Surf</STRONG></TH><TH VALIGN=TOP><STRONG>Annotation and Comments</STRONG></TH></TR>


<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://vrml.sgi.com/">SGI's VRML Pages</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>One of the key sites for the new movement into VRML 2.0</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.well.com/user/caferace/vrml.html">Jim Race's VRML Page</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>Award-winning site.  Valuable site.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://vrml.wired.com/">Wired's VRML Forum</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>A more formal clearing house of information about VRML.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://amber.rc.arizona.edu/vrml.html">Experimenting with VRML</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>Marvin Landis's (University of Arizona) gathering of VRML objects, scenes, and converters.  All have the "VRML 'Good Housekeeping Seal of Approval', via verification as legitimate VRML objects by Daeron Meyer's VRML Authenticator.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.newcollege.edu/vrmLab/">New College VRML Lab</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>New College of California's VRML Lab offers is a good place to go if looking for some a <A HREF="http://www.newcollege.edu/vrmLab/Warehouse/">warehouse</A> of objects and spaces rendered in VRML (October 1995 update.)</TD>
</TABLE>

