<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>VRML W</FONT>orlds</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=10 CELLPADDING=10>

<TD VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2>
<P>The proliferation of VRML worlds is astoundingly rapid.  Below are a few sites with links to some interesting VRML worlds.  This list should NOT be considered definitive by any means.</P>

<TR><TH VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=+1>Selected Worlds</FONT></TH><TH VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=+1>Annotation and Comments</FONT></TH></TR>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.sdsc.edu/SDSC/Partners/vrml/examples.html">The VRML Repository's Sample Applications</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>The <STRONG>first</STRONG> place anyone should go to find out what is most current in the VRML project and community.  Produced and maintained by the San Diego Supercomputer Center, this site has links to documentation, browsers, archives, etc.  The site is regularly updated.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><a href="http://www.aereal.com">Aereal Inc.</a> <IMG SRC="../../media/gifs/new.gif" BORDER=0></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>Aereal Inc., with their own <a href="http://www.aereal.com/home.wrl.gz">home world</a> comes online with a vast array of links and VRML services, including the <a href="http://www.aereal.com/instant/">instant VRML home world</a> option off their front page.  They also offer links to more than <A HREF="http://www.aereal.com/boom/"> 1000 VRML URLs</A> (yes, seeing is believing).  Overall, this site rivals the Repository as a central clearing house for links to VRML worlds. 
</TR>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://vrml.sgi.com/worlds/">The SGI VRML Worlds</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>This site is a collection of VRML 1.0 worlds and 2.0 worlds.  Check it out..</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://jefferson.village.virginia.edu/">UVA's WAXWeb</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>You've got to see this site to really understand it.  Highly recommended if you can get your hardware and software to render it.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.hyperion.com/planet9/vrsoma.htm">SOMA - The San 
Francisco Walkthrough</a></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>And I quote:  "Planet 9 Studios, using a specially modified portion of their larger San Francisco model, has created VIRTUAL
     SOMA, the first 3D city model to be viewed in real time on the Internet. SOMA (South of Market Street Area)
     is the neighborhood in San Francisco where most of the Internet software and animation development happens."  Check this site out.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.gsaup.ucla.edu:80/vrml/" >UCLA VRML Studies</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>The Architecture and Urban Design group of  of the UCLA School of the Arts and Architecture has put together some interesting worlds. </TD>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=2>
</TABLE>
