<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>VRML B</FONT>rowsers</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=10 CELLPADDING=10>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2>Browser Overload!  Because I simply cannot keep up with all the browsers, I'm going to link directly to the Repository's annotated list of VRML browsers. Good luck.</TD></TR>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=+1>Browser</FONT></TH><TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=+1>Comments</FONT></TH></TR>


<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="http://www.sdsc.edu/SDSC/Partners/vrml/software/browsers.html">VRML Browsers</A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>The VRML Repositories list and links to the current browsers on the market.  The links on this site are extensive and often the best place to start looking.</TD>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=2>

<FONT  SIZE=+1>The State of the Browsers...</FONT>

<P>The state of VRML browsers reflects the state of the technology.  In looking over as many browsers as I could get my hands on, I've come to one simple characterization that applies to them all:  the first pimples of adolescence.  Though VRML 1.0 standard exists and the 2.0 standard is being announced and settled as we speak, the browsers haven't quite gained the discipline needed to meet the needs of users.  Like adolescents, they're searching to find themselves, and most of them aren't making too much headway.

<P>The youth of the interfaces alone hinder any sense of the 3D space on the 2D flatscreen.  From Pioneer to WebSpace to Lived3D, the means of "moving" within the 3D space is clumsy, like the teenager who just jumped four shoe sizes and shot up six inches--in a year.  Pioneer gives you almost nothing to go on when it comes to movement in the 3D space.  WebSpace tries to give the first-person perspective of riding a space sled complete with throttle and funky nobs.  WorldView offers the most intuitive movement interface with its three arrow-button palates that give you at the least a sense of what direction you'll be moving.  Bear in mind, though, that movement in these 3D spaces is nothing more than a shifting of perspective.  

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<CENTER><A HREF="mailto:chad_kearsley@unc.edu">Drop a note</A> to <A HREF="http://www.unc.edu/~chad_k/">Chad Kearsley</A>, IAT Webmaster and Research Assistant.
</CENTER>
