<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>VRML A</FONT>uthoring <FONT SIZE=+3>T</FONT>ools</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=10 CELLPADDING=10>

<TR><TH VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="350"><STRONG>Selected Authoring Tools</STRONG><BR></TH><TH VALIGN="TOP"><STRONG>Annotation and Comments</STRONG></TH></TR>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.sdsc.edu/SDSC/Partners/vrml/software/modelers.html">The VRML Repository</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>The <STRONG>first</STRONG> place to go when hunting for current VRML tools, both authoring and browsing.  Produced and maintained by the San Diego Supercomputer Center, this site has links to documentation, browsers, archives, etc.  The site is regularly updated.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.caligari.com/">Pioneer</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>One of the more recent developments, Caligari's Pioneer combines an authoring tool with a browser.  The interface requires a practice and seems a tad slow on some systems.  Compared to the market standards for shareware VRML tools, Pioneer is close to the top.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://webspace.sgi.com/WebSpaceAuthor/index.html">WebSpace Author</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>Silicon Graphics tools are SGI tools.  The biggest problem with SGI is the hardware requirements.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.us.paragraph.com/whatsnew/homespce.htm">Homespace Builder</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>The Repository folks say that Homespace Builder "will bring easy-to-use and inexpensive 3D paradigm to millions of Internet members."    The rendering tool may be relatively easy to use, but what it gives in ease-of-use, it loses in the range of object creation.  Note, however, that the Paragraph folks have moved forward quickly into the multimedia VRML arena.  Definitely look at this product if you're looking for adding multimedia to your VRML.</TD>

<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.virtus.com/">Virtus Walkthrough Pro 2.5</A></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>Virtus's lastest version of Walkthough Ori allows the user to export the file as VRML.  As a modelling package, Walthrough Pro is robust and easy to use; as a VRML modelling package, it is less than robust but still easy to use.  For getting started with VRML, you can't go wrong with Virtus's 3D Web Builder.</TD></TR>

</TABLE>


