<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Digital Distribution Methods for Multimedia Networking</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>Digital Distribution Methods for Multimedia Networking<BR>
An Introduction to Multimedia Networking</H2>

By:  David Luttrell
<BR>
Institute for Academic Technology
<P>
<I>Last revised:  June 2, 1994</I>
<HR WIDTH=200></CENTER>
<P>
Multimedia computer systems combine a variety of sensory inputs such as
audio, video, still photos, and animation with the text and
number-oriented interactivity and flexibility of the computer.  The
combination of these elements provides a more natural interface, the
ability to present information in a wide variety of forms and formats,
and a degree of interactivity unavailable before.  This results in
systems which have been shown to be much more effective in such
applications as training and education, sales and marketing,
entertainment, and other areas than their "monomedia" predecessors. 
While the concept of multimedia computing has been around for some
time, only in recent years has a combination of evolving standards and
declining costs made multimedia systems practical enough for widespread
use.
<P>
As Multimedia based systems mature, their development closely parallels
the early days of the microcomputer.  When microcomputers first became
widely available, applications written for individual PC's were
developed, improved, and ultimately widely adopted by users.  Then,
with the proliferation of these separate computers, came the need to
share information and expensive peripherals between multiple users and
their computers.  This in turn led to the development of
microcomputer-based Local Area Networks (LAN's).  LAN's were then
followed by Wide Area Networks (WAN's), and variations such as
Campus-wide networks, Enterprise networks, and Global networks.
<P>
Multimedia systems and applications are improving and rapidly gaining
acceptance by computer users.  As this happens, questions are arising
about sharing multimedia materials and related peripherals.  The
logical progression of this leads next to the need for and the
development of multimedia capable networks.  
<P>
This document will help explain the requirements of, and some solutions
for distribution of multimedia over a network.  It will first examine
the two broad categorizations of multimedia distribution systems
(analog and digital) and the relative merits of these systems.  Then a
more detailed examination of the technologies involved in digital
multimedia will be undertaken. 


<H3>Types of Multimedia Networks</H3>

In order to explain the requirements of networked multimedia, we must
first examine the two types of data  and signals which may be
distributed to the network users.  Traditional video (i.e., television)
and audio (i.e., radio) signals are composed of continuously varying
(analog) electromagnetic waves.  The senses of sound and sight are
inherently analog-wave-based.  VCR's, laserdisks, audio cassettes, and
records all use electrical or mechanical methods to store and re-create
these waves.
<P>
While analog signals are the norm for human beings, digital signals are
the native mode for computers.  Digital signals represent data as a
series of 1s and 0s which can be transmitted, manipulated, and stored
by the computer.  Analog signals, such as sound, can be digitized for
handling by a computer through a process called sampling.  Basically,
sampling breaks down an analog wave into smaller pieces, and represents
those pieces digitally (1s and 0s).  When needed, the computer can take
this digital data and re-create a wave similar to the original.  If
done properly, any differences between the two waves (the original and
the digitally re-created) will be indistinguishable to humans. 
Computer disks, compact disc audio (CDs), and digital audio tape (DAT)
are all examples of digital storage devices.
<P>
Analog distribution systems which can coexist with, but operate
separately from a digital computer network have existed for some time. 
Traditional television distribution systems, along with matrix-switched
video and audio distribution systems are examples of these systems. 
While these systems perform some functions very well, digital networks
have a number of significant advantages.


<H3>Advantages and Disadvantages of Digital Networks</H3>

The single biggest advantage of digital distribution of multimedia is
the ability to integrate and control the resulting audio and video
signals in the computer environment.  This provides a number of
significant benefits.  Once these signals are in the digital
environment, they can be analyzed, manipulated, and controlled like any
other type of data.  Over the last several years, digital processing of
video signals has revolutionized television, movie production,
satellite data analysis, weather tracking/forecasting, and numerous
other areas.  Incorporating audio and video signals into the digital
network environment promises to similarly revolutionize desktop
computer usage.
<P>
Another significant advantage of the digital processing and
distribution of these signals can be seen in the way computers are
used.  Computers' inherent interactivity and control are encouraging
development of entirely new methods of training, education, and
entertainment.
<P>
Finally, because digital signals can be duplicated perfectly, digital
data can be transmitted over long distances, copied, edited, enhanced
and otherwise modified, generation after generation, without loss of
signal quality.  Error correction available in digital networks can
insure the integrity of the final signal.
<P>
Even with these advantages, digital distribution is not yet widespread
because of some differences between analog and digital signal
distribution.  Among these differences are the distance information can
be effectively transmitted, and the quality of sounds and images
transmitted.


<H3>Transmission Distance / Scope of Distribution</H3>

Mature technology exists to transmit analog signals to large numbers of
viewers over virtually unlimited distances.  Television signals which
are frequently broadcast over wide areas are a common example. 
Existing satellite technology allows these analog signals to be sent
virtually anywhere with little degradation in quality.  Since these
signals are one-way, it is relatively simple to add additional
receivers without affecting quality.
<P>
Digital transmission is currently less well suited to very long
distance transmission.  Digital transmissions' size,  and their
frequent two-way nature are more than many transmission media can
currently handle.  For example, wireless networks, which transmit data
in much the same way that broadcast TV transmits video and audio
signals, are currently much slower than traditional (i.e., Ethernet or
Token-Ring) networks, which themselves are not always adequate for the
demands of multimedia (as will be seen later.)  


<H3>Signal Quality</H3>

Distributed signals' quality can be perceived by users in two main
areas, audio quality and video quality.  Broadcast television, with
which most people are familiar, gives a good standard for comparison.
<P>
In general human beings can hear sound in the frequency range of 20Hz
to 20,000Hz.  This then is the "ideal" maximum bandwidth for sound. 
While the reproduction of these sounds varies from one television to
another, a very good TV, or one whose audio is channeled through a
stereo amplifier should be able to reproduce most of the 20-20,000Hz
spectrum.  Digitally recorded audio quality varies depending on the
sampling rate and sampling width (bit depth) at which the original
analog wave is converted to digital.  A sampling rate of 44KHz (44,000
samples per second) will provide the full 20-20,000Hz spectrum.  If it
has a 16 bit sampling width it will have CD quality noise levels. 
However, this also creates very large files.  Because of this, other
sampling rates (22KHz, 11KHz) and bit widths (8 bits) are used when
lower quality audio is acceptable.  An 11KHz sampling rate will produce
a spectrum encompassing approximately 20-5500 Hz.  (For comparison, the
audio sent over standard telephone connections covers the frequency
range from 300Hz through 3,000Hz.)  This slower sampling rate will
significantly reduce the storage requirements of the recorded sound. 
Switching from a 16 bit sample (65,536 volume levels) to an 8 bit
sample (256 volume levels), will significantly increase the noise
level, but will halve the storage requirements.
<P>
A television picture consists of a matrix of dots (or pixels) whose
visible portion measures 484 rows by 360 columns.  By combining various
combinations of red, green, and blue, the pixels on a TV screen can
display a range of approximately 16 million colors.  The color pictures
created by the television are delivered at a rate of 30 frames per
second, providing the illusion of smooth motion.
<P>
As with audio, there are varying levels of digital video quality. 
There are three areas in which the video quality can vary in a digital
system.  These are the size of the reproduced picture, the range of
colors in the picture, and the speed in frames per second (FPS) at
which the video is reproduced.  To accurately reproduce the quality of
a traditional television, a digital system should create a picture with
a resolution of 640 rows by 480 columns (full-screen standard VGA),
24bit color resolution (16.7 million colors), and a frame rate of 30
FPS.  As with digital audio, this requires a tremendous amount of
storage.  As a result, video images are often stored in smaller screen
sizes (i.e. 320x240 or 160x120), with fewer colors (i.e. 8 bit
resolution, 256 colors), and slower frame rates (minimum of 15FPS for
motion).


<H3>Digital Distribution Methods</H3>

<H4>Differences Between Multimedia Networking and Traditional Networking</H4>

There are numerous factors which distinguish multimedia network demands
from traditional (data-oriented) networking demands.  Key among these
are the differences in size of multimedia and traditional data files,
and multimedia data's isochronous (time-sensitive) nature.
<P>
A quick look at the data files associated with audio or video reveals
that these files can be orders of magnitude larger than traditional
files.  Uncompressed, ten minutes of CD quality audio can require over
100 megabytes of storage.  That same ten minutes of true color, 30 FPS
uncompressed video running in a 320 X 240 window might require over 3
gigabytes of storage.  Although several standards exist for compressing
these files, even compressed the files can be quite large.  Ten minutes
of audio and video compressed and stored in the common  Audio Video
Interleaved (AVI) format used in Windows can still require some 90
megabytes of storage.
<P>
The size of these files presents a variety of challenges to stand-alone
multimedia systems, such as maximizing use of limited storage space and
providing adequate speed to move the data from disk to memory.  Adding
a network to the equation creates two more challenges.  One of these is
the issue of storing and managing all of these large files for multiple
users.  This issue is currently addressed by specialized video servers
or software from companies such as IBM, Starlight, ProtoComm and
Novell.  The second issue, and the one which we will discuss in this
paper, is the delivery of these large amounts of data across the
network.
<P>
Multimedia traffic's isochronous or time-sensitive nature is another
factor which distinguishes it from traditional network traffic.  In a
traditional networking environment, data flow is "bursty".  This means
that there are frequently long delays between transmissions on the
network.  For example, when a word processor is being used, there is
typically network traffic generated when the program loads,  when a
file is saved or retrieved, and when other parts of the program (such
as a spelling checker) are loaded.  Slight delays during each of these
steps are normal and generally accepted.  If the network is busy, and
it takes an extra fraction of a second to load a data file, most users
will not notice.  However, audio and video (AV) traffic have different
requirements.  First, AV traffic is generally stream oriented rather
than bursty.  Instead of just loading a file across the network (with a
brief wait), and then working with the file locally, audio and video
often require a constant flow of information across the network.  For
example, if we wanted to view the 10 minutes of video mentioned before,
we generally cannot load all 90 megabytes across the network into the
local machine and then view it.  Instead we must view the data as it
flows across the network.  This is the second difference in multimedia
traffic, its isochronous nature.  As mentioned before, slight delays in
data transmission are common and generally unnoticed in traditional
network traffic.  Indeed, most networks are optimized for this kind of
traffic.  However human senses very quickly notice these delays in
multimedia traffic.  Delays in video transmissions result in jerky
motion, and delays in audio transmissions can quickly render sounds
unrecognizable.  Therefore it is important that multimedia data be
delivered to workstations "on time".


<H3>Limitations of Existing Networks</H3>

Using traditional networks such as Ethernet and Token Ring to
distribute multimedia to client computers has revealed some limitations
associated with those networks.  These limitations generally fall into
two main areas; a lack of bandwidth or capacity to move the large
amounts of data associated with multimedia, and an inability to
effectively handle isochronous traffic.


<H3>Bandwidth</H3>

As mentioned previously, sending digital audio and video across a
network entails moving very large amounts of data from a server to the
client computer.  Shared media networks such as Ethernet and Token-Ring
have limited capacity which must be shared among all of the machines
which are using them.
<P>
For example, an Ethernet network has a theoretical data rate of 10
megabits per second (in reality, overhead and other factors reduce this
by a significant amount).  A typical CD-ROM drive which meets the MPC
(Multimedia Personal Computer) standard is required to be able to send
data at 150 kilobytes (or approximately 1.2 megabits) per second.  At
first glance, it would appear that an Ethernet network should be able
to handle about 8 multimedia connections (10Mbps / 1.2Mbps).  In
reality however, Ethernet was not designed to handle the continuous
streams of data that audio and video require.  Token-Ring networks have
similar limitations. These "contention based" networks were designed to
handle multiple machines which generated bursty traffic and were
tolerant of delays.  While one computer is sending data across the
network, any others that want to send information must wait and then
attempt to get control of the network when it becomes available.  As
more computers try to use the network, not only is there more
information to be transmitted, but the efficiency of the network
simultaneously drops.  The result of this is that unmodified shared
Ethernet is generally effective for a maximum of only four simultaneous
multimedia connections.  According to IBM, Token-Ring's contention
scheme and higher bandwidth can support up to ten connections.
<P>
FDDI networks, which are based on high speed fiber optic cable,
overcome this problem to some extent by providing higher bandwidth. 
The FDDI specification provides a maximum throughput of 100 megabits
per second (10 times faster than standard Ethernet, and some 6 times
faster than 16Mbps Token-Ring).  In practice however, FDDI suffers from
the same problems as Ethernet and Token-Ring.  As more users are added,
each trying to send large continuous streams of data, the efficiency of
the network drops far below its theoretical maximum.


<H3>Isochronous Traffic</H3>

A second, related problem with traditional networks is that due to
their original design goals, they have no way of insuring a constant
even flow of data to the client computers. Traditional Ethernet (and
Token Ring) are packet-switched networks.  This means that when a
station wants to send information to another station, it puts variably
sized packets of data out on the network, and the network eventually
passes the packets to their destination.  This is analogous to the way
the postal service handles mail.  There is no direct connection between
the sender and the receiver.  The main problems that packet-switched
systems present for multimedia delivery are that there is no way to
guarantee the amount of time it takes a packet to get to its
destination (latency), and there is no guarantee of specific packet
sizes.  While these limitations cause little difficulty for traditional
data, they lead to problems such as jitter (jumpy video or audio) for
multimedia.
<P>
These problems are further complicated by the fact that as more and
more computers are added to the network, traditional networks behave
"democratically".  They reduce the speed of all users' data equally. 
Unfortunately, while traditional data flows can handle this (i.e. a
slightly longer delay when opening a word processing document), audio
and video signals cannot be slowed down significantly without
meaningful (often unacceptable) degradation in the quality and
therefore usefulness of the sounds or pictures they are carrying. 
While using a faster network such as FDDI or the new CDDI (100Mbps over
copper wire) can provide a larger margin for error, they contain no
provisions for insuring a steady flow of data such as is required by
multimedia.


<H3>New Network Topologies</H3>

There are several new network technologies in various stages of
development which promise to facilitate multimedia networking.  These
include variations on existing network types, such as switched Ethernet
and Token-Ring, extensions of existing network types, such as "fast"
Ethernet, FDDI-II, and Isochronous Ethernet, and new networks, such as
ATM.


<H4>Switched Ethernet / Token-Ring</H4>

In a traditional Ethernet network such as 10BaseT, each computer has a
network card which connects to a central hub.  The 10BaseT hub is
basically a repeater which takes any signal coming in on one port, and
rebroadcasts it on all ports.  Thus, in keeping with Ethernet's basic
bus structure, every machine "hears" every other machine.  Similarly,
every machine on a Token Ring network handles data for other machines.
<P>
Switched Ethernet and Token-Ring use standard cabling and network
interface cards (NICs), but replace the central repeater with a central
switch which sends data arriving on one port only to its destination
port.  This switch in effect gives each machine a dedicated (unshared)
10Mbps (Ethernet) or 16Mbps (Token-Ring) channel to the switch.  So,
while shared Ethernet or Token-Ring are poorly suited to multimedia
traffic, a dedicated channel of either type can be much more effective.
This dedicated channel, while still not specifically designed to handle
isochronous traffic, can provide enough unshared bandwidth to overcome
these problems. On most switched systems, a single port can support a
small cluster of PC's (i.e. the four machine limit on Ethernet
discussed earlier).  
<P>
Because a single Ethernet or Token-Ring card in the server would
present a bottleneck which would negate the benefits of a switched
system, the server must either have multiple NICs so that each client
machine (or cluster) can have its own connection to the server, or have
a much faster link such as FDDI. 
<P>
Switched Ethernet and Token-Ring's primary advantages are their
preservation of much of the existing network investment (i.e. existing
10BaseT interface cards and wiring can still be used), and their
relative familiarity.  Apart from the switching hub itself, there are
no new elements to learn.
<P>
There are two primary disadvantages currently associated with switching
systems.  The first is their relatively high cost per port.  Typical
systems currently retail for $800 to $1500 per port for switched
Ethernet.  The second problem is that the basic design of these systems
(i.e. multiple unshared links) does not lend itself to use in anything
other than a Local Area Network.  Interconnection to WAN's is certainly
possible, but other systems on the network gain no performance
enhancements.
<P>
Switched Ethernet is currently available from a number of
manufacturers.  Appendix B lists some of the major manufacturers and
their switching products. Switched Token-Ring is in the works from
several manufacturers, but has not been released as of the publication
of this paper.


<H4>Fast Ethernet</H4>

A second technology which may offer advances in multimedia networking
is a developing standard called Fast Ethernet.  The theory is that Fast
Ethernet will ultimately provide FDDI-like performance (100Mbps) at a
much lower cost. According to the proposals, Fast Ethernet is very
similar to 10BaseT Ethernet in its physical layout.  Although upgrading
to Fast Ethernet will require replacing network cards and hubs, it is
hoped that existing wiring can be used.  
<P>
One of the main obstacles to the rapid introduction of a Fast Ethernet
standard is the debate over how it should work.  While most proponents
have agreed on certain features (100Mbps speed, 100 meter segment
length, support for twisted pair wiring, support for 802.3 frame
format, etc.), they are divided on how logical access to the media
should be controlled.  One group believes that Fast Ethernet should use
the same control method (CSMA/CD) that 10Mbps Ethernet uses.  This
would in effect be identical to current 10BaseT Ethernet, but would run
at 100Mbps.  The other group, calling their Fast Ethernet 100BaseVG
(Voice Grade), proposes to use a control system called Demand Priority
Access (DPA).  DPA would allow for "normal priority" and "high
priority" traffic to coexist on the network.  Traditional data would
generally be classified as normal priority, while audio and video would
be high priority.  DPA would require more fundamental changes to the
Ethernet standard (leading many to say it is not really Ethernet at
all), but might be better suited to multimedia needs.  The IEEE 802.3
committee has decided to sanction the pursuit of both standards
<P>
Current supporters of true 802.3 based 100Mbps Fast Ethernet include
Cabletron Systems, Chipcom, David Systems, Grand Junction Networks, IMC
Networks, Intel Corp., LAN Media, Micro Linear, National Semiconductor,
NCR, Networth, Racal-Datacom, SMC, Sun Microsystems, Synoptics, and
3Com.
<P>
100BaseVG is supported primarily by AT&T Microelectronics, Banyan
Systems, Hewlett-Packard, Microsoft, Novell, Ungerman-Bass, and
Wellfleet.
<P>
Several manufacturers have announced 100Mbps "Fast Ethernet" products
already, but since the standards have not yet been finalized, these
should be considered proprietary networks.  See Appendix C for a list
of manufacturers and their products.


<H4>isoENET</H4> 

Another attempt to add multimedia capability to Ethernet comes in the
form of a new transport called Isochronous Ethernet, or isoENET. 
IsoENET, developed by National Semiconductor and IBM represents an
attempt to combine IEEE 802.9 Isochronous LAN standards with regular
802.3 10BaseT Ethernet.  IsoENET adds a 6.144Mbps synchronous channel
to the 10Mbps channel already supported by Ethernet.  This 6.144Mbps
channel can be divided into multiple 64Kbps segments for allocation to
different isochronous communication tasks.
<P>
IsoENET's additional 6.144Mbps capacity takes the form of a
circuit-switched network. A circuit-switched network in effect
establishes a guaranteed connection between specified stations (as
opposed to the packet-switched networks described previously).  The
telephone system is a good example of a circuit-switched network.  Once
a connection is established, you are guaranteed enough capacity for
your conversation, and there are no system-introduced delays.  Circuit
switched computer networks similarly are able to guarantee latency with
a fixed packet size.  
<P>
IsoENET will use existing 10BaseT compatible wiring and will be
compatible with some hubs.  Using IsoENET will require replacement of
the interface cards in the PCs on the network, and replacement of the
10BaseT modules in the network hubs.  IsoENET is designed to be
backward compatible with 10BaseT, and forward compatible with FDDI-II
(described below).
<P>
Apple Computers, AT&T Bell Laboratories, and others are sponsoring
IsoENET's submission to the IEEE for standardization, but it will be
some time before products based on IsoENET are readily available. 
Current estimates call for IsoENET based products to be available in
first quarter 1994, at about twice the cost of existing 10BaseT
components.  


<H4>Fiber Distributed Data Interface II (FDDI-II)</H4>

FDDI-II (ANSI X3T9.5) is a proposed superset of the FDDI specification
which incorporates mechanisms to support isochronous traffic.  The
addition of this support suggests that FDDI-II will be better suited to
multimedia delivery than standard FDDI.
<P>
FDDI-II adds circuit-switching technology to FDDI  in much the same way
isoENET adds to Ethernet.  FDDI-II divides its 100Mbps bandwidth into
16 6.144Mbps circuit-switched channels for isochronous traffic.  These
channels can be further subdivided for lower speed requirements.  Any
unallocated bandwidth may be used by traditional asynchronous data. 
FDDI-II basically guarantees a specific amount of capacity to a given
machine at a specific time interval.  This guarantee, along with the
relatively high capacity of the fiber-based network, should enable
FDDI-II to deliver relatively large numbers of simultaneous multimedia
sessions.
<P>
While FDDI-II seems well suited to multimedia networking, there are
several obstacles to its rapid introduction. First, it is estimated
that it will be one to two years before the FDDI-II specification is
finalized and in production.  Second, FDDI-II is not compatible with
standard FDDI.  This means that existing FDDI networks must be
completely switched to FDDI-II in order to utilize it.  Finally, like
FDDI, FDDI-II components (network interface cards, hubs, and fiber) are
significantly more expensive than copper based networks.
<P>
While FDDI-II is not available yet, a company called Alfa, Inc. (110
Breeds Hill Rd., Hyannis, MA 02601 (508) 790-9901) has introduced a
system called FDDI-Sync which is essentially a pre-standard FDDI-II
implementation.  As with the fast Ethernet products described
previously, this should be considered a proprietary standard. 


<H4>Priority Enhanced Token Ring</H4>

IBM is working with an enhancement to Token Ring which has proven
effective at handling multimedia traffic in early tests.  IBM's newest
Token Ring card, the LANStreamer, supplements standard Token Ring with
two significant enhancements.  The first is a method of transferring
data directly from the network to the computer's memory, or from the
computer's memory to the network.  Traditionally data has been
transferred from the computer's memory to memory on the Token Ring
card, and then from the card's memory onto the network (or vice versa).
This change significantly enhances the performance of the Token Ring
network for all types of data.
<P>
The LANStreamer card also implements a priority queuing function which
allows multiple streams of data to pass through the card
simultaneously, and allows specified streams (i.e. multimedia) to get
more attention and faster processing than other, traditional
data-oriented streams.  Planned software from IBM will also coordinate
servers' use of the network with the priority queuing process, further
enhancing multimedia delivery.


<H4>Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM)</H4>

One of the most promising new technologies is Asynchronous Transfer
Mode (ATM).  ATM will ultimately support a wide range of speeds,
transparent integration with Wide Area Networks, and built-in support
for isochronous multimedia traffic.  The protocols comprising ATM are
suitable for voice, traditional data, image, and video distribution. 
It promises to unite traditional data networks, telephone networks, and
multimedia-oriented networks.
<P>
ATM technology evolved out of the telephone industry's search for
better digital phone systems.  It was designed to satisfy voice
traffic's requirements for extremely low delay.  The data processing
industry, working in conjunction with the telephone industry, has
worked toward adding basic data networking capability, as well as the
very high throughput capability needed for such things as full-motion
video to ATM's basic design.
<P>
The result of this interaction is a system which divides network
traffic, regardless of type, into small (53 byte) cells which can be
switched (transferred) from one machine to another through the network
with very little delay or jitter.  Further, since the ATM protocols are
independent of the speed of the physical media they run on, upgrades to
faster media are possible as they become available.
<P>
ATM provides for varying classes of service depending on the priority
and/or importance of the data being transmitted.  For example, it is
very important that all data being sent in a traditional data network
arrive at its destination.  If part of a spreadsheet or word processing
document does not arrive significant problems ensue.  On the other
hand, some types of data (such as video) can be much more tolerant of
such losses.  If a small amount of data in a video stream is dropped in
transit, its absence may be undetectable, and therefore unimportant. 
ATM takes advantage of these differences by assigning one of four
priority classes to each data stream depending on the streams
individual requirements.
<P>
When an application needs to communicate across the network, it makes a
request to the ATM hub, in which it specifies the class of service, and
the amount of bandwidth it needs.  If the network has sufficient
capacity to handle the request, it guarantees the requesting
application or machine the level of service it needs.  If the hub
cannot guarantee the service requested, the application can either wait
and ask again at a later time, or adjust its requirements and request a
smaller amount of bandwidth.  The net effect of all of this is that
once a connection is established, an application which needs to
communicate across the network knows that it can transmit its message
at a given level of service.  This contrasts with traditional networks
such as Ethernet where each packet transmitted may behave differently
depending on the network's load at the time of transmission (or
attempted transmission).
<P>
ATM systems are currently under development at speeds varying from
25Mbps through Synchronous Optical Network (SONET) speeds of up to 2.5
Gbps.  Initial implementations promise to be at 25 and 155Mbps and to
move quickly to 622Mbps.
<P>
While ATM currently looks to be the best long term solution for
multimedia networking (among other things), it is also among the least
mature of the new technologies discussed.  While a number of
manufacturers have announced ATM products (see Appendix D), the initial
targets of most of these systems are network backbones.  It is likely
to be some time before ATM to the desktop is a truly viable and
wide-spread option.  While some of the most important ATM standards
have just been finalized, a number of additional standards and features
are still under development.  ATM's potential, and the tremendous
amount of interest it has generated suggest that ATM developments may
proceed at a rapid pace.


<H3>Conclusions and Recommendations</H3>
	
As is evident from the preceding discussion, networking technologies
are in something of a transitional period.  At the time this paper was
published, changes to these technologies, and the companies developing
them were occurring weekly.  There is no one "correct" answer to the
questions posed by networked multimedia.  There are however a number of
general guidelines whose consideration will help to maximize the
potential for success.
<P>
For limited multimedia requirements, traditional networks such as
Ethernet and Token-Ring can be acceptable solutions.  As was mentioned
previously, a single Ethernet network can handle about 4 multimedia
sessions simultaneously.  Token-Ring (16mb) should be able to handle up
to about 10 sessions on a single ring.  (Keep in mind that for either
network type, significant traditional traffic will reduce the number of
possible multimedia sessions.)  For slightly larger numbers of
workstations, several small networks (Ethernet or Token-Ring), each
with their own interface in the server, can provide acceptable
performance.
<P>
If a significant investment in a 10BaseT Ethernet or Token-Ring network
already exists, a switching hub can provide multimedia capability while
preserving that investment.  Switching hubs are currently available for
Ethernet, and will soon be available for Token-Ring.
<P>
In new network installations, perhaps the most important decision that
can be made is the selection of the appropriate wiring.  Changing
network adapters and hubs can be expensive, but in a large network
changing the wiring is generally more expensive.  Ultimately it appears
that running fiber-optic cable to each desktop will provide the best
network capacity.  However the current cost of fiber installation and
of the equipment to utilize fiber (i.e. FDDI) limits its availability
to most users.  Assuming that fiber is not a possibility, it appears
that the best current choice for maximizing the usefulness and life
expectancy of wiring is star-wired category 5 unshielded twisted pair
cable.  In a star-wired network, cable runs from each computer location
(usually by way of a telephone-type jack in the wall) to a central
site.  Category 5 (sometimes called level 5) is a standard which
specifies minimum electrical and physical requirements for twisted pair
wire.  Most proposed high-speed network implementations are geared
toward category 5 cable, and commonly used technologies such as
Token-Ring and Ethernet can run over it too.  Generally accepted
procedure is to run 4 pairs of this cable to each location where a
computer might ever be.  (That means 4 pairs per computer that might be
installed.)  Note that it is imperative when installing a category 5
twisted pair network that all connectors and terminators are also
category 5 rated.  A wiring company experienced in network cabling
should be familiar with the end-to-end requirements of a category 5
cabling installation.


<H3>Appendix A. Sample Network Configurations</H3>

<H4>10BaseT Network</H4>
The first two examples shown below illustrate small traditional network
topologies which are effective for many types of multimedia.  The first
example shows a traditional 10BaseT Ethernet network comprising a
server and four workstations.  As mentioned previously, standard
Ethernet can support a maximum of four simultaneous multimedia
sessions.  Note that thick or thin Ethernet would function similarly.

<IMG SRC="tek5fig1.gif">

<P>
<H4>Token Ring Network</H4>
The next example shows a traditional Token-Ring Network (16Mbps) with a
server and 10 workstations.  IBM's testing indicates that 10 is the
maximum practical number of simultaneous multimedia sessions over a
standard 16Mbps Token-Ring network.

<IMG SRC="tek5fig2.gif">

<P>
<H4>Multiple Ethernet Networks</H4>
Traditional networks can support larger numbers of multimedia sessions
as long as they are divided into appropriate segments.  For example,
the following figure shows an Ethernet network (actually 3 networks)
configured to support 12 multimedia sessions.  As was mentioned
previously, the use of multiple independent segments and multiple
interfaces in the server can overcome many of the limitations inherent
in traditional networks.  The limiting factor in this type of network
is the number of interfaces and workstations that the server and its
software are capable of supporting.

<IMG SRC="tek5fig3.gif">

<P>
<H4>Multiple Token-Ring Networks</H4>
The last example of a traditional network shows a 16Mbps Token-Ring
configuration capable of supporting up to 20 simultaneous multimedia
sessions.  Again, this configuration can be expanded by adding
additional rings and interfaces up to the maximum capacity of the
server and its software.

<IMG SRC="tek5fig4.gif">

<P>
<H4>Switched Ethernet Network</H4>
The next example shows a switched Ethernet network.  It shows a network
capable of supporting some 96 simultaneous sessions.  Its layout
differs from 10BaseT Ethernet in that it uses multiple high-speed links
(such as FDDI) from the hub to the server, and the connections from the
hub to the workstations are not shared.

<IMG SRC="tek5fig5.gif">

<P>
Many of the newer networks have the same physical appearance as
traditional networks.  For example, Fast Ethernet has the same general
layout as 10BaseT Ethernet, the only difference being the speed of the
hub and of the network interfaces.  Similarly, FDDI looks like a
Token-Ring network, but uses optical fiber as its media, and uses
special hubs and interfaces.  An ATM network, while using different
hubs and interfaces, has the same physical layout as 10BaseT Ethernet.


