<HEAD>
<TITLE>Higher Education and the NII - From Vision to Reality</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Higher Education and the NII - From Vision to Reality</H2>
<H4>by William H. Graves</H4><HR>

<H3>Track B: Networked Applications</H3>

<H4>Report</H4>

<P>Track B’s papers represent a rich and diverse mix of experiences and perspectives. A common theme nevertheless emerged from the eclectic discussion based on these papers and the plenary Track B presentation: the Global Information Infrastructure (GII - Internet) enables higher education to extend its services beyond its present reach. Higher education can be a growth industry!  

<P>Today’s Internet infrastructure already provides global access to some of higher education’s resources and thereby affords higher education the opportunity to extend its services beyond the reach of traditional academic infrastructure - and thus to become a growth industry. The social and technological fabric for such growth is fast emerging, as the following observations reveal:

<OL>
<LI>The rapid growth of the home market for PCs and Internet-connected commercial network access services is well documented. This suggests that most homes in the developed world will have intelligent access to the GII by the end of the decade.  

<LI>The World Wide Web and its cross-platform browser tools are likely to evolve into the dominant network access paradigm, even as the architecture of the Web is transformed to scale better to meet the demands of exponential success.  

<LI>The rapid growth of the standards-based intelligent infrastructure cited above will raise public expectations for the networked delivery of educational services, whether provided by today’s educational enterprise or by new, for-profit educational ventures. Web standards can be the foundation for a broad-based, commodity approach to the delivery of educational materials and programs, a possibility that has been noticed by the commercial sector.</OL>

<P>If higher education is to remain a keystone in the social and economic development of a global democratic community, it must embrace the benefits to be derived through the transformational technologies of the GII, identify the barriers to these beneficial changes, and overcome these barriers through communal action.   

<H4>Benefits</H4>

<P>Internetworking is amplifying. The resources of one networked institution or individual are amplified and enriched by those of others on the net. Anytime, anyplace asynchronous communications and anyplace synchronous communications can dramatically improve the social fabric for human communication and collaboration. This is the basis for the opportunity for higher education to become a growth "industry."  

<P>Many scholarly and research communities long ago (in network time) realized the collaborative benefits of e-mail and listservs and are now realizing the benefits of the Web as a medium for dissemination. As the Web becomes more interactive with the introduction of new development tools, such as Java, the network "collaboratory" can gain functionality and mature into a infrastructure for instruction and learning. Learning includes not only the student learning associated with instruction, but also the expert learning (research and scholarship) that is the basis for our evolving understanding of the human condition and the scientific and technological advances that fuel society’s economic engines.  

<P>Instruction is currently more dependent on time (the class schedule) and place (the classroom) than are research and public service. The time and place dependencies of the contact-hour model dampen the impact of technology overlays on today’s instructional practices, which therefore are a target of maximum opportunity for the application of the anytime, anyplace technologies of internetworking. The opportunity is to utilize the GII to mitigate the expensive infrastructure of the campus-bound classroom and the labor-intensive lecture and, in the process increase access to instruction while containing its cost. Increasing access and containing costs will be hollow benefits if the quality of students’ learning is not increased or at least maintained. The time is right to demonstrate that all three are possible in a way that scales to meet today’s public expectations and fiscal realities.

<H4>Barriers</H4>

<P>Higher education is viewed by many today as a learned society, inwardly focused by its academic self-interests and too often unresponsive to the needs of society. Yet a knowledge economy must rest on an outwardly focused academic enterprise responsive in an affordable way to the educational needs of a learning society and capable of tailoring its services to meet those needs as they evolve in times of rapid change. If higher education is to meet the needs of a learning society, it must replace its one-size-fits-all instructional and public service offerings with more flexible services that can be customized to meet individual needs and changing circumstance. From a customer perspective, academic infrastructure and practices appear to be teacher- and institution-centered. Today’s academic infrastructure must be transformed into a service and learning infrastructure as the foundation for a modular, more flexible set of educational services. Existing barriers to change, such as those noted below, must be recognized and lowered.

<P><OL>
<LI>Computers connected to the GII are not yet pervasive in colleges and universities and the communities they serve. Computers and network infrastructure, like telephones and the telephone network, must be personally accessible to all of higher education’s constituents to be useful. Success will require annualized funding for information technology, an understanding of the economics of networking infrastructure and services, and the participation of the commercial sector.  

<P><LI>Higher education must remove today’s barriers to collaboration if institutional investments in networking are to pay maximum dividends. Colleges and universities are accustomed to associating and cooperating but have little experience in planned collaboration involving shared investments with contractual responsibilities and deliverables. Geopolitical boundaries are antithetical to the effectiveness and efficiency of networking, and so collaboration generally should be planned around programmatic needs rather than geopolitical boundaries. Existing geopolitical arrangements, however, may make joint investments easier. For example, purposeful shared investments within state systems could be especially effective as state political leaders issue new calls for accountability and educational productivity.

<P><LI>Higher education has honed its instinct for inertia over the years. Now is the time to find ways to amplify for the common institutional good the individual entrepreneurial innovation that persists on campuses everywhere. Higher education must begin now to experiment with new service models, especially new instructional models that compete with the prevailing, comfortable contact-hour model by taking advantage of new asynchronous and synchronous communication technologies to extend the reach and productivity of instructors. The flexibility and leverage of the GII can be used to transform the education market into a commodity market for those wanting "education on demand." Whether a commodity market develops in education or not, institutions must awaken to the possible consequences of students being able to customize their education by assembling courses from a global market basket of suppliers.  

<P><LI>There are too few faculty and institutional development programs designed to meet the challenges and opportunities inherent in the GII and its impact on funding patterns and societal expectations. Many faculty will need help in learning to use the network and in rethinking the currently dominant lecture model to take advantage of the network and its shareable resources. A few will become developers of immersive learning materials for sharing with others, whether on a commercial or inter-institutional basis.  

<P><LI>There are no high level standards-based tools for developing interactive Web content and networked processes for managing distributed curricula and instructional programs. Such tools will be needed to create a market for distributed instruction.  </OL>

<H4>Recommendations</H4>

<P>Several recommendations for social change within the academy are implicit in the above discussion of barriers. It is the last barrier cited above, however, that directly intersects Track B’s focus on network applications and that is the basis for two recommendations that fall within the scope of action of the conference’s sponsors.  

<P>The Web currently provides access primarily to resources created in the rather static HTML format. New, more interactive networked applications will be required to create a distributed environment for: 1) guided, immersive self study; 2) managed asynchronous communication and collaboration; 3) real-time (synchronous) collaboration and application sharing among learners, instructors, and researchers; and 4) managed networked instructional and public service offerings. The Web phenomenon, however, suggests that such applications will be developed if access tools and de facto development standards are available to remove the constraints of developing on a particular configuration of hardware and operating system. This observation leads to two related recommendations.

<P><B>Recommendation 1</B> - <I>Investments by governments, foundations, and industry in networked educational applications should focus on open-system (cross-platform) application development tools in order to create a leveraged environment for developing scaleable, networked educational services.</I> Component technologies - building blocks - can encourage a "1,000 flowers to bloom." The foundations for such building blocks are now emerging from the industry in the form of object-oriented development tools and distributed object architectures - Blackbird, Common Point, DSOM, Java, OLE, OpenDoc, Visual Age, to name a few. These generic tools and "standards" will not provide all of the building blocks necessary to create a distributed environment for instruction, research, and public service, even though they likely will solve many problems - authentication, authorization, and security, for example. The new component tools and models, however, can be extended to include the required functionalities. 

<P>Creating networked content materials for learning, for example, will be much easier if generic, cross-platform building blocks and protocols are available to developers. For example, the developer of an application designed to allow students to collect and analyze data from a scientific instrument on the Internet should have access to a networked data sampling tool which recognizes various data protocols, an intelligent plotting window with a variety of display and scaling features, and a tool for passing sampled data to the plotting window. With such tools, the developer could concentrate on developing a networked learning environment incorporating interactive data collection and analysis.  

<P>More generally, the interoperable building blocks required by content developers would include 2- and 3-dimensional graphing templates, mathematical modeling templates, symbolic computation and manipulation engines, a mathematical scripting language, molecular modeling templates, intelligent periodic tables and atomic bonding tools, other science-specific generic functionalities, templates for developing case studies around video clips, tools for glossing texts, tools for synchronizing temporal data (such as music) with related text and images (such as musical scores), bilingual lexical databases and search tools for developing second-language acquisition applications, and many other generic functionalities. There is an equally compelling need for building blocks from which many different applications for managing distributed curricula can be developed.  

<P>The investments in application development building blocks envisioned in this recommendation will bear little fruit unless there is an "open-standards" mechanism in place to provide an interoperability framework and aggregated advice to developers. This is the thrust of the next recommendation.  

<P><B>Recommendation 2</B> - <I>Develop an international open forum to frame and guide the development of application building blocks otherwise not likely to be available for the development of education-specific networked services. </I>The time is right to develop a mechanism to accomplish at the applications level what the Internet Engineering Task Force has accomplished at the transport and middleware levels of the Internet. (Applications must be able to interoperate and take advantage of other resources on the network.) The forum should be organized to ensure the international participation of: 1) leading academic technology organizations, 2) systems and applications companies active in the development of the Web and the GII, 3) federal agencies and foundations with mandates synergistic with the investments envisioned in Recommendation 1. The forum should invite discipline-specific contributions to its work on an as-needed basis. This recommendation is aimed at the organizations sponsoring the conference, especially at EDUCOM. (The leadership of EDUCOM’s National Learning Infrastructure Initiative is on record as favoring the approach captured in these two recommendations.)  

<P>The two recommendations are intended to seed a global market for networked educational services.  

<P>The discussants in Track B believe that education is the engine for global socioeconomic order and progress. They offer their observations and recommendations in the belief that technology-enabled radical change is imminent and that higher education, with help from its non-profit and commercial partners, must participate in that change for the common social good - and for its own good.  

<P><HR>
<P><I>This paper is adapted from the author's article which appeared in "Higher
Education and the NII:  From Vision to Reality," Monterey Conference
Proceedings, September 1995, published by EDUCOM.</I>

<H4>Track B Discussants:</H4>

<UL>
