<HEAD>
<TITLE>A Higher Education Perspective on Network Applications</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>A Higher Education Perspective on Network Applications</H2>
<H4>by William H. Graves</H4>
<HR>

<P>Network applications are playing an increasingly transformational role in higher education. E-mail, listservs, and news groups are connecting far-flung scholars and students into global communities of intensely shared academic interests. The World Wide Web and its client browsers, such as Mosaic and Netscape, are democratizing publication and access to publications at a rate challenging to traditional academic quality assurance mechanisms. But to understand the broadest and deepest implications of network applications for higher education, we must train our eyes on the Web of the future to envision even more than is offered by today’s tools for connecting to remote host applications, communicating asynchronously, publishing information, and searching for information. To look ahead effectively, however, we must be fully aware of the implications for higher education of today’s rapid and often discontinuous social and economic change.

<P>In many industries, the globalization of labor and capital are combining with off-the-shelf component technologies and parts to create fierce competition and shrinking profit margins, thereby squeezing investments in research and development, infrastructure, customer support, and employee benefits. Competition, standardization, and other factors are moving such industries away from traditional one-size-fits-all mass production and toward mass customization. The computer industry is a good example. A commodity market is emerging for customized personal computers selling at a very thin profit margin. Call an 800 number you found in a trade magazine, specify the features you would like in a personal computer, and ask that your new computer be shipped overnight. To understand the analogy in higher education of such industrial mass customization, we must understand higher education’s current mass production practices.  

<P>Although institutional missions are varied and multi-faceted, higher education’s core mission is instruction, especially as it is understood by the public. Variations in class size can be used to create economies of scale or to create more intimate classrooms, but in both cases the lecture dominates the current contact-hour model of instruction. In this sense, the contact-hour model is a one-size-fits-all model mass produced on an infrastructure of classrooms, chalkboards, and rigid class schedules - a teaching infrastructure. The contact-hour model is labor-intensive and especially costly when quality is a concern, for quality is typically associated with small class sizes. Yet its true costs are difficult to grasp because so many cost centers and revenue centers are aggregated together in institutional budgeting. In disaggregating this morass to respond to rising external demands for accountability and cost containment, we should recognize the distinction between instruction aimed, on the one hand, at learning particular skills and bodies of knowledge and, on the other hand, at underpinning the residential undergraduate experience with its goals of socialization and learning to learn. Network applications can be used to mitigate costs in both cases, but the residential undergraduate experience will continue to be expensive because of its residential nature and the presupposition that students are willing to pay for comprehensive four-year courses of study bundled to certify accomplishment in a major as added value to a general education. (An attendant question in today’s socioeconomic climate is whether the residential undergraduate experience will fall from grace as a public good and become a luxury available only to the affluent.)  

<P>Not all students are interested solely, if at all, in a residential experience. Many express tightly focused, self-selected learning objectives as consumers of instruction. This is especially the case with "non-traditional" learners and "life-long" learners who may have legitimate educational needs not easily accommodated by either the time-and-place constraints of traditional campus-based study or the four-year bundling of general education and the major. Since networked applications can be designed to disintermediate support for instruction, its management, and the assessment of its outcomes, higher education has a new opportunity to customize educational opportunities to meet students’ self-selected needs. If we diffuse information technology throughout our institutions and share it wisely across institutions, we can simultaneously increase the quality of learning, increase access to instruction, and contain the costs of instruction. These three holistic goals and the new technology-enabled opportunities to mass customize instruction are at the heart of EDUCOM’s National Learning Infrastructure Initiative.  

<P>As a conduit for change, the Global Information Infrastructure (Internet) raises fundamental questions for me as a faculty member reflecting on the rising socioeconomic expectation for increased instructional productivity. How can I use the leverage of the network to optimize the impact of the time that I spend communicating with students? Will new network applications allow me to reach more students tomorrow as effectively, more flexibly, and with the same commitment of time as I do today? What ultimately will be the best use of my time with students? Where is technology taking teaching?

<P>We have known for some time that the stand-alone multimedia computer can be deployed effectively as an immersive learning environment. The award-winning <A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/demos/nouvelle.html">Nouvelles Dimensions</A> (<A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/faculty/noblitt.html">J. Noblitt</A> and others for Heinle & Heinle Publishers of Boston) demonstrated at this conference provides an excellent example in the context of second language acquisition. Now we can also glimpse the emergence of a learning infrastructure in the example of a Web-accessible library of interactive (immersive) modules for learning introductory mathematical topics. This <A HREF="http://ike.engr.washington.edu/mathwright/">Mathwright Library</A> (J. White and others for the Institute for Academic Technology), also demonstrated at this conference, is available on the Web. But a network library of immersive learning modules is not the sole ingredient for successful instruction any more than is a textbook or today’s campus library. We need networked course management tools, such as those emerging from Miami-Dade Community College and its partners in <A HREF="http://www.mdcc.edu/synergy/">Project Synergy</A>.  We also need networked tools to assess learning in order to ease the labor of grading. Together with today’s asynchronous communication and publication tools, such network applications can support for-credit learning while mitigating the need for classrooms, lectures, and rigid, time-defined measures of academic success - the contact hour, the semester, and the four-year degree. Emerging building-block (component) technologies, such as Java and OpenDoc, allow us to create these kinds of network applications and, thus, to modularize both content and instructional practice. We have many opportunities to reflect on the meaning of mass customization in instruction.  

<P>A learning infrastructure, then, must support modular, distributed instruction, a concept already at work in today’s video-dominated distance education model. But we must understand the differences between computer networks and video networks if new instructional models are to scale in ways that respond to the growing demand for cost containment. The primary difference between computer (data) networking and video networking is not video itself. After all, we can capture, store, and retrieve video in digital form across computer networks - video on demand. The critical difference is that a real-time video network, as typically deployed for distance education, is time dependent with interconnections mediated by humans. The resources for a teleclass or teleconference are scarce and must be negotiated and scheduled, and the time-dependent interconnections among the participating sites must be managed by a technician. In contrast, a student at a computer connected to a computer network can have access any time to any available resource on the network, and this access is mediated by computers without additional human intervention. In short, the Internet model of inter-networking scales more readily than today’s (real-time) interactive video model, and we should remember this significant difference as we blend these two technologies into new distributed instructional environments.

<P>The changes portended by new educational network applications are changes that will require new policies and investment patterns at the institutional level and beyond if flexible, scaleable, and affordable educational practices are to emerge. Policy makers and academic leaders must understand that the computer lab, although necessary in the short term to guarantee network access to all students, is not the end game. Like the phone booth, the computer lab is only a safety net in the quest to ensure personal access to every member of the academic community. Similarly, the technology-enabled classroom is only a starting point in navigating the transition from the prevailing campus-based teaching infrastructure to a global learning infrastructure. Even the centrality of the four-year degree may be eclipsed by a more flexible portfolio concept of certification which emphasizes learning outcomes, de-emphasizes time on task, and is less friendly to dogged persistence toward degree with a grade of C. "Collabotition" - competition based on pre-competitive collaboration - will have to prevail. Colleges and universities have learned to associate but have little experience with the kind of shared-risk investments required to develop distributed instructional resources. Networks do not respect geopolitical boundaries, and so higher education will have to learn to accept transfer credits and to share the high costs of application development and delivery infrastructure for networked instructional materials and processes. If textbook publishers do not learn to utilize network technologies to shift their costs from back-loaded production, marketing, and distribution processes to front-loaded application development, then higher education itself may have to learn to invest consciously and effectively in curriculum development rather than in curriculum delivery.

<P>If we believe that the goal of instruction is learning, then these remarks, which have focused on instruction, apply equally to two other expressions of the learning theme: research and public service. Learning, whether by the student or the researcher, must be quality assured and credited. In a distributed model, this will require new tools for authoring and delivering content, managing curricula, managing intellectual property, managing interactions, sharing data (whiteboard), and visualizing data. Such tools have been available to selected researchers in limited form for some time. Now these tools can be broadly available and easy to use. Access to tools and authentic data will no longer differentiate the scholar from the student, and the theme of learning can unify the islands in the educational enterprise.  

<P>Our opportunity is to utilize network technologies to amplify the impact of higher education and to position higher education in the public mind, not as an inwardly focused learned society, but as the intellectual cornerstone of an emerging knowledge society - a learning society - in which instruction, research, and public service are growth "industries." Whether or not we seize this opportunity, commercial education providers are sure to take advantage of the growing presence in the home of networked personal computers. Higher education’s competitive advantage lies in its seminal contributions to the Internet and its embedded World Wide Web. Our collegial problem-solving approach to inter-networking led to de facto standards for the transport layer, the middleware layer, and the presentation layer (Web) of the Internet. With component technologies now emerging to enhance the utility of the Web beyond the locate-and-display capabilities of today’s Web browsers, the time is right to craft a collegial approach to creating a set of sharable application building blocks for enhancing the Web as an open framework for distributed instruction, research, and public service. This is the challenge to those conference participants interested in the future of network applications and attuned to the related papers published elsewhere in this volume.
<P><HR><P>
<I>This paper is adapted from the author's article which appeared in "Higher Education and the NII: From Vision to Reality," Monterey Conference Proceedings, September 1995, published by EDUCOM. </I>
<P>

