<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cognitive Approaches to Listening Comprehension</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Cognitive Approaches to Listening Comprehension</H2>
<H4>by James S. Noblitt, Ph.D.</H4>
<P>
<HR>
<P>

<P><CENTER><I>In the mind of the beginner, there are many possibilities.
<BR>In the mind of the expert, there are few.</I>
<P><I>- Zen saying</I></CENTER>

<P>
<H3>Introduction</H3>
<P>I have always been impressed with how much more native speakers hear in their own language than I do.  The participants in a conversation, with nodding heads and animated faces, seem to process everything with ease.  The outsider, even with advanced language training, struggles to keep up.  For members of the culture, much is taken for granted and important communications take place without explicit linguistic reference.  To the novice, the flow of speech seems continuous, with no clear indication of even the boundaries of meaningful elements.  It seems there is not enough time to process the current input before the next utterance is presented to the ear.
	
<P>Instructors know, of course, that listening comprehension is a classic "learn-by-doing" task.  The learner must adopt the strategy of listening for key elements around which to construct meaning, all the way moving along with the flow of discourse.  In reader mode, of course, one may rescan the text to solve difficulties, since the reader controls how information reaches the eyes.  Listening is really quite different.  (You may read from left to right, but you can't listen from left to right!)  The instructor can not effectively ask the student to "listen faster," nor does study of vocabulary and grammar per se produce direct improvement in hearing at the rate native speakers speak.  Practice with tape recordings of spontaneous speech can be useful, but students report that it is difficult to maintain concentration for more than a brief period of time.  In any case, listening labs have not produced particularly dramatic improvement in comprehension.  Even when well designed, most tape recordings offer little opportunities for interaction; and once the content of a tape recording is understood, it offers no opportunity to rehearse rapid comprehension of novel utterances.
	
<P>Part of the problem, in my opinion, is that materials for listening comprehension are often designed as if hearing were solely an acoustic phenomenon.  With this understanding of the issue, producers of pedagogical materials take care to adhere to studio recording conditions.  Their objective is to eliminate background noise and emphasize ideal pronunciation to reduce what is considered undesirable variation in input.  In real life, of course, people talk at the same time, ambient noise masks speech sounds, and people do not pronounce words as consistently as the written language would lead us to believe.  Missing acoustic signals are more than compensated for by situational and contextual elements in the speech event.  Although acoustically enhanced recordings are extremely useful for establishing norms, they do not provide practice in dealing with the redundant signals of everyday, situational, listening comprehension.
	
<P>Relying on classroom exposure for situationally based listening comprehension is likewise constrained in presenting variation in the speech sample.  Students who become comfortable with an individual teacher's speech may resist changing to another instructor, even though variation in input is obviously an intrinsic part of learning to understand a foreign language.  Clearly, the learner must learn to distinguish what elements of linguistic input remain the same and which are different when there is variation in acoustic input, such as the speaker's age, gender, regional accent, style, or speech register.  These differences in speech input are essential ingredients of the learning environment.  A single instructor, no matter how talented, cannot provide the needed variation in sampling for proficient listening.
	
<P>On the other hand, simply dropping the student into an environment where nothing but authentic speech is available doesn't solve the problem either.  In the worst case, students who do not succeed begin to assume that they have no aptitude for language learning and drop out of instruction.  Immersion techniques require a lot of time on task and a lot of individual feedback so that the student can confirm or reject the countless interpretations available for raw speech percepts.  There is little provision for this process in most academic programs of language instruction.  It is an often heard comment among professionals that listening comprehension is a "neglected skill."

<H3>Cognitive Elements of Comprehension</H3>
	
<P>It is interesting to note that those who have addressed the listening comprehension problem (e.g., Stevick 1976, Brown 1980, Hatch 1983) take pains to point out that the qualitative aspects of practice are extremely significant.  That is, more is not always better, particularly if drill is based on rote learning procedures; for even if adequate speech samples are available, much more is involved in learning to understand what someone is saying, even in one's native language.  People "hear" what may be totally lacking in the acoustic input, principally because a significant portion of what people understand is supplied by the context of the speech event.  Native speakers draw on vast amounts of shared knowledge to construct meaning when they are listening.  It is not so much that the speech sounds "contain" meaning; it is rather that the speech sounds trigger meaning in the minds of the listener.  It is in this sense that we may speak of listening comprehension as being essentially cognitive, drawing on support from a number of sources available for general intelligence.
	
<P>Far from being a "passive" skill, listening requires the active creation of plausible messages from sometimes incomplete acoustic input.  As an example, consider this scene in which the husband, changing TV channels, comes across an old film that shows a very young Cary Grant in his first movie.  Relying chiefly on the actor's voice quality, the husband recognizes the actor and asks his wife (who is reading) to look at the screen.  She studies the screen for a moment before realizing who the actor is.  Here is the transcript of the actual exchange:
	
<P><DT><I>Example 1:  Telegraphic Speech
<DD>Husband:	Look, that's, uh...
<DD>Wife:	Oh.  Yes.</I>

<P>The reader can easily fill in the missing elements by assuming that both wife and husband share knowledge of the actor's movie career, that neither has seen the actor's first movie, and that the husband has a temporary lapse of memory concerning the actor's name (but she knows he knows who it is).
	
<P>The ability to fill in missing information, a commonplace in human behavior, has been termed "analysis by synthesis" by psychologists.  (See Clark and Clark 1977, especially Chapter 5, "Perception of Speech.")  The term refers to the strategy of internally generating or "shadowing" what people are saying (or doing) so that we may easily predict the next step, or at least reduce the number of possibilities to consider.  If you speak very slowly or deliberately, you may find that others do more than shadow: they actually finish sentences for you.  We take time to use our full processing capacity only when the situation is highly unusual or unexpected.  Without this kind of efficient information processing, we can easily become overwhelmed by input, which of course is exactly the situation the language learner is in.
	
<P>We deal with sensory overload by creating internal representations of the outside world so that we may deal more efficiently with information.  With learning, we cut down on processing time through a mechanism called "feedforward."  The physiological basis for this ability, the gamma efferent system, is a relatively recent discovery by brain specialists (Pribram 1971).  The phenomena accounted for by the discovery are very familiar, however.  Our nervous system allows us to anticipate, after learning, the various kinds of feedback that may reach the brain through the sensory system.  As long as no change from the norm is encountered, we notice very little, at least consciously.  A simple example is how the body adjusts to ambient temperature.  (The water is fine once you get in.)
	
<P>Although difficult to describe objectively, there is a mild discomfort or malaise felt when an unexpected sensation is experienced.  For example, I enter an elevator, press "down," and prepare unconsciously to descend.  A prior call, however, causes the elevator to go up instead, and I momentarily feel a kind of disequilibrium.  Much the same feeling is experienced when, in reality, I have reached the top of the stairway but, in the dark, I expect there to be another stair.  Likewise, a startling sensation is produced if I sit in a chair that is softer than expected.  I have even noticed an odd feeling when walking up an escalator that is under repair.  Although I can easily observe that it is not moving, I still feel motion as I step on.  These examples offer a generalization: In each case the feedback simply does not match the feedforward.
	
<P>Cognitive psychologists are quick to point out that we carry within our central nervous system a kind of "map" of the external world that we refer to continuously as we process information in our surroundings.  Cognitive maps offer redundant ways of dealing with problems in everyday life, from finding our way in the dark to opening a door with our arms full of groceries.  Highly skilled activities, such as playing a musical instrument from a printed score, require a kind of "fusion" of various representations of the music.  Even the amateur pianist can "hear" music in his or her head (its acoustic form), or "see" the notation of a familiar composition (its symbolic form), or "play" the motions of the fingers (its motor form).
	
<P>Similar effects of analysis by synthesis can be observed in the way humans process speech.  Most of what we recall is not retrieved from stored "tapes" of acoustic material; it is rather based on reconstructed "scenarios" that are consistent with what we have observed and learned.  Psychologists who have studied eye-witness testimony offer powerful evidence that memory is more a constructive process than a physical "thing."  Anyone who has played the parlor trick of passing a story from person to person around the room is impressed at the number of creative changes that occur as each intelligence reinterprets the input according to personal knowledge and bias.  A particularly interesting finding is that information that does not fit the cognitive schemata of the listener is simply not processed.  Experimenters have inserted an extraneous sentence into an otherwise coherent story to test recall of the intrusive element.  Most do not remember that it was even present in the narrative!
	
<P>A number of strategies have been identified by psycholinguists to account for the way humans process speech.  Although we teach grammar for a good understanding of syntactic parsing, there is good evidence that native speakers also use, perhaps even prefer, "semantic parsing" in their everyday listening comprehension.  That is, listeners simply fit content words to a scenario that they can easily construct from their knowledge of the world and society.  Some of the grammatical cues to meaning may not be actively processed if the message is thought to be understood because of the general meaning and context.  This strategy causes trouble only if precision is essential (as in the courtroom) or if hypothesis formation and deduction of meaning are required (as in scientific debate).
	
<P>Utterances taken out of context are often said to be misunderstood, especially if the syntactic structure is complex.  You may wish to try reading the following sentence to a colleague and then asking for an interpretation of the context that it refers to:
	
<P><I><DT>Example 2: Semantic Parsing
<DD>Since the doctor was not examined by the patient,
<DD>her lawyer filed a malpractice suit.</I>

<P>If the sentence is read hastily, it is possible to reconstruct a scenario in which the patient sued the doctor for malpractice:
		
<P><DD><I>doctor / not examine / patient / lawyer / sue</I>

<P>In reality, the syntactic structure offers a more complex and unexpected scenario:
		
<P><DD><I>patient / not examine / doctor / lawyer (whose?) / sue</I>
	
<P>Semantic parsing is often quite satisfactory for getting the gist of a narrative, especially when visual support or pragmatic constraints assist in the analysis.  Children (and second language learners), over time, also learn how to add syntactic parsing to their repertoire of strategies for arriving at meaning.  I recall a scene in which my daughter, about five years old, was reproached for using the guest towels to dry her hands.  When asked to explain why the towels were dirty, she defended herself in the following way:
		
<P><DD><I>I washed my hands because I dried them on the towel!</I>

<P>You have only to substitute the word "and" in place of the word "because" for the sentence to make perfect sense.  (That is, replace the subordinating conjunction, which would require a shift in the clause structure, with a coordinating conjunction that retains the clauses in the order of temporal events.)  Her attempted shift from semantic to syntactic structures to express causation was apparently more than my daughter could handle under the circumstances.
	
<P>A great deal of the skill in precise reading lies in the ability to make a correct syntactic parse, but a visual representation is naturally not available to the ear for rescanning, as is the case with the visual system.  Effective speakers use rhetorical devices to repeat important information and enlarge upon the imagery available to the hearer, whereas effective writers may exploit the more stable visual medium for effect (Ong 1982).  The lesson here is that complex structures (passive negatives with ambiguous scope of reference) make for bad writing and impossible listening.  We appear to rely on our store of likely images to mediate in the process of interpreting what we hear.  When these are lacking, we may fail altogether to make sense of the input.
	
<H3>Cues to Listening Comprehension</H3>
	
<P>Using the written word as a support for listening comprehension for learners has distinct limitations.  For one thing, the learner may skip to the text whenever a difficulty is encountered in hearing, and thus never learn to rely on the ear for information.  For another, there are cues available for the ear, such as intonation, that have no representation in writing.  Children begin to repeat the tune of language well before they master vocabulary and syntax.  It is as if humans find it easier to learn the music than the words; over time, however, the two become paired in an intimate way.  An easy example for speakers of English is to try to communicate by humming the words of a set phrase, such as "I don't know."  Most speakers will know exactly what you "said," if uttered as an answer to a content question, such as "What are you going to do?"
	
<P>A little more difficult exercise consists of trying to mismatch intonation and content.  The effect is a bit surreal, as the utterance will sound both familiar and strange at the same time.  For example, try the following exchange in you mind's ear: 
		
<P><DD><I>"Excuse me."
<DD>"You're welcome."</I>

<P>It may take a moment to realize that the intonation contours for "Thank you." / "You're welcome." and "Excuse me." / "No problem." can be identical.  Routine or frequently repeated phrases often become "stylized" in this way.  The point is that the redundant clues offered in the melodic structure of speech assist enormously in processing spoken language.  The printed word, obviously, is not the appropriate medium for learning to process intonation.
	
<P>Another example may help make the point, as well as relate intonation cues to acoustic processing through analysis by synthesis.  One evening, while listening to public broadcast radio at Cornell University, I noticed that the announcer used a particular intonation for reporting tie scores (which are rather common in hockey).  You may wish to rehearse the effect, noting that an unequal score, (e.g., Boston 3, Pittsburgh 2) does not sound the same as a tie score (e.g., Boston 3, Pittsburgh 3).  As Cornell was in the running for first place that particular year, I listened for the results and was surprised to note that I knew the game result well before (in milliseconds) the number was actually said.
	
<P><I><DT>Example 3: Meaning and Intonation
<DD>Uneven - Princeton 4, Brown 2
<DD>Uneven - Dartmouth 2, Columbia 1
<DD>Tie - Harvard 3, Cornell  ?</I>

<P>(If you wish to produce an unsettling effect on the listener, try reading an uneven score with tie score intonation, or vice-versa.  The information will be hard for others to process.)  Note that the "tie score" intonation is used in other utterances that contain information that is considered identical, such as "If Mary is for it, John is for it."
	
<P>The culturally determined associations available to native speakers as they listen to one another mediate comprehension in ways that the outsider cannot fully understand.  I recall an instance in which the transcribers of a Spanish conversation recorded the phrase, "Me llamo Elgar."  At least two others (including myself) confirmed the transcription, hearing clearly the acoustic sequence [ e l g a r ].  A native speaker immediately rejected the transcription, saying it should be [ e d g a r ].  We all listened again intently, trying to determine whether the sound in question was [ l ] or [ d ].  Finally our exasperated informant declared that the man's name was "Edgar" because "Elgar" does not exist in Spanish!  And that was that.
	
<P>A last example is offered as an illustration of the surprising role of cognition in the most routine processing of acoustic input.  The context is a situation in which a football game is playing in the background, barely attended to by others in the room because of preparations for a Thanksgiving meal.  The announcer says, in a matter of fact tone, the following:
	
<P><DT><I>Example 4:  Meaning and Rhythm
<DD>Over the middle and through the line, a penalty on the play.</I>

<P>Non-native speakers are to be forgiven if they do not "hear" what immediately came to my mind, no doubt because of the season of the year:
		
<P><DD><I>Over the river and through the woods, to Grandmother's house we go.</I>

<P>It turns out that the rhythmic structure of the two utterances is identical.  There is a familiar song associated with the line of verse that most members of my culture would recognize immediately.  
	
<P>Naturally the shared cultural associations illustrated by the example above are just the tip of the iceberg.  The rich array of material that mediates in comprehension of acoustic input, from childhood songs to works of art, should remind us of the depth of  training necessary for truly proficient listening comprehension.  But surely there is not enough instructional time to attend to such a vast curricular undertaking!  How can we provide our students with a learning environment that provides appropriate skills for going beyond acoustic input?

<H3>Multimedia and Listening Comprehension</H3>
	
<P>Current advances in computer-aided instruction offer some straightforward solutions to the problems sketched above.  Taking our cue from research in language learning, we should take care to augment our curriculum-based teaching program with a corpus-based learning environment.  This means that students must have access to authentic material if they are to develop appropriate feedforward mechanisms.  Computers support a meaningful learning environment for listening comprehension by combining visual, auditory, and textual information with interactivity.  Visual support is extremely efficient for providing context and for maintaining interest; textual information (for the literate) is an economical way to provide conceptual support.  Interactivity is extremely important, for students must have control of the rate of information presentation if they are to maintain comprehension when using authentic materials.
	
<P>In my analysis (Noblitt 1993), an adequate learning environment requires support of at least three modes of learning, which may be successfully enhanced by the use of computers.
<OL>
<LI>The sequential mode, familiar to anyone who has designed a syllabus, provides for a linear presentation of information and takes the student to areas that would not be discovered by browsing or other adventitious means.  Samples of speech, song, or works of literature are also sequential, but designed primarily for the expressive rather than analytical use of language.
<LI>The relational mode, familiar to anyone who has used reference works such as dictionaries or maps, provides support for tasks that are open-ended and that require critical thinking.  The gathering of relevant material for the task at hand is driven by student query.  The information thus acquired takes on meaning by its power to solve problems by analytical means.
<LI>The creative mode, involved in improvisational speech or original writing, provides support for learning-by-doing.  Often viewed as the primary objective of language study, the creative mode is essential for instruction stressing communicative competence.</OL>
	
<P>Interactive learning environments can easily incorporate the learning modes described above.  Students may comfortably observe the context of an utterance and process holistically all the redundant cues in the visual and acoustic modes.  At the same time they have recourse on demand to relational databases of information in textual form that supports analytical processing and creative use of language.  (See Noblitt 1995 for an example of an interactive multimedia application designed to assist the learner in listening comprehension.)
	
<P>An important motivational feature can be built in with authentic samples of speech and full-motion video.  The material provides an opportunity to observe the expressive use of language.  That is, students can observe the use of language that reflects esthetic, ethical, or cultural values in addition to purely the communicative or informational intent of an utterance.  Although the linguistic material is more complex in content, such examples of language use provide the student with insights that make language study engaging and rewarding.  Information technology provides an excellent medium for balancing the analytic or form-focused study of language with a synthetic or content focused learning environment.
	
<P>The question of balance in language skills is important.  Many of our students have learned well to perform in the sense of repeating a dialogue with tolerable accuracy.  However, the learner's attempt to enter into an authentic conversation may result in the awkward discovery that his or her ability to speak is not matched by an equal ability to hear.  That is, it is easier to ask a question than it is to understand the answer!  "Natural" approaches provide for balance by allowing for developmental staging in skill acquisition.  As shown by the following sample from child language acquisition, it is normal for listening comprehension to precede spoken ability.
	
<P><DT><I>Example 5:  Hearer and Speaker
<DD>What's your name?
<DD>Litha.
<DD>Litha?	
<DD>No! Litha.
<DD>Lisa?
<DD>Yeah.  Litha.</I>

<P>What elements in the learning environment assist the learner in gaining skill in processing both the cognitive and acoustic elements of listening?  Above all, the learner needs to deal with authentic samples of language in context.  Since native speakers of a language appear to listen more to the speaker's intent than raw acoustic input, it is important for the learner to appreciate how intended meaning is negotiated in another language.  (See Kramsch 1993, passim, and especially p.196, "The challenge of multimedia.")  Intent is informed by an elaborate set of cultural assumptions that are part and parcel of learning the elemental facts of a foreign language.  By observing visual and linguistic sensory inputs, the student is able to arrive inductively at intention .  The increased complexity of input through interactive multimedia thus enhances cognitive processing and renders the task meaningful.
<P><HR>
