<HEAD>
<TITLE>Scholarship, Publishing and Computing:  Interactions in the Educational Marketplace</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Scholarship, Publishing and Computing:  Interactions in the Educational Marketplace</H2>
<H4>by James S. Noblitt</H4>
<P><HR><P>
<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>Our mission at the IAT allows us to observe how the public and private sectors come together to discuss ways of doing business.  We note that the notion of value as applied to information technology in education takes different forms as we compare the contributions of the academy, publishers and the computing industry to educational innovation.  Scholars want to see evidence of added value in research and teaching before adopting technology; publishers want to see evidence of demand before investing in the production of quality products; technology vendors want to see a market for their goods and services before adapting to the demands of the educational marketplace.  Each has a viewpoint concerning inhibitors to the adoption of technology, but there appears to be little realization of the mutual dependencies involved.

<H3>The Profit Motive</H3>

<P>Attitudes toward "profit" represent a major cultural difference separating educators from the publishing and computing industries.  The lack of understanding on this point constitutes an inhibitor to the adoption of technology.  The not-for-profit education industry draws heavily on public and philanthropic support to accomplish its mission, thus scholars are not accustomed to assessing the economic value of activities such as instructional computing in higher education.  As one analyst puts it, "There is no metric in higher education comparable to money in business, and no goal comparable to profits . . . [As a result,] the accountability techniques of the business corporation are of little benefit to the education purposes of higher education."  (R. Birnbaum, How Colleges Work:  The Cybernetics of Academic Organization and Leadership, Jossey-Bass Publisher, 1988) 
 
<P>Within higher education, the concept of accountability techniques represents sharply differing concepts in the minds of educators focused on the outcomes of education and in the minds of administrators focused on the financial health of their institution.  Since the for-profit sector is more attuned to a business case than a plan for curriculum reform, it is not surprising that industry representatives have been more comfortable talking with administrators than with faculty.  However, the successful salesperson in publishing or the computer industry must learn to appreciate the concerns of the various clients in higher education: faculty attuned to what is valued by their particular discipline, computer support personnel interested in state- of-the-art technology,  and administrators searching for efficient solutions for instruction.
  
<P>There is little wonder that the dialogue between the private and public sectors has only begun to address the serious issues in curriculum reform raised by the new information technology.  But even here there are surprises.  Our experience has been that individuals in both the publishing and computing industries are highly sensitive to the qualitative issues facing education.  After all, our business leaders have all been through the system and hold opinions based on direct experience.  Given opportunity and encouragement, they participate fully in the intellectual debate concerning the role of education in our culture.  Publishers seek opportunities for leadership in quality control and distribution of educational materials; technologists seek opportunities for leadership in innovative design of hardware and software.  The tragedy is that we have not found the means to bring their collective knowledge and expertise to bear on the educational problems confronting our society.

<H3>The Matter of Timing</H3>

<P>Quite apart from the differing cultural points of view on what to do about implementing educational technology, there is a more subtle issue about when innovation is likely to be successful.   The issue of timing involves educators, publishers and technologists in an intricate dance of mutual dependence.  We shall return to these interconnections in the course of this series, but it will suffice at this time to point out that qualitative issues may render quantitative measures of the value of educational technology relatively meaningless.  Quality depends on timing.  (If something is not worth doing, it’s not worth doing well.)  For example, if the economy requires consolidation, innovation can be extremely disruptive.  If innovation is needed, moneys spent on continuing the status quo are a waste, regardless of the quality metric applied.  (This activity has been called "rearranging the deck chairs on the Titanic.")  The focus must be on what reform is needed and how productive change will take place.

<P>The role of information technology as change agent is complex and far-reaching.  The digital medium solves certain problems brought on by the information age, but it also introduces new ones.  We must, of course, be alert to the consequences of unintended side-effects as the learning environment is transformed.  If we are to take the metaphor of the "information high-way" seriously, we should reflect upon the fact that super-highways led to, among other things, a vast increase in the production of cars! 
 
<P>As we are fond of saying at the IAT, our emphasis must be on learning technology, not on information technology per se.  A major inhibitor in the minds of many educators is the question of the maturity of the new industry.  Without standards for sharing scholarly and pedagogical materials, the benefits of educational computing will be difficult to implement.  Happily, de facto standards appear to be emerging as educators have adopted a "bottom up" approach to materials production.  We are just beginning to see the creation of multimedia authoring and network navigation tools that are driven by genuine educational needs.  And textbook publishers, for example, are now deeply involved in seeking authors who can be creative in the new medium.

<H3>Resistance to Change</H3>

<P>Innovation can be exciting, but it can also be distressing.  We don’t like having to cope with a working environment for which we were not fully trained.  As an academic colleague likes to put it, "All change is bad."  His observation expresses the concern caused by the process of change, even when it is needed.  Change diverts energy from normal standards of productivity into new activities, often with uncertain outcomes.  The new information technology is a symbol of threat to a way of life; it represents the "disconnect" many educators feel between their background and training and the current needs of society.  We must recognize (if only to be able to put the issue aside) that the "information explosion"  redefines the conditions of psychological and economic well-being for ourselves and our students, and ultimately alters the dynamics of teaching and learning.

<P>Many of the elements driving innovation lie outside the direct control of the academy; it is nonetheless important to understand the strategic significance of the commercial sector, in particular the publishing and computing industries.  Educational publishers will bring their expertise to the task of creating materials that are commercially viable, that is, appropriate for broad distribution.  The publisher’s opportunity for leadership lies in underwriting significant software development.  Significant utilization of information technology will be impossible without this important service, simply because material that can’t be shared is not interesting in the scholarly domain.  The "shareware" concept, although attractive philosophically to the not-for-profit sector, generally does not produce high quality applications that can be used in broad educational reform.

<H3>Inhibitors</H3>

<P>Under the current system of rewards, individual faculty members as software developers have no incentive to go beyond proof of concept, much less writing error traps and full documentation.  Field testing, debugging and other steps necessary for commercial-grade applications are not feasible without significant levels of support.  Of course, the debate in academia between applied and theoretical scholarship is much older than the microcomputer.  The academic world, especially in this culture, tends to rate theory above application in its reward structure.  Publishers have long been aware of this fact and have compiled separate author profiles for successful textbook authors in theoretical and applied fields.

<P>New kinds of leadership and support are needed to address some powerful inhibitors.  A new kind of social "covenant" is needed to overcome the powerful inhibitors to change that we have identified here at the IAT.

<UL>
<LI><B>Educators</B> interested in software development are not always accustomed to the idea of team-work; they have been socialized to think "vertically," that is, to work within their own disciplines.  The most successful projects we have observed have joined faculty expertise, administrative leadership, and computer support services.

<LI><B>Publishers</B> face serious problems in making a transition to publishing in the digital medium.  The business case for software development for microcomputers depends critically on the cost of support for cross-platform development, as well as for competing operating systems in various stages of maturity.  Copyright issues are troublesome in the extreme.

<LI><B>The computing industry</B>, for its part, faces difficulties in making a business case for its dealings with higher education.  Because of intense competition, the hardware has dropped in profitability to the commodity level, which means that mass marketing techniques are required for business health.  In the absence of de facto or de jure standards for software design and production, it is difficult to create broad market appeal for a single educational  product.</UL>

<H3>The Need for Innovation</H3>

<P>Professional groups, such as the Textbook Authors Association and consultants to the publishing industry have, for the past four or five years, been developing strategies for diversifying the format of educational offerings.  There are a number of reasons for this activity:  (1) Students are less and less willing to pay the high prices charged for 4-color, illustrated texts.  Those who do buy them sell them back to the book store, and the market in second-hand books has reduced publishers profits.  (2) The industry sees less teacher demand for expensive texts and the ancillary accompanying material, like slides and tapes.  Some instructors prefer "custom" textbooks with no frills, or just-in-time publishing of selected material.  Many instructors hesitate  to require expensive textbooks and prefer to have them put on reserve in the library for their students.  (3) The publishing industry is faced with diversifying its offerings.  The printed textbook does a better job of basic exposition and synthesis -- it remains the preferred medium for reading extended narrative treatment -- but more students have computers, and well-designed multimedia instruction does a better job of instruction in areas like illustration, visualization, and interactivity.  (4) Diversification means that publishers will have to  find new ways for quality control and distribution of their material.  That means that  new "electronic editors" must be found or trained for ensuring good design and content.  New authoring techniques must be found for electronic publishing, and the educational establishment must rethink teacher training.  (5) Educational publishers have noted that their customers are more attracted to content than to medium per se.  That is, students and scholars are happy to deal with information in whatever form best suited for the acquisition of knowledge.  As long as the dynamics of interaction are correct, it does not matter whether the delivery system is book, CD-ROM, or network.

<P>A discussion of the market demand for learning materials would take us well beyond the purpose of this article.  Suffice it to say that the publisher’s business case must take into account who will purchase learning material (teachers, school boards, students) and in what medium (print, film, digital).  But the responsibility for determining the shape of the solution will likely be shared by the educational establishment, the information technology industry, and the publishing industry.  A cooperative effort is needed to produce a meaningful combination of content, platform, and quality control.  The initiative for the effort is likely to be driven by the publishing industry, already accustomed to the use of computing for printing instructional and reference materials as well as network collaboration with authors, editorial consultants, and marketing staff.  Electronic distribution of materials through networks is a logical extension of this process, as the business case suggests possibilities for higher quality, greater access, and lower distribution costs.

<H3>Interactive Learning</H3>

<P>The success of the familiar print textbook was based in part on well-defined roles for author and publisher in its development.  As interest now focuses on interactive learning materials, developers are facing interesting new issues of production, distribution, and quality assurance.  Everyone is for quality, but quality means different things to different people:

<UL>
<LI><B>Administrators</B> are likely to focus on the issues of effectiveness and productivity.  They promote learning environments that improve the quality of education while reducing the costs of implementation.

<LI><B>Faculty</B> are concerned about educational content.  They value interactive materials that provide more student exposure to authentic sources, and they like material that can be easily integrated with existing curricula.  

<LI><B>Computer support personnel</B> are responsible for servicing the high technology learning environment .  They like interactive materials that rest on a solid basis of industry support and for which adequate maintenance is feasible with limited resources.

<LI><B>Publishers</B> think of quality as excellent material produced in a timely fashion.  They need to know if such materials can compete successfully in the marketplace and whether they can absorb the expense of integrating their software offerings with multiple networks, operating systems, and hardware platforms.</UL>

<P>Multimedia materials will not so much replace textbooks as transform them.  Publishers say that the glossy, 4-color textbook with rich ancillary materials has become too expensive  to compete with the relatively cheap CD-ROM medium.  The problem for publishers is how to build a business plan that shifts costs from printing to software development.   In the classical print paradigm manuscript review was one of the least expensive parts of the publishing process.  Not so with software, since the equivalent of a manuscript does not exist until extensive effort (and cost) has been incurred in the application development.  Once a viable product is in hand, however, manufacturing costs are relatively minor.

<P>Educators are generally pleased to see the spectrum of instructional tools broadened to include interactive visual, acoustic, and textual elements.  Compound documents are not only rich in educational content, they also introduce new elements of composition and graphic design for instruction.  Particularly attractive is the fact that the computer makes it possible for the learner to make choices that determine both the kind of material presented and the rate of information flow.  Hypermedia documents open up the ability to follow relationships among ideas.  Timely access to relevant information is intellectually arousing for the student.  These features create a learning environment where the student can interact with more authentic learning material.

<P>Educators are observing that multimedia materials have considerable power to engage students in learning.  Instructors are pleased to see the primary material of their subject matter available to the student for observation and interaction.  These functions go well beyond the ability to entertain, a term that educators associate with the for-profit sector.  The not-for-profit motive of the educational establishment is focused on the long-term achievement of students and is driven by a sense of responsibility for the student and for society.  They wish to see the new technology give wider access to information to their students, freeing them to concentrate on the creative aspects of teaching.

<P>Educators tell us that they value interactive learning environments that allow them to share primary observed data with their students and provide the tools for performing operations on the data.  It is very satisfying for educators to demonstrate to others the interest that their subject matter holds.  A successful demonstration of the methodology of the discipline also lessens the tension that is felt between teaching and research.  Innovations that support these activities generally remove inhibitions to the adoption of technology.

<H3>Conclusion</H3>  
 
<P>Naturally the computing industry needs software to sell its goods; and academics need publishers for product development; but publishers need an installed base for market development.  As they say here in North Carolina, "That dog chases its tail!"

<P>The mutual dependencies discussed in the preceding section can lead to stalemate, or they can lead to creative synergy.  The keys to a positive outcome are participation and communication.  Academics need to analyze how information technology is actually used for educational purposes and inform the computing industry about their needs.  Above all, scholars need to contribute their knowledge to the creation of effective educational materials.

<P>Successful commercialization can serve the interests of all involved.  For example, we have noted at a number of institutions that computers placed in lecture halls are not heavily used.  People only trust one computer, their own.  They need to know its state of configuration and that the files are up to date.  Above all, they need to be assured that it will function reliably and in a timely fashion without extensive set-up time.  This points to personal ownership, which is now feasible with the development of the current class of laptop computers and docking stations.  The laptop permits the educator to keep important material at hand while at home, in the office, or in the classroom.  The same computer serves for the various modes important to the scholarly lifestyle: research, administrative duties, and classroom presentation.  In this model, institutional support is required for communication (e-mail) and classroom display, but not for lab maintenance.  The arrangement may be extended to student computing as well, which makes it possible for some of the costs of life-cycle budgeting to be passed on to the consumer.

<P>Educational publishers, for their part, want to know how to bring  their expertise to the task of creating materials that are commercially viable.  Their opportunity for leadership lies in underwriting significant software development.  The scholarly community will need heavy involvement from the commercial sector if excellent materials are to be created for educational purposes.  If higher education is not involved in this important enterprise, the creation of materials for general education are likely to pass to those who control the mass media. 

<P>Just as the scholarly community will need heavy involvement from the commercial sector for the creation of excellent educational materials, educational publishers will need the participation of scholars in materials design.  If higher education is not involved in this important enterprise, the creation of materials for general education is likely to pass to the mass media specialists with backgrounds in gaming, advertising, and entertainment.  The computing industry, for its part, will need input on lifestyle and content issues at this critical juncture in the development of educational computing.  

<P>Cross-platform and standards-based instructional technology offers a great deal of promise for the educator, if for no other reason than it has capabilities that offer publishers and authors a better chance for wide adoption.
<P><HR><P>
<H3>Copyright Notice</H3>
