<HEAD>
<TITLE>K-12/Higher Education Technology Partnerships</TITLE>
<!-- Created April 1995 by Carolyn Kotlas -->
<!-- Originally created for IAT satellite broadcast "Higher Education/K-12 Connection"  -->
<!-- Last revised: March 28, 1995 -->
<!-- Filename = irg-27.html -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFCE7" TEXT="#00006F">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>K-12/Higher Education Technology Partnerships</FONT></STRONG>
<P>
Compiled by: Carolyn Kotlas, MSLS <BR>
Institute for Academic Technology <BR>
Last revised: March 28, 1995
</CENTER>
<P>
(Note: project descriptions were adapted from the project Web
pages.)
<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>National/Regional Partnership Projects</STRONG></FONT>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Appalachia Educational Laboratory, Inc.</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Appalachia Educational Laboratory is a private, nonprofit
corporation located in Charleston, West Virginia. Supported primarily
by federal funds, AEL provides research and development services
to national, regional, state, and local education agencies. AEL's
mission is to link the knowledge from research with the wisdom
from practice to improve teaching and learning. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.ael.org/about.html" >http://www.ael.org/about.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>ArtsEdge -- Linking the Arts and Education through Technology
</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
ArtsEdge is a cooperative agreement between the National Endowment
for the Arts, U.S. Department of Education, and John F. Kennedy
Center for the Performing Arts, representing an important investment
in the future of the arts in American education. It is meant to
literally place and maintain the arts alongside science, math,
and other subject areas in the warehouses and service stations
that will line the superhighway to education in the 21st Century.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information:<BR>
URL = <A HREF="http://k12.cnidr.org/janice_k12/artsedge/artsedge.html" >http://k12.cnidr.org/janice_k12/artsedge/artsedge.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Collaborative Visualization (CoVis)</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The CoVis Project at Northwestern University is attempting to
transform K-12 science learning to better resemble the authentic
practice of science. The CoVis Project will explore issues of
scaling, diversity, and sustainability as they relate to the use
of networking technologies to enable high school students to work
in collaboration with remote students, teachers, and scientists.
An important outcome of this work will be the construction of
distributed electronic communities dedicated to science learning.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.covis.nwu.edu/CoVis_Welcome.html" >http://www.covis.nwu.edu/CoVis_Welcome.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Earth System Science Community Curriculum</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Earth System Science Community Curriculum, a collaborative
science education initiative funded by NASA, serves to facilitate
interactions and communications among members of the Earth System
Science Community by providing curricula designed to guide student
investigations of the Earth system, and access to data, tips,
techniques and guides, tools, and expert support. Participating
students communicate the findings of their investigations by publishing
hypermedia documentation (what you see here) for review and comment
of the Earth System Science community and the benefit of the general
public. Student are encouraged to use any relevant resources developed
in the process of their investigation in order to communicate
their findings. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.circles.org/index.html" >http://www.circles.org/index.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>ENC -- Eisenhower National Clearinghouse</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The purpose of the Eisenhower National Clearinghouse is to: encourage
the adoption and use of K-12 curriculum materials and programs
which support national goals to improve teaching and learning
in mathematics and science by providing better access to resources
for all who are interested in creating an effective learning environment.
The Clearinghouse will accomplish this by: creating and maintaining
a comprehensive, multi-media collection of materials and programs
which will be distributed in a timely manner through a national
system using both traditional formats and advanced computing and
telecommunications technologies. ENC is part of the Eisenhower
National Program for Mathematics and Science Education in the
Office of Educational Research and Improvement (OERI), U.S. Department
of Education. The five-year contract for ENC was awarded to The
Ohio State University in September 1992. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://enc.org/" >http://enc.org/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Explorer</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Explorer is part of a research and development effort to establish
an on time means of delivering a full range of information resources
to educators and students. The Explorer's graphical user interface
and icons are designed to improve the range of navigation, contributing,
search, and retrieval tools available to educators and students
on the Internet. The Explorer database, including its contents
and organization, is being developed by the Great Lakes Telecommunications
Collaborative and the University of Kansas UNITE group with funding
support from the U.S. Department of Education OERI (Star Schools).
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://unite2.tisl.ukans.edu/" >http://unite2.tisl.ukans.edu/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>FWL -- Far West Laboratory for Educational Research and
Development</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
FWL is a non-profit agency providing educators and policymakers
with information and support based on the best knowledge from
educational research and practice. One of 10 regional educational
laboratories created by Congress in 1966, the Laboratory provides
services and expertise to the education communities in the Far
West region (Arizona, California, Nevada and Utah) and nationally.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.fwl.org/" >http://www.fwl.org/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Global Schoolhouse Project -- Linking Kids Around the World
</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Global Schoolhouse Project was a technology demonstration
project funded in part by the National Science Foundation. The
project was designed to demonstrate the potential of high speed
Internet connectivity in the public school classroom. The Global
Schoolhouse Project officially ended on December 29, 1994. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://k12.cnidr.org/gsh/gshwelcome.html" >http://k12.cnidr.org/gsh/gshwelcome.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>ICS -- Interactive Communications and Simulations</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
ICS is a dynamic program of exciting and innovative educational
exercises. Using accessible telecommunications and computer conferencing,
students can spend part of every school day in a &quot;global
classroom.&quot; A small group of educators at the University
of Michigan form the core of ICS. Working closely with classroom
teachers, they have developed a series of student-centered activities
that have gripped and challenged young people -- from gifted and
talented to the most &quot;at risk&quot; -- throughout the U.S.
and around the world. These exercises are carefully structured
but allow teachers the flexibility to meet their own objectives.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://ics.soe.umich.edu/" >http://ics.soe.umich.edu/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>JEI -- Joint Education Initiative</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
JEI is a National Science Foundation project at the University
of Maryland at College Park under the department of Geology. The
project exists to help assist educators who are interested in
the use of scientific data sets in the classroom. JEI is the interface
between K-12 science educators and the federal, industrial, and
academic science communities. Started at the US Geological Survey
in 1990, the project was transferred to the University of Maryland
in 1991. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="gopher://jei.umd.edu:70/1" >gopher://jei.umd.edu:70/1  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>The Journey North</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Journey North is made up of different themes: the environment,
wildlife migration, different cultures -- and more. While students
share observations on wildlife migration with each other, they
also receive reports from the explorers on their training trip.
The project is a collaboration of the World School for Adventure
Learning at Indiana University, ICS at the University of Michigan,
and Brandon Plewe of the University at Buffalo. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://ics.soe.umich.edu/ed712/IAPIntro.html" >http://ics.soe.umich.edu/ed712/IAPIntro.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>MathMol -- Mathematics and Molecules K-12</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
MathMol is being developed at the NYU/ACF Scientific Visualization
Center in association with the NYU Collaborative for Excellence
in Teacher Preparation, District 2 in Manhattan and the YMCA Beacon
Technology Center . The purpose of MathMol is to provide the K-12
educational community with information and materials dealing with
the rapidly growing fields of molecular modeling and 3-D visualization.
As the program gains momentum, databases and activities will be
posted for educational use. Many activities will permit students
to work interactively with molecular and mathematical images.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://cwis.nyu.edu/docs/providers/rich/education/mathmol/mathmol.html" >http://cwis.nyu.edu/docs/providers/rich/education/mathmol/mathmol.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>McREL -- The Mid-continent Regional Educational Laboratory
</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
McREL is a nonprofit organization dedicated to improving the quality
of education for all students. As one of 10 regional educational
laboratories sponsored by the Office of Educational Research and
Improvement (OERI) of the U.S. Department of Education, McREL
provides federally funded services to a seven-state region: Colorado,
Kansas, Missouri, Nebraska, North Dakota, South Dakota, and Wyoming.
McREL's products and services are also available outside the Mid-continent
region through a variety of contractual agreements, through the
Mid-continent Laboratory, Inc. (MCL) and the nonprofit McREL Institute.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.mcrel.org/" >http://www.mcrel.org/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Media Literacy On-Line Project</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Media Literacy On-Line Project is a continuing research activity
coordinated at the University of Oregon's College of Education.
The project's goal is to make online information and resources
available to educators, producers, students, parents, and others
interested in the influence of electronic media on children, youth,
and adults. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: <BR>
URL = <A HREF="gopher://Interact.uoregon.edu:70/1D-1%3A632%3AMedia%20Literacy" >gopher://Interact.uoregon.edu:70/1D-1%3A632%3AMedia%20Literacy  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>NCREL -- North Central Regional Educational Laboratory</STRONG>
</EM>
<BR>
NCREL is a not-for-profit organization devoted to researching
and implementing best practices in public schools so that all
students achieve standards of educational excellence. From providing
technical assistance to developing products, from sharing research
to collaborating with state agencies, we strengthen state educational
reform efforts and support regional networks in our region. In
particular, our emphasis is on supporting School Development.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://cedar.cic.net/ncrel/" >http://cedar.cic.net/ncrel/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>NEIRL -- Regional Laboratory for Educational Improvement
of the Northeast and Islands</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Regional Laboratory for Educational Improvement of the Northeast
and Islands is one of the 10 regional educational laboratories
authorized by Congress and sponsored by the U.S. Department of
Education's Office of Educational Research and Improvement (OERI).
Under the direction of a 41-member, regionally representative
governing board, the Laboratory does development work and provides
assistance to educators and policymakers throughout its service
area. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.neirl.org/labhome.html" >http://www.neirl.org/labhome.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>NWREL -- NorthWest Regional Educational Laboratory</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
NWREL, an independent, educational research and development institution,
is one of the 10 regional educational laboratories in the United
States. The Northwest Region includes the states of Alaska, Idaho,
Montana, Oregon, and Washington. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.nwrel.org/" >http://www.nwrel.org/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Odyssey of the Mind</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
Odyssey of the Mind is a world-wide, nonprofit organization that
promotes creative team-based problem solving in a school program
for students from kindergarten through college. The program helps
students learn divergent thinking and problem solving skills while
participating in a series of challenging and motivating activities,
both inside and outside their regular classroom curriculum. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.odyssey.org/odyssey/" >http://www.odyssey.org/odyssey/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>PREL -- Pacific Regional Educational Laboratory</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
PREL, a non-profit corporation, is an educational laboratory funded
by the U.S. Department of Education to serve the U.S. affiliated
territories. PREL helps Pacific schools improve educational outcomes
for children, youth, and adults by providing training, technical
assistance, group facilitation, information resource activities,
research, and evaluation services. In addition to its federally-funded
activities, PREL performs a variety of services on other contractual
bases. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://prel-oahu-1.prel.hawaii.edu/" >http://prel-oahu-1.prel.hawaii.edu/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>RBS -- Research for Better Schools</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
RBS is a private, nonprofit corporation which has served as the
Mid-Atlantic regional educational laboratory for 28 years under
funding from the U.S. Department of Education. RBS has also offered
educational development, evaluation, technical assistance, and
training services under client funding within the region, and
operates a self-supporting publications division on a national
basis. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.rbs.org/" >http://www.rbs.org/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG><EM>SEDL -- Southwest Educational Development Laboratory</EM></STRONG><BR>
SEDL is a private, non-profit corporation funded by the U.S. Department of Education's 
Office of Educational Research and Improvement. Current serving the states of Arkansas, 
Louisiana, New Mexico, Oklahoma, and Texas, SEDL assists organizations that work 
directly with schools by collecting resources, synthesizing research, and providing 
materials, training, and technical assistance.<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.sedl.org/">http://www.sedl.org/</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>SERVE -- SouthEastern Regional Vision for Education</STRONG>
</EM>
<BR>
SouthEastern Regional Vision for Education (SERVE) is the federally-funded
education laboratory serving Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Mississippi,
North Carolina and South Carolina. SERVE works under a five-year
contract with the U.S. Department of Education to provide leadership,
support and research to assist state and local efforts in improving
educational outcomes, especially for at-risk and rural students.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://nwrel.org/serveinfo.txt" >http://nwrel.org/serveinfo.txt  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>TEIS -- Teacher Education Internet Server</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The University of Virginia and the University of Houston have
collaborated to establish a Teacher Education Server on the Internet.
The Teacher Education Internet Server was established to explore
ways in which the Internet could benefit teacher education programs
around the world. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://curry.edschool.virginia.edu/teis/" >http://curry.edschool.virginia.edu/teis/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>TIE -- Telescopes in Education Program</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
This is a project designed to bring research-grade astronomy to
schools, amateur clubs, etc. by way of a remotely-controlled telescope
and easy-to-use software for data acquisition. The telescope was
built and used by Caltech, and was used in the 1960's for a project
during the Apollo program to test if the Moon's surface was solid
enough (as opposed to soft moon dust) for spacecraft to land on.
It has been re-commissioned by the Mount Wilson Institute to advance
hands-on education in astronomy. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.mtwilson.edu/tie.html" >http://www.mtwilson.edu/tie.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>State Projects</FONT></STRONG>
<P>
<U><STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Alabama</H3></STRONG></U>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>PACERS Cooperative</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The PACERS Cooperative is a group of 29 small rural Alabama public
schools encompassing kindergarten through twelfth grade. It was
organized in 1990 by the Program for Rural Services and Research
at the University of Alabama and by ACCESS, Inc. a state-wide,
non -profit small school support organization. The Cooperative
is demographically representative of rural Alabama. Its purpose
has been to develop and implement a program of education reform
and community development. Its program, &quot;Better Schools Building
Better Communities,&quot; includes a variety of innovative projects
which are interrelated in ways that improve and change the nature
of schooling. The strategies of the Cooperative developed to create
its program also created a process of reflection and sharing which
leads to genuine school reform. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://peop.tdsnet.com/pacers/pacers.html" >http://peop.tdsnet.com/pacers/pacers.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>California</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Interactive Multimedia for Middle Grade Life Sciences</STRONG>
</EM>
<BR>
Interactive Multimedia for Middle Grade Life Sciences is a partnership
of Stanford scientists and specialists in adolescent education,
middle school science teachers, and multimedia design specialists
at Volotta Interactive Video in Marin County. The project will
create an extensive, interactive multimedia life science education
resource for the classroom focusing on the problems of high risk
behaviors in adolescents. The resource will cover the nervous
system and the effects of drugs and alcohol, and will relate these
biological processes to adolescent development, behavior, and
health. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information:<BR>
URL = <A HREF="gopher://sepa1.bio.cmu.edu:70/11/Science%20Education%20Partnership/06" >gopher://sepa1.bio.cmu.edu:70/11/Science%20Education%20Partnership/06  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Colorado</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Together Foundation Education Service: Colorado Education
Online</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
Colorado Education Online, a partnership with the Together Foundation,
effectively demonstrates how precollegiate school systems can
work together with prominent universities to build local electronic
infrastructures and information pathways, and connect these local
pathways to the National Information Infrastructure. The Together
Foundation believes that linking schools through an interactive,
inexpensive, easy-to-use, electronic network supports the improvement
of learning, instruction, teaching and school administration.
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.together.org:80/together/tgfedu.html" >http://www.together.org:80/together/tgfedu.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Massachusetts</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>REMS^2 -- Regional Electronic Magnet School RE: Math and
Science</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
REMS^2 is an educational research project encompassing 14 high
schools in the Merrimack Valley, drawing on the teaching and research
facilities of the University of Massachusetts at Lowell and Fitchburg
State College. The program's aim is to lead and challenge students
through exposure to current research problems and methods using
a powerful electronic network and resource system. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://adler.mec.mass.edu/www/rems.html" >http://adler.mec.mass.edu/www/rems.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Michigan</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Kids' College</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
Kids' College, a program sponsored by the Ingham Intermediate
School District and Michigan State University, has 240 third and
fourth graders who are studying either Rocks, Forestry, Water
or Flight. These groups will be putting up their own WWW pages
that will contain information about themselves, their interests
and what they have learned. They will also be making inquiries
about their particular subject matter. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://web.cal.msu.edu/kc/kidscollege.html" >http://web.cal.msu.edu/kc/kidscollege.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Lapeer Community Schools Internet Training Seed Program
</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Lapeer Community Schools Internet Training Seed Program is
a joint project of the School of Information and Library Studies
at the University of Michigan and the Lapeer Community Schools.
This seed program is intended to provide high-quality Internet
training to a small number of teachers and media specialists in
the Lapeer Community Schools, with the expectation that this training
will be a starting point for a self-sufficient development program
within the district. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://http2.sils.umich.edu/LCSITSP/LCSITSP.html" >http://http2.sils.umich.edu/LCSITSP/LCSITSP.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>New York</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Empire Internet Schoolhouse</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
Part of the NYSERNet &quot;Bridging the Gap Project,&quot; The
Empire Internet Schoolhouse provides resources for new K-12 users.
Bridging the Gap promotes collaboration and partnership in the
educational community to meet the needs of students and educators
at every level. Empire Internet Schoolhouse provides a selection
of K-12 resources, projects and discussion groups from every corner
of the Internet community. As new users of the Internet, teachers
and students face a steep learning curve to becoming Internet
navigators. Empire Internet Schoolhouse addresses this &quot;gap&quot;
in new user experience by providing useful resources for the classroom.
The project is funded in part by The IBM Corporation, The New
York State Science and Technology Foundation, and the National
Science Foundation. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="gopher://nysernet.org:3000/1" >gopher://nysernet.org:3000/1  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>LiveText</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The LiveText resources on ILTweb are being developed by the Institute
for Learning Technologies, Teachers College, Columbia University,
to provide K-12 related resources to educators, students and others;
and to support the Institute's Advanced Media in Education Project,
a long-term effort to integrate technological innovations into
a practical process of education. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.ilt.columbia.edu/LT/LiveText" >http://www.ilt.columbia.edu/LT/LiveText  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>VICE in REST -- Virtual Instructional Collaborative Environment
in Research, Education, Service and Teaching</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
VICE in REST represents a joint effort between SUNY Plattsburg
and the Peru Central School District to integrate the use of the
Internet in K-12 and involves the use of computer and telecommunications
technologies to connect and empower both instructor and students
to work together in unique and collaborative ways in the practice
of teaching-learning, with emphasis on student contributions to
the Internet. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://bio420.hawk.plattsburgh.edu/VICEinREST.html" >http://bio420.hawk.plattsburgh.edu/VICEinREST.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>North Carolina</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Impact North Carolina</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
Impact North Carolina is a partnership between Appalachian State
University, AT&amp;T, and Bell South in which the applications
of modern, cost effective computer and telecommunications technologies
in educational settings are explored and to provide computer,
graphics, and video connections between Appalachian and three
schools in the Watauga County School System. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.ced.appstate.edu/erin/Impact.html" >http://www.ced.appstate.edu/erin/Impact.html  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>North Carolina Information Highway</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The North Carolina Information Highway (NCIH) is a state-of-the-art
broadband telecommunications network that will provide educational,
medical, economic development, criminal justice, public safety
and governmental benefits to all parts of the state. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://ncih.osc.state.nc.us/" >http://ncih.osc.state.nc.us/  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Pennsylvania</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Common Knowledge: Pittsburgh</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
Common Knowledge: Pittsburgh (CK:P) is a school networking project
of the Pittsburgh Public Schools, the University of Pittsburgh
and the Pittsburgh Supercomputing Center. CK:P is a collaborative
venture consisting of teachers, technical experts and research
evaluators. Local universities, corporations, and foundations
help to facilitate project activities. Affiliated organizations
include Carnegie-Mellon University, University of Pittsburgh,
Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh, Pittsburgh Supercomputing Center,
Digital Equipment Corporation, and The Mattress Factory (an arts
center). <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://info.ckp.edu/home.html" >http://info.ckp.edu/home.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Tennessee</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>MECCA -- Memphis Educational Computer Connectivity Alliance
</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
MECCA is a consortium of academic institutions within the Memphis,
Tennessee area. Its organizing membership is composed of the University
of Tennessee, Memphis , University of Memphis , Christian Brothers
University, LeMoyne-Owen College, Rhodes College , teaching hospitals,
The Planetree Center, and the Memphis City Schools (East High
School). One of MECCA's goals is to accommodate an educational
partnership between a local area high school and the member institutions
of higher education. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.mecca.org/" >http://www.mecca.org/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Tennessee Information Infrastructure</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
One of this project's goals and objectives is to standardize and
achieve interoperability between public networks, beginning with
three operated by the Tennessee Office of Information Resources,
University of Tennessee, and Tennessee Board of Regents for areas
of education, health-care, libraries, and community services,
emphasizing disadvantaged groups (e.g., rural, urban, disabled).
<BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.state.tn.us/tnii/tniistat.html" >http://www.state.tn.us/tnii/tniistat.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Texas</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>TEC -- The Texas Environmental Center</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
TEC is an environmental information clearinghouse with the mission
of creating a communications network linking the diverse and geographically
separate environmental interests of Texas. TEC is a non-profit
and non-partisan organization that was formed in the Spring of
1991 with the mission of promoting environmental awareness through
information sharing. Currently TEC's focus is to integrate and
enhance the water quality education of Texas high school students.
TEC is accomplishing this through the use of high speed Internet
connections in four Texas high schools and an electronic bulletin
board system. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://198.214.57.13/WWW/TEC/abouttec.html" >http://198.214.57.13/WWW/TEC/abouttec.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Utah</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>CATE -- Center for the Advancement of Technology in Education
</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
CATE serves as a bridge between the University of Utah Graduate
School of Education, other University of Utah colleagues and departments,
business, and public education. The Center's mission is to assist
faculty in public and higher education in Utah to successfully
plan for and utilize existing and developing technologies in classrooms
and instructional labs; alto, to provide forums for the increased
awareness of, access to, and effective use of technology systems,
programs, and related resources. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.gse.utah.edu/Cons/CATE/CATE.html" >http://www.gse.utah.edu/Cons/CATE/CATE.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Vermont</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Vermont Educational Gateway Service</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The Vermont Educational Gateway Service is a collaborative effort
of the Together Foundation and the Vermont State Department of
Education. This service is designed to benefit educationally-focused
electronic bulletin boards and online systems in the state of
Vermont. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://www.together.org:80/together/tgfedu.html" >http://www.together.org:80/together/tgfedu.html  
</A></STRONG><HR>

<P>
<H3>Virginia</H3>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>CNELink</STRONG></EM>
<BR>
The CNELink K-12 School Community is a cooperative effort among
the Center for the New Engineer (CNE) at George Mason University,
the Community Learning and Information Network (CLIN), and eight
public schools representing three different public school districts.
Funded by the Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA) of the
Department of Defense, the objectives of the project are to demonstrate
the ability of public school teachers and students to develop
collaborative educational activities and projects through a connection
to the Internet. <BR>
<STRONG>For more information: URL = <A HREF="http://cne.gmu.edu:80/cnelink/" >http://cne.gmu.edu:80/cnelink/  
</A></STRONG>
<P>
<HR>
