<HEAD>
<TITLE>K-12 on the Internet: How Wired Is K-12?</TITLE>
<!-- Created February 10, 1995 by Carolyn Kotlas -->
<!-- Last revised: December 10, 1996 by Carolyn Kotlas and Sarah Ivey -->
<!-- Filename = irg-19.html -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFCE7" TEXT="#00006F">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>K-12 on the Internet: How Wired Is K-12?</FONT></STRONG>
<P>Compiled by: Carolyn Kotlas, MSLS <BR>
Institute for Academic Technology <BR>
Last revised: September 13, 1996</CENTER>
<P>&quot;The U.S. Department of Education reports that only one-third of the nation's public schools have access to the Internet. However,75% have computers, 74% have cable TV and 70% have broadcast TV.&quot;(<EM>Broadcasting &amp; Cable</EM>, 2/13/95 p.51) How much K-12 presence is there on the Internet? Here is a sampling of Internet sites established by and for the K-12 sector.
<HR><P>
<STRONG><EM>K-12 Internet Sites</EM></STRONG>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../media/gifs/update.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="UPDATED"> <STRONG>HotList of K-12 Internet School Sites - USA<BR></STRONG>
 <A HREF="http://rrnet.com/~gleason/k12.html">http://rrnet.com/~gleason/k12.html</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="../media/gifs/update.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="UPDATED"> <STRONG>Web 66 -- WWW Schools Registry<BR></STRONG>
<A HREF="http://web66.coled.umn.edu/schools.html" >http://web66.coled.umn.edu/schools.html</A>
<P>
<STRONG>United States K12 Libraries<BR></STRONG>
<A HREF="http://Galaxy.EINet.NET/hytelnet/US000K12.html" >http://Galaxy.EINet.NET/hytelnet/US000K12.html</A>
<P><HR><P>
<STRONG><EM>Internet Sites for Use in K-12 Activities</EM></STRONG>
<P>
