<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFCE7" TEXT="#00006F">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>CD-ROMs, Laserdiscs, and Videos: Sources</FONT></STRONG>
<P>
Compiled by: Carolyn Kotlas, MSLS<BR>
Institute for Academic Technology<BR>
Last revised: July 1996
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG>Overview</STRONG></FONT>
<P>
Multimedia uses the power of the computer to combine voice, music,
still pictures, full-motion video and text into an integrated,
interactive package invaluable for teaching. Most educators, however,
do not have the time or the money to create all their own resources as
well as incorporate them into multimedia applications. There are
abundant resources currently available for such people, created and
stored in a variety of formats for the convenience of the developer.  A
collection of vendor catalogs can be a valuable tool for selecting
multimedia materials. The following is a list of sources of CD-ROMs,
laserdiscs, videotapes and other resources for multimedia instruction
and development.
<P>
