<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Computer Classroom and Laboratory Design:  Bibliography</TITLE>
<!-- Converted to HTML format: August 1995 -->
<!-- Last revised: July 9, 1996 by Carolyn Kotlas -->
<!-- Filename = irg-03.html -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFCE7" TEXT="#00006F">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>Computer Classroom and Laboratory Design:  Bibliography</STRONG></FONT>
<P>
Compiled by Carolyn Kotlas, MSLS<BR>
Institute for Academic Technology<BR>
Last revised: July 9, 1996<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Incorporating computer technology into the education process also involves redesigning the physical space where instruction takes place. Articles in this guide provide examples and advice on modifying existing classrooms to accommodate new technologies and on designing and building new teaching environments. 
<P>
Barba, Robertta. "Examining Computer Configurations: Mini-Labs."
	<EM>Computing Teacher</EM> 17 (May 1990): 8-10.
<P>
Barker, Thomas T. "Guidelines for Opening a Multipurpose Microlab in an
	English Department." <EM>Collegiate Microcomputer</EM> 4 (May 1986):
	115-122.
<P>
Bunson, Stanley N. "Design and Management of an IMC Micro Center."
	<EM>Educational Technology</EM> 28 (August 1988): 29-32.
<P>
Bunson, Stanley N. "Put a Micro Lab in the Media Center."<EM> Instructional
	Innovator</EM> 29 (January 1984): 29-30.
<P>
Cavalier, Robert. "Furniture or Infrastructure." <EM>Higher Education
	Product Companion</EM> 3 (September 1993): 30-32.
<P>
Clabaugh, Sue.<EM> Design of General Purpose Classrooms, Lecture Halls, and
	Seminar Rooms</EM>. 2nd ed. College Park, MD: Educational Technology
	Center. University of Maryland, 1993.
<P>
Connolly, Frank W., and Thomas E. Eisenberg. "The Feedback Classroom:
	Teaching's Silent Friend." <EM>T.H.E. Journal</EM> 17 (December/January
	1990): 75-77.
<P>
Conway, Kathryn. <EM>Master Classrooms: Classroom Design with Technology in
	Mind</EM>. Research Triangle Park, NC: Institute for Academic
	Technology, 1993.
<P>
Cowles, Jim. "Logistics in the Computer Lab." <EM>Media and Methods</EM> 26
	(September-October 1989): 10, 12, 114-115.
<P>
<EM>Creating and Managing an Academic Computer Lab</EM>. Cupertino, CA: Apple
	Computer, Inc., 1991.
<P>
Czerwinski, W. Peter. "Developing a Multipurpose High School Student
	Computer Room." <EM>Computing Teacher</EM> 18 (May 1991): 19-22.
<P>
Day, C. William. "What Makes a Computer Lab: Use These Ideas to Design
	Your Own." <EM>School Administrator</EM> 46 (April 1989): 20-23.
<P>
Dileepan, Parthasarati. "Planning Academic Microcomputer Laboratory
	Resources: A Simulation Approach." <EM>Journal of Education for
	Business</EM> 63 (February 1988): 210-214.
<P>
<EM>Drexel University Microcomputing Program. Microcomputing Facilities:
	Objectives and Policies</EM>. Philadelphia, PA: The Microcomputing
	Program. Drexel University.
<P>
Duggan, Brian. "A Measured Approach to Microcomputer Lab Design." <EM>Tech
	Trends</EM> 39, no. 4 (September 1994): 24-28.
<P>
Earle, Daniel W., Jr. "The Macintosh Based Design Studio." <EM>Collegiate
	Microcomputer</EM> 6 (February 1988): 1-22.
<P>
Espinosa, Leonard J. "Ten Commandments for Microcomputer Facility
	Planners." <EM>Media and Methods</EM> 27 (May-June 1991): 32-34.
<P>
<IMG SRC="../media/gifs/new.gif"> Gayeski, Diane M., ed. <EM>Designing Communication and Learning Environments.</EM> 
	Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Educational Technology Publications, 1995.
<P>
Gibson, Chris. <EM>Video-Out Projection and Lecture Hall Set-Up</EM>.
	Philadelphia, PA: The Microcomputing Program. Drexel
	University, 1985.
<P>
