<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFCE7" TEXT="#00006F">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>Smart Cards: Readings and Resources
</STRONG></FONT>
<P>
Compiled by: Carolyn Kotlas, MSLS<BR>
Institute for Academic Technology<BR>
Last revised: October 14, 1996
</CENTER>
<P>
Is there a Smart Card in your future? What are Smart Cards, and who is using them? Industry, government, and educational institutions are increasing their use of Smart Cards as cash replacements, for identification cards, and to record and store data in a highly-portable medium. This surge in use can be attributed to factors such as the maturing of the technology (the cards are getting smarter), decreasing costs, increasing need for transaction security, and the move towards a "cashless society." Find out how Smart Cards are changing how we do business and if there is a place for them in your organization.
<P>
<A HREF="#articles">Papers, Articles, Press Releases, Books</A><BR>
	· <A HREF="#articles1">General Background Information</A><BR>
	· <A HREF="#articles2">Education</A><BR>
	· <A HREF="#articles3">Financial Services, Banking, Electronic Purse</A><BR>
	· <A HREF="#articles4">Health and Social Services</A><BR>
	· <A HREF="#articles5">Telecommunications</A><BR>
	· <A HREF="#articles6">Transportation, Travel, Leisure and Entertainment</A><BR>
<A HREF="#newsletters">Smart Card Newsletters</A><BR>
<A HREF="#education">Educational Institutions Using Smart Cards</A><BR>
<A HREF="#companies">Companies Providing Smart Card Solutions</A><BR>
<A HREF="#associations">Smart Card Associations</A>
<P>

