<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Instructional Technology Review and Update"</H2>
<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> Thursday, October 27, 1994
<BR>[<A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Information</A>]</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Have you ever tried to select hardware and software for a multimedia lab or a master classroom? or been faced with purchasing a multimedia-enabled network or an interactive distance learning system? If so, you probably were confronted by a dizzying number of choices, all explained in acronyms. In this video, our panel of experts clarifies this confusion as they discuss and demonstrate instructional technology from the basics to recently announced new products. You will learn about:
<UL>
<LI>Basic instructional hardware technology - such as multimedia, computer classroom equipment and networks.
<LI>Multimedia-enabled software for developing instructional applications and presentations.
<LI>Exciting new instructional technologies that enable or enhance group-based learning, distance learning and network distribution of multimedia.</UL>

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3> 

<UL>
<LI>Steve Dischinger - Consultant in networking, multimedia and distance education, IBM Higher Education.
<LI>Steve Griffin - IAT Director of Technical Services.
<LI>David Luttrell - IAT Manager of Network Integration Services.
<LI>Joe Schuch - IAT Facilities Development and Support Consultant.</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>


<H3><A NAME="video">Video Ordering Information</A></H3>
