<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Hi-Touch Technology: Authenticity in the Learning Environment"</H2>
<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> Thursday, February 23, 1995
<BR>[<A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Information</A>]</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Technology can go beyond school exercises to engage the learner in exploring authentic samples of learning material. At the same time, technology creates more creative and flexible learning environments. The challenge to educators is to use technology to improve instruction within the new learning environments.

<P>In this video, our panel of experts discuss and demonstrate how to implement and integrate technology throughout the entire spectrum of instruction, from novice to advanced levels.

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3> 

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../../noblitt/noblitt.html">James S. Noblitt</A> - IAT Academic Chair, moderates the broadcast. He is Research Professor of Romance Languages at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. Noblitt is interested in the ways information technology is being used for teaching and research in the humanities, especially foreign languages.
<P><LI>Frank Dominguez - Assistant Chairman and Director of Graduate Studies in the Department of Romance Languages at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, demonstrates a language resource center for undergraduate to graduate courses in foreign language and literature. Dominguez is also Director of UNC's Language Resource Center and Fellow of the IAT.
<P><LI>William Geoghegan - Academic Consultant with IBM Higher Education, studies how information technology enters the mainstream of teaching and learning. Geoghegan has more than 25 years experience in the innovation and effective application of information technology to teaching, research and administration in higher education.
<P><LI>James J. O'Donnell - Professor of Classical Studies and Coordinator of the Center for Computer Analysis of Texts at the University of Pennsylvania, uses the Internet to broaden the scope of his teaching by reaching students worldwide as well as those in his classroom. O'Donnell has been active in the scholarly use of networked communication for several years. He is co-editor of Bryn Mawr Classical Review and Bryn Mawr Medieval Review, on-line book review journals in the humanities, and now teaches seminars on the Internet at an advanced level in his area of expertise.   
<P><LI>Anne Parker - Deputy Director of the Office of Information Technology for the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill's campus-wide network and academic technology support organization, discusses institutional barriers for the infusion of technical innovation.
<P><LI>Albert Van Helden - Lynette S. Autrey Professor of History at Rice University, discusses the development of the Galileo Project, a pilot effort to move routine information out of the classroom in order to leave more time for discussion. The Galileo Project is part of Rice University's Electronic Studios Project, where the studio concept of an electronic workplace and repository for student tools, course assignments, papers and personal files is being tested in numerous disciplines.
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../../../guides/irg-18.html">Hi-Touch Technology: Authenticity in the Learning Environment</A></UL>

