<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Higher Education/K-12 Connection: Using Technology
to Assist Public Schools
"</H2>

<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> April 27, 1995
<BR>[ <A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Info</A> ]
</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Public education is in transition. Public leaders and educational leaders alike believe that education must be restructured if it is to remain the cultural and economic foundation of a prosperous democracy into the next century. But there are more exhortations to restructure the public schools than prescrip-tions for doing so. Perhaps the most promising vehicles for change are the same computer and video networks and technologies that are driving the industrial economy into the knowledge economy along the "information superhighway."

<P>But higher education, federal and state governments, and the private sector will have to work together with the public schools if the emerging National Information Infrastructure is to become a learning infrastructure that enables the public schools to improve learning outcomes while serving as a primary socializing force for the nation’s children. This video explores the possibilities from a variety of perspectives.

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3>
<UL>
<P><LI><A HREF="../../graves/graves.html">William H. Graves</A> - Director of the IAT, will moderate the broadcast. Graves is Professor of Mathematics and is responsible for the information technology infrastructure and services at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. He also chairs the planning committee for EDUCOM’s National Learning Infrastructure Initiative.

<P><LI>Colleen S. Kennedy - Dean of the Graduate School of Education and Professor of Educational Studies at the University of Utah. Kennedy has co-authored a text on mainstreaming students with learning and behavior problems, conducted research on strategies to improve students’ mathematical performance, and written and lectured extensively in the U.S. and overseas on such topics as data-based instruction, curriculum-based assessment, technology, and on teacher education policies and practices.

<P><LI>Jane Smith Patterson - Advisor to the Governor for Policy, Budget and Technology, for the state of North Carolina. She is responsible for the management of policy issues, policy oversight for budget issues and state planning, development of technology policy and deployment strategies, and other areas as assigned by the Governor.

<P><LI>Anne-Lee Verville - General Manager of IBM Education Businesses, manages IBM’s efforts with colleges and universities (Higher Education), kindergarten through 12th grade (EduQuest), and corporate training including IBM’s own internal education (Education & Training).

<P><LI>Jerry D. Weast - Superintendent of the Guilford County School System, third largest in North Carolina, operating 93 schools and serving approximately 56,000 students. He has made technology applications for all schools an important part of comprehensive, systemwide efforts to improve student performance.
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../../../guides/irg-21.html">Higher Education/K-12 Connection: Bibliography</A>
<LI><A HREF="../../../guides/irg-19.html">K-12 On the Internet: How Wired is K-12?</A>
<LI><A HREF="../../../guides/irg-27.html">K-12 / Higher Education Technology Partnerships</A>
</UL>

