<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Computer Conferencing: Alternative to Lectures"</H2>
<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> Monday, November 13, 1995
<BR>[<A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Information</A>]</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Computer conferencing is an asynchronous (store and forward) way of communicating that works similarly to e-mail and listserves. However, computer conferencing software is designed specifically for text-based group discourse. It has special features that enable and enhance group communication and projects. Because it is asynchronous, computer conferencing can reduce the constraints of time- and place-based instruction, both on campus (lectures) and off-campus (two-way video distance education).  

<P>In this video you will visit four different campuses and meet six faculty who will demonstrate the use of computer conferencing in a wide range of courses and with diverse student populations. You'll also learn how to convert your own lecture-based courses to computer conferenced courses.

<P>You can examine the benefits of computer conferencing from both the teacher's and learner's points of view, with emphasis on issues such as motivation, student interaction, empowerment, and depth and understanding of subject matter through dialogue. You will see computer conferencing tools ranging from e-mail and screen capture software to more sophisticated applications such as Lotus Notes&#174; and FirstClass&#174;.

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3> 

<UL>
<LI>Steve Andriole - Chief Technology Officer, CIGNA Corporation
<LI>Linda Collins - Coordinator, Information Technologies Services, Rio Salado Community College
<LI><A HREF="../../conway/conway1.html">Kathryn Conway</A> - Senior Analyst for Distributed Learning Environments, IAT 
<LI><A HREF="../../graves/graves.html">William H. Graves</A> - Director of the IAT and Associate Provost for Information Technology for the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill
<LI>Mary Hannaman - Program Director, Academic Studies, Rio Salado Community College
<LI>Steve H. Nickles - Bess and Walter Williams Distinguished Professor, School of Law, Wake Forest University 
<LI>Diana Oblinger - Solutions Manager, IBM Higher Education
<LI><A HREF="../../roberts/roberts.html">Lowell Roberts</A> - IAT Research Fellow</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>
<UL><LI>Our <A HREF="sb_nov95.html">supplemental materials page</A> includes articles written by broadcast presenters, software vendor resource lists, audio files from the broadcast and more.</UL>

