<HEAD>
<TITLE>IAT: Instructional Study Summary</TITLE>
<! -- Created: August 15, 1996 by Carolyn Kotlas -- >
<! -- Filename = summary.html -- >
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFCE7" TEXT="#00006F" LINK="#006700" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#EE0000">

<IMG SRC="../../../media/gifs/iatlogo.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=5  ALT="illust.">
        
<TABLE  ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR><TD>
<A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/media/navigate.map"><IMG SRC="http://www.iat.unc.edu/media/gifs/navigate.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#navigate" ISMAP ALIGN=RIGHT></A>

<MAP NAME="navigate">
<!-- #$-:Image Map file created by Map THIS! -->
<!-- #$-:Map THIS! free image map editor by Todd C. Wilson -->
<!-- #$-:Please do not edit lines starting with "#$" -->
<!-- #$VERSION:1.30 -->
<!-- #$DESCRIPTION:IAT Web Site Navigational Toolbar -->
<!-- #$AUTHOR:Chad Kearsley -->
<!-- #$DATE:Thu Jul 18 11:27:42 1996 -->
<!-- #$PATH:M:\docs\WWW\media\gifs\ -->
<!-- #$GIF:navigate.gif -->
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="13,1,56,22" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/index.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="58,2,99,22" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/general/new.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="102,0,160,23" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/search/search.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="162,0,239,22" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/feedback/feedback.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="241,1,293,23" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/general/about.html">
<AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="294,1,374,23" HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/cybrary/cybrary.html">
</MAP>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<BR><BR><BR>

<CENTER><STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>A</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+3>G</FONT>utenberg <FONT SIZE=+3>J</FONT>uncture: <FONT SIZE=+3>R</FONT>elated <FONT SIZE=+3>R</FONT>eading</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>

<P>
<STRONG>Shute, Valerie, and Lisa Gawlick. "Practice Effects on Skill Acquisition, Learning Outcome, Retention and Sensitivity to Relearning." <EM>Human Factors</EM>  37, no. 4 (December 1995): 781-803.  </STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>Tom's Summary of the Study:</STRONG><BR>
Subjects with no knowledge of aviation were divided into four groups to receive computer-based tutoring in flight engineering (navigation).  The tutoring program was divided into two segments, each containing several blocks of practice questions.   All groups received practice problems.  There were two practice problem conditions: extended (E) blocks of 12 problems and abbreviated (A) blocks of 3 problems.  Groups received all extended, (E-E), all abbreviated (A-A) or mixed (A-E, E-A) problem blocks.  Subjects did not know which group they were in, so the mixed groups experienced a change in practice problem block size.  Both groups were self-paced.  
<P>
The large block group performed better on the practice problems than the small block group.  At the conclusion of their training, the subjects were tested. There were no significant differences among practice conditions on posttest scores!   The authors expected to find better performance to coincide with working larger numbers of practice problems, reasoning that the more time spent in learning should equate to better performance. When tested two years later, the mixed (A-E, E-A) groups performed significantly better than subjects in either of the other two test conditions.  

<P>In the flight engineering training all students used the same tutoring resource.  The mode of use differed, however.  The extended block (E-E) group spent a more total time the study process than the abbreviated (A-A) group.  The small block (A-A) group spent more time (X1.8) in the tutoring resource than did the extended group.  

<P>
What might this mean?  How might it be applied to technology-enhanced instruction?  It appears that students learn the most from the first few questions.  Subsequent practice does little to improve performance.  Also, the unexpected change in pace in the mixed (A-E, E-A) groups kept the students "on their toes" in some way. 

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Carlson, R.A., and Yaure, R.G., 1990.  "Practice Schedules and the Use of Component Skills in Problem Solving." <EM>Journal of Experimental Psychology: Learning, Memory and Cognition</EM> 16, no. 3 (1990): 484-496.</STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>Tom's Summary of the Study:</STRONG><BR>
Carlson and Yaure reported three studies which demonstrated that randomized practice schedules produced poorer acquisition performance, but better retention compared to massed block practice sessions.  Clearly, the nature of questioning affects the students outcome.  
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
See also the <STRONG><A HREF="http://hfes.org/HFES/">Human Factors and Ergonomics Society</A></STRONG>'s Web page.
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/publications/monitor/issue1/wason.html">Back</A> to Tom's Article.

<BR>
