</MAP>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<H2>Creating MacWebApp archives</H2><HR>
<P>
MacWebApp provides several features that you can use to perform special
installation tasks for your application. Do the following 3 steps
to create a MacWebApp archive.
<OL>
<LI>Create a Stuffit archive that contains the application you
want people to download and run. If you don't already have
a tool to create the Stuffit archive you can get a shareware version
of Stuffit Lite from the <A HREF="http://hyperarchive.lcs.mit.edu/HyperArchive/Abstracts/cmp/HyperArchive.html">Info-Mac 
HyperArchive</A>
or see <A HREF="http://www.apple.com/documents/sharewaresites.html">FTP sites for Apple-related shareware...</A>
for other software repositories.
<LI>You should name your archive with the extension .mwa so that
the web server can recognize the type.
<LI>You must get the site administrator to configure the web server
to associate the extension .mwa with the MIME type application/macwebapp.
</OL>
<P>
You can specify special installation instructions by creating a plain text file
called <I>MacWebApp</I> that you include with your application in the Stuffit
archive.
The first line should contain the identifier [MacWebAppAutoInstall]
as the only thing on the line. Subsequent lines have one or more
of the following identifiers in any order followed by = (equal
sign) and the specified value. There should be no spaces
between the equal sign and the value.  When the value is a list
of multiple file names, use commas to separate the names.
The last character in the file should be a RETURN.
<P>
The meaning and format of the value
for each identifier is described below.
<DL>
<DT>ApplicationName<DD>
  Specifies name of file to run.  This is useful if there is more
  than one application in your archive.

<DT>InstallDirectory<DD>
  Specifies name for the folder into which the archive is extracted.

<DT>ReadmeFile<DD>
  Specifies the name of the readme file if any.

<DT>NeedToRestart<DD>
  Specify "yes" or "no" to indicate whether the system needs to
  be restarted after installation.

<DT>RebuildDesktop<DD>
  Specify "yes" or "no" to indicate whether the desktop needs to
  be rebuilt after installation.

<DT>CopyToControlPanels<DD>
  Specify one or more files to move to the system Control Panels
  folder.

<DT>CopyToExtensions<DD>
  Specify one or more files to move to the system Extensions
  folder.

<DT>CopyToPreferences<DD>
  Specify one or more files to move to the system Preferences
  folder.

<DT>AliasToStartupItems<DD>
  Specify one or more files to alias in the system Startup Items
  folder.
</DL>
Here is an example MacWebApp file.
<pre>
[MacWebAppAutoInstall]
ApplicationName=DinoDancers
ReadmeFile=Read Me First!
InstallDirectory=DinoDancers 1.0
</pre>
Go back to the <A HREF="index.html">MacWebApp Homepage</A>. 

<BR>
