<BR>

<H1>Frequently Asked Questions</H1>
<B>Why do I receive messages like "An error occurred while executing an
object script: Finder got an error: AppleEvent timed out. (-1712)" or
"Unable to continue because FaceSpan Extension is missing or would
not open. (0)"?</B>
<P>
Your system software does not meet the minimum requirements required to run
MacWebApp, which are
<UL>
<LI>A system version <I>later</I>  than 7.1.1, OR 
<LI>System 7.0 or later with a scriptable version of the Finder
installed (typically Finder version 7.1.3 or later) and the extensions
<I>AppleScript</I>  and <I>Finder Scripting Extensions</I>  installed.
</UL>
<P>
<B>I am always told that "Stuffit Expander needs your attention...."
When I look at Stuffit Expander, it is asking where it should
install the software, even though I have already told MacWebApp
where to install.  How do I fix this?</B>
<P>
In Stuffit Expander, select Preferences, choose Destination Preferences,
and click on "Same as Original."
<P>
<B>How do I enable virus scanning?</B>
<P>
MacWebApp does not support automatic virus scanning.  If you want to manually
scan
files before executing them, turn on "Prompt before running program"
in the MacWebApp preferences.
<P>
<B>Why do I receive an "Unable to continue because project script
could not be saved (-61)." message every time I quit?</B>
<P>
MacWebApp is locked (check the Get Info box in the Finder) or is on
a locked disk volume, such as a network disk.  This is not a serious
problem, but it might prevent you from saving your preferences.
<P>
<b>MacWebApp installs software and starts the application with no problem.
However, when I quit the newly installed application and go back to MacWebApp,
the
cursor spins indefinitely.  What's going on?</b>
<p>
Did you start any other applications after MacWebbApp started the newly
installed application?  If so, you must quit those applications too
before MacWebApp recognizes that it's time to uninstall the software.
This is typically a problem when MacWebApp starts the new application
and then you start another application to look at documentation or a
ReadMe file.
<P><P>Go back to the <A HREF="index.html">MacWebApp Homepage</A>. 

<BR>
