<BR>
<CENTER><H2>Computer Conferencing: Alternative to Lectures</H2>
<B>Updated:</B> November 10, 1995</CENTER>
<BR><B>What's New:</B> <A HREF="#reading">Additional Reading</A> | <A HREF="../library/liblinks/ccvendor.html">Computer Conferencing Software Vendors List</A> | <A HREF="#audio">Audio files</A>
<P>
<HR>
<P>This page will be updated before, during and after the broadcast.  To help stay tuned to the changes, mark this URL with the <A HREF="http://www.netmind.com/URL-minder/URL-minder.html">URL-Minder</A>.

<P><B>REMINDER</B>: During the week of the broadcast, November 13-17, the IAT will be monitoring a discussion list on computer conferencing issues in education. Our broadcast panel and interview participants will be available to answer any questions you may have about computer conferencing or the case studies we examined during the broadcast. We also encourage you to discuss these issues amongst yourselves. To subscribe to the list, send the message <KBD>subscribe iatforum yourname</KBD> to <A HREF="mailto:listserv@unc.edu">listserv@unc.edu</A>. For questions regarding the listserv or the broadcast itself, contact <A HREF="mailto:barbara_bickell@unc.edu">Barbara Bickell</A>, IAT Communications Program Manager.


<H3>Supplementary Materials</H3>
<UL>

<P><LI><B>Kathryn Conway</B>, Senior Analyst for Distributed Learning at the IAT, welcomes you to the broadcast and introduces the concept of computer conferencing in education.  For more information, see the IAT document <A HREF="../../../guides/irg-36.html">"Computer Conferencing Software Vendors List."</A>

<P><LI><B>Stephen J. Andriole</B>, Senior Vice President and Chief Technology Officer for CIGNA Corporation, teaches his software engineering classes at <A HREF="http://www.drexel.edu/">Drexel University</A> without any classroom meetings. Students use Lotus Notes for computer conferencing, along with online design tools to design software and to review and analyze each other's designs. Stephen will discuss what computer conferencing requires of teachers and the flexibility and benefits it gives to students. For more information, you can read his article in the October issue of T.H.E. Journal, <A HREF="http://thejournal.com/october/10andriole.html">"Asynchronous Learning Networks: Drexel's Experience"</A> or see the IAT document, <A HREF="../../../guides/irg-45.html">"Lotus Notes Information on the Web."</A>

<P><LI><B>Diana Oblinger</B>, Solutions Manager, IBM Higher Education, will discuss student collaboration in the classroom. For more information, read her article, <A HREF="../../oblinger/oblinger.html">"Educational Alternatives Based on Communication, Collaboration and Computers."</A>

<P><LI><B><A HREF="http://www.rio.maricopa.edu/">Rio Salado Community College</A></B> provides an opportunity for working adults to obtain an education by taking courses online and asynchronously from home. These students would not be able to participate in a more traditional course that required them to come to classes on campus. Some of Rio Salado's students will tell us how they feel about using computer conferencing to "go to school" electronically. And their teacher will tell us about her role now that she doesn't have lectures to deliver. Mary Hannaman, Program Director for Academic Studies, and Linda Collins, Coordinator for Information Technology Services, will describe the kind of support services they provide the students and their low-cost approach to making technology available to the students.

<P><LI><B>Burks Oakley</B> is Associate Director of the <A HREF="http://w3.scale.uiuc.edu/scale/">Sloan Center for Asynchronous Learning Environments</A> and Professor of Electrical Engineering at the <A HREF="http://www.uiuc.edu/">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</A>. Burks teaches his classes using FirstClass computer conferencing software in combination with online circuit analysis software. His students work on their homework online, getting assistance from online tutors that allow them to work more efficiently and master concepts more thoroughly. These online homework sessions replace regular classroom tutorial sessions. Burks and the other instructors use the same computer conferencing application to conduct online meetings with the tutors. These electronic meetings save valuable time usually spent trying to coordinate schedules for face-to-face organizing sessions. For more information, you can read his article, <A HREF="http://www.sloan.org/oakley/Maine/index.html">"A Virtual Classroom Approach to Learning Circuit Analysis"</A> or see the IAT document <A HREF="../../../guides/irg-40.html">"FirstClass Information on the Web."</A>

<P><LI><B>Steve Nickles</B>, Bess and Walter Williams Distinguished Professor of Law at <A HREF="http://www.wfu.edu/School-of-Law/">Wake Forest University</A>, has used computer conferencing in Law courses at Wake Forest and at the University of Minnesota to discuss issues relating to their legal case studies. Study and discussion of these cases asynchronously prepares students for a more in-depth and exacting oral analysis of the cases in the classroom. For more information, check out the extensive legal and financial document database at <A HREF="http://www.westpub.com/">West Publishing</A>.

<P><LI><B><A HREF="../../roberts/roberts.html">Lowell Roberts</A></B> is a Research Fellow at the IAT specializing in asynchronous learning and instruction. He has used computer conferencing as an
instructional platform since 1987 and has written and presented
extensively on learning, pedagogy and conferencing, including
workshops at EDUCOM '94 and <A HREF="gopher://cause-gopher.colorado.edu/11/conferences/CAUSE94/precon-seminars/">CAUSE '94</A>.  His <A HREF="../../roberts/template.html">Template for
Converting Classroom Courses to Distributed, Asynchronous
Courses</A> is available from the IAT Web site. Formerly the
Director of the <A HREF="http://www.sunycentral.edu/clt/CLTHOME/textbased.html">SUNY Center for Learning and Technology</A>,
Roberts is the architect of <A HREF="http://www.sunycentral.edu/clt/CLTHOME/sunywide.html#sloan">MHRLN</A> (merlin), now the SUNY
Learning Network, a distributed education network delivering
courses by Lotus Notes that connects 8 campuses, homes and
businesses in the Hudson Valley of New York State. MHRLN was
demonstrated at <A HREF="http://www.educom.edu/web/conf.semi/educom95/conftracks.html#scholarships">EDUCOM '95</A>.</UL>

<A NAME="reading"><H3>Additional Links</H3></A> 
<UL>
<LI>Computer Conferencing: Alternative to Lectures - <A HREF="sb_bib95.html">Selected Bibliography</A>.
<LI><A HREF="ftp://ftp.rpi.edu/pub/communications/internet-cmc">"Information Sources: The Internet and Computer-Mediated Communication,"</A> by John December.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.hs.nki.no/~morten/cmcped.htm">"The Online Report on Pedagogical Techniques for Computer-Mediated Communication,"</A> by Morten Flate Paulsen.
<LI>Papers by the IAT's Director <A HREF="../director/graves.html">William H. Graves</A>.</UL>


