<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>L</FONT>etter from the <FONT SIZE=+3>F</FONT>ounder</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>


<H3><I>Dear Colleague:</I></H3>
<P>We at the IAT welcome your interest in our programs.  We believe that information technology is education's most promising lever for improving the quality of learning and containing the cost of instruction.  The content and structure of our satellite broadcasts, hands-on workshops, custom sessions and other offerings described in this brochure reflect this belief and are the direct result of our experience and your advice.  
<P>We have programs designed to assist you, whether your interests lie in the instructional applications of multimedia and networking technologies, in supporting or managing such technologies or in applying them as vehicles for change in your organization.  We view learning as a richly human undertaking that is most likely to succeed when the learner is a willing party to a social contract that guides learning and adds value to its accomplishment.  Information technology is a means, not an end.  This philosophy shapes both the selection of content for our programs and their delivery.  
<P>With generous financial and technical support from our partner, IBM, we have steered a course for six years that allows us to work with the latest technologies in an educational context and, thereby, to understand educational needs and to respond to these needs with varied national program offerings.  These offerings are designed to meet the needs of public schools, community colleges, four-year colleges and universities, continuing education programs, and training programs in the commercial sector.  
<P>Try us.  Visit our facilities to learn and to share your experiences.  Tune in to our satellite broadcasts.  Utilize our Internet resources.  And let us know the results. 
<P>Sincerely, <A HREF="../publications/graves/graves.html">William H. Graves</A>
<P>

<BR>
