<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>I</FONT>nstructional <FONT SIZE=+3>S</FONT>taff </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR><BR><BR>


<A NAME="graves"></A>
<P><B><A HREF="../publications/graves/graves.html">William H. Graves</A></B>, Ph.D., Founder of the IAT, is Chief Information Officer and Professor of Mathematics at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. A national leader  in the educational use of information technology, he coordinates the IAT’s effort to integrate academic and industry concerns.
<A NAME="ansari"></A>
<P><B>Amin Ansari</B>, B.S., IAT Multimedia Support Engineer, specializes in multimedia hardware and software configuration support and digital video capture tools and techniques. Amin has been involved in multimedia support and development for the past six years.
<A NAME="conway"></A>
<P><B><A HREF="../publications/conway/conway1.html">Kathryn Conway</A></B>, M.A., IAT Senior Analyst, Distributed Learning Environments, is Director for Research in Learning Technologies for the Office of Information Technology at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. She combines experience  in instructional environments, multimedia and distance learning into a focus on distributed learning strategies.
<A NAME="freedman"></A>
<P><B>Darryl Freedman</B> has a master's degree in Electrical Engineering from the Polytechnic University of New York. He was a member of the technical staff at Bell Telephone Laboritories where he taught telecommunications. He has lectured and taught multimedia, animation and telecommunications for over 10 years at IBM. He has lectured in animation at ACM, IEEE and SALT conferences, at the University of Milan and in the Peoples Republic of China. Freedman is currently president of VIVA Associates, a company specializing in multimedia education and training.
<A NAME="geissinger"></A>
<P><B>Ladnor Geissinger</B>, Ph.D., IAT Mathematics Chair, is Professor of Mathematics at the University  of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. He has been experimenting with the use of computers in undergraduate mathematics education for more than a decade and is an award-winning developer of mathematics software. 
 <A NAME="griffin"></A>
<P><B>Steve Griffin</B>, B.S., IAT Director of Technical Services, leads the technical activities of the IAT. He speaks on multimedia, networking and technology trends at IAT and industry events and is a published author of academic software. Steve has been actively involved in interactive technology for the past 10 years.
<A NAME="kaufman"></A>
<P><B>Philip Kaufman</B>, B.S., IAT Instructor, has six years of computer technical support experience and is working toward a master’s degree in mass communications. He also manages the IAT database.
<A NAME="noblitt"></A>
<P><B><A HREF="../publications/noblitt/noblitt.html">James Noblitt</A></B>, Ph.D., IAT Chair for Academic Programs, is Research Professor of Romance Languages at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. He and his colleagues at the IAT have developed a multimedia approach to listening comprehension in foreign languages.
<A NAME="ozer"></A>
<P><B>Jan Ozer</B>, B.A. and J.D., President and Founder of <A HREF="http://www.doceo.com/">Doceo Publishing, Inc.</A>, is a published author of articles on video-related topics for several popular technical magazines--including CD-ROM Professional, PC Magazine, PC Computing and Morph’s Outpost on the Digital Frontier--and has given many presentations and seminars across the country. 
<A NAME="pfaltzgraff"></A>
<P><B>Nancy Pfaltzgraff</B>, B.S., IAT Instructor, has taught college-level mathematics and physics courses, as well as a business calculus course for the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill’s Continuing Education Department. She is also a published author of computer-based algebra texts.
<A NAME="robison"></A>
<P><B>Drew Robison</B>, B.S., IAT Manager of Multimedia Support, consults on multimedia hardware and software solutions and develops multimedia software development tools. Drew has worked with multimedia technologies for the past seven years. 
<A NAME="sladeczek"></A>
<P><B>Jürgen Sladeczek</B>, Ph.D., IAT Research Associate, has a decade of experience in software development and authoring on a variety of platforms. His special interest is in the design of effective software solutions.  
<A NAME="thomas"></A>
<P><B><A HREF="http://www.unc.edu/home/kdt/">Kathy Thomas</A></B> is Instructional Technology Consultant for the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill's Office of Information Technology. She has also been involved with <A HREF="http://www.unc.edu/home/kdt///ssp/">Simple Start</A> -  a pilot program designed to facilitate the instructional use of Internet technologies like electronic mail and the World Wide Web at UNC-CH.
<A NAME="white"></A>
<P><B>Jim White</B>, Ph.D., IAT Mathematics Fellow, is Research Associate Professor of Instructional Technology at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. He is the principal architect and author of MathKit and its programming language, MathScript. 
<A NAME="wolf"></A>
<P><B>Albert Wolf</B>, M.A., IAT Instructor, has worked in multimedia authoring and development for seven years and has done extensive work using ToolBook to create authoring tools and end-user applications.
<P>

