<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Welfare plan shows results in 3 months of operation</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Welfare plan shows results in 3 months of operation</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>tories and statistics from the first three months of Tennessee&#39;s welfare reform plan are a mix of good and bad news, as expected from a program aiming to move 91,500 families from welfare to work.
<P>   Families First began Sept. 1.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think we&#39;re seeing some real progress and some real success stories,&#39;&#39; said Vivian Stidham, district program supervisor for the Department of Human Services in Knoxville.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It is definitely not perfect. We&#39;ve got a great number of things to work out. It&#39;s the most complex thing we&#39;ve done or thought about doing, but I don&#39;t think you&#39;d find anyone in this office who doesn&#39;t think it&#39;s the most important thing we&#39;ve ever done.&#39;&#39;
<P>   About 49,400 welfare recipients statewide met with DHS case managers in the first three months of the program to decide whether to take part in Families First. About 83.3 percent -- 41,155 -- enrolled, according to a quarterly report filed by DHS with state legislators and distributed last week.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think that it basically says that once time is taken by our case managers and our customers to fully explain the program, that the customers are opting in,&#39;&#39; DHS spokeswoman Patricia Harris-Morehead said.
<P>   Statewide, there were about 91,500 families getting Aid to Families with Dependent Children when Families First took effect. AFDC is the monthly cash payment commonly known as &#39;&#39;welfare.&#39;&#39; A mother with two children in Tennessee can get a $185 monthly check.
<P>   To keep the check, Tennessee families must enter Families First, a plan that requires them to sign a Personal Responsiblity Plan (PRP) showing how they&#39;ll move from welfare to work.
<P>   They must spend 40 hours a week at work or in a combination of work and training. After 18 months, their check stops. While they can reapply, there&#39;s a five-year lifetime cap.
<P>   Of the 41,155 who decided to enroll, DHS reported about one in five -- 8,300 people -- went to work either full- or part-time.
<P>   &#39;&#39;A lot of the jobs that are being secured early on are jobs that have been advertised in the local papers,&#39;&#39; said Glenda Shearon, DHS state director of cash assistance and food stamps.
<P>   Many are in service industries, at fast-food restaurants and hotels, for instance. Some got jobs after finishing training programs.
<P>   Almost 2,700 people -- 6.5 percent of those who signed PRPs -- were referred to training programs, which require part-time work. More than 8,600 families (21 percent) were referred to formalized job search activities, and more than 6,800 (16.6 percent) were referred to a life-skills training program called Fresh Start or to an adult education program.
<P>   DHS gave several reasons that almost 8,300 recipients didn&#39;t sign PRPs in the first three months of Familiies First.
<P>   About 3,100 cases were closed because people started earning too much money to qualify for welfare, although they can continue to get transitional benefits including child care, TennCare and food stamps.
<P>   Another 3,100 cases were closed &#39;&#39;voluntarily&#39;&#39; -- often due to missed appointments. The University of Memphis is conducting in-depth surveys this month to find out why people didn&#39;t participate.
<P>   Almost 2,100 people refused to sign PRPs, which automatically closed their welfare cases. In addition, 1,200 people who signed a PRP but didn&#39;t follow it were cut off of Families First.
<P>   Welfare advocates say challenges remain.
<P>   Lynne Williams, a Knoxville welfare mother who works in the federal Volunteers in Service to America program, said transportation and child care are needed.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The transportation system in Knoxville isn&#39;t that great because of the times in the morning the buses start and the times in the evening they end,&#39;&#39; Williams said. &#39;&#39;Services are limited on Saturdays, and there&#39;s no Sunday service. People&#39;s jobs go on beyond the hours that the buses run during the week.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The same issue relates to child care for those working night shifts at supermarkets or restaurants.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There&#39;s not a lot of 24-hour child care,&#39;&#39; Williams said. &#39;&#39;There&#39;s no sick care available, and there&#39;s not a whole lot of weekend care available. Those things are very hard.&#39;&#39;
<P>   DHS officials acknowledged at the outset that the program will evolve as problems surface. Stidham said the state has allowed flexibility.
<P>   For instance, Families First&#39;s 40-hour work/school requirement didn&#39;t count study time for college or nursing school students.
<P>   &#39;&#39;In counting their 40 hours, we could only count the hours they were in class or lab,&#39;&#39; Stidham said. The state decided to credit one hour of study time for every hour in class that requires outside study. &#39;&#39;It was a big issue for students,&#39;&#39; she said.
<P>   The state also has approved six more case manager specialists, who assist case managers, for Knoxville, she said.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The biggest challenge we&#39;re facing in our office is the workload, the volume,&#39;&#39; Stidham said. &#39;&#39;We know what needs to be done, and we simply have not had enough time. . . . Case managers have not been able to give the personal attention they want to give.&#39;&#39;
<P>   She said caseloads average around 170 cases per manager.
<P>   Still, she said, &#39;&#39;As difficult as it&#39;s been, because the workload&#39;s been heavy, this is the first time you can say the whole program is geared toward something that has the definite potential to make a difference in somebody&#39;s life.
<P>    &#39;&#39;Before, we have fostered dependency. We have given our benefits without requiring responsibility in return.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
