<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="144"><p align="left"><a
        href="http://ads.knoxnews.com/OAS/rm/try-it.cgi/www.knoxnews.com/up_front/up_front.htm@Position2"><img
        src="http://ads.knoxnews.com/OAS/rm/adstream.cgi/www.knoxnews.com/up_front/up_front.htm@Position2"
        align="center" border="0" width="2" height="2" ismap></a>
        <br>
        <a href="/"><br>
        </a><img src="../../images/v3/othernews.gif" width="108"
        height="21"></p>
        <p align="left"><a href="4380.htm"><font size="2">Welfare
        plan shows results in 3 months of operation</font></a><font
        size="2"> </font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><!--MENUITEM--></font></p>
        </td>
        <td width="25">&nbsp;</td>
        <td valign="top" width="450"><p align="left"><br>
        <img src="../../images/heads/upfront.gif" alt="Up Front"
        width="415" height="58"><br>
        <br>
        <img src="../images/0120bird1mp.jpg" alt="Runaway rhea"
        width="300" height="182"><br>
        <img src="../../images/v3/credits/MPcredit.gif"
        width="144" height="21"><br>
        <font size="2"><strong>Tommy Prince, a Knox County school
        board member, tries <br>
        to lasso a rhea with help from his son, Rollin Prince,
        14, <br>
        and passerby Sharon Howard. The rhea finally was caught.</strong></font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="6"><b>Runaway rhea</b></font><br>
        <font size="5"><br>
        Bird snared after 2-hour chase in West Knoxville</font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Randy Kenner, News-Sentinel staff
        writer</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">T</font>ommy Prince conceded he's ''no
        Stan Brock,'' but Monday afternoon, Prince did his best
        imitation of the ''Wild Kingdom'' star as he and others
        chased down a young rhea in the wilds of West Knoxville. </p>
        <p>''It was a circuitous route, maybe three (miles),
        maybe half a mile as the crow flies,'' the Knox County
        school board member later joked. </p>
        <p>The rhea, a tall South American bird that resembles
        the African ostrich but is smaller, was finally hemmed in
        and captured by Alcoa schoolteacher Sharon Howard after a
        nearly two-hour chase that started in the Suburban Hills
        subdivision and ended just off Gleason Road. In between,
        the rhea made jaunts through the Concepts 21 apartments
        complex parking lot, the area around Gallaher Memorial
        Baptist Church and down Gallaher View Road. </p>
        <p>''He got in a thicket and when he got tangled up, I
        grabbed him and just hung on,'' Howard said of the
        stong-legged bird. ''It took everything I had to hold
        him.'' </p>
        <p>Howard and her husband, Ronnie, carried the apparently
        uninjured but somewhat tired animal to the University of
        Tennessee Veterinary Hospital in the back of their
        pickup. </p>
        <p>Sharon Howard, who rode in the bed of the truck with
        the rhea, said it occasionally lifted its head over the
        tailgate to look around during the trip. </p>
        <p>''We'd be driving along, and someone would pull up to
        pass us and . . . they'd do a double take,'' she said. </p>
        <p>The bird was still at UT Monday evening. Its owner had
        called the school looking for the rhea after discovering
        it was missing but had not yet arrived to retrieve it. </p>
        <p>According to Prince, the chase started just after noon
        Monday while he was working in his backyard and heard
        what sounded like footsteps coming through a wooded area
        being his house. He looked up, expecting to see a person.
        He saw something else instead. </p>
        <p>''I looked up and (thought) it was an emu or an
        ostrich,'' Prince said. </p>
        <p>Concerned the animal might get hit by a car, Prince
        enlisted the help of his three children, Rollin, Nathan
        and Merry Katherine, to help corral the bird. Neighbor
        Joe Goeltz also became involved in the chase. </p>
        <p>It proved to be harder than expected because the
        flightless bird turned out to be a fleet-footed runner. </p>
        <p>''Oh yeah, it's amazing how it could (run),'' Prince
        said. </p>
        <p>The Howards and their two sons, Jason and Chris,
        joined the pursuit when the bird ran out in front of them
        on Gleason Road. </p>
        <p>''We saw him and there were some kids from the
        neighborhood chasing him,'' Sharon Howard of Maryville
        said. ''I was afraid he was going to get hit by a car''
        or that dogs might get him. </p>
        <p>The bird was cornered two or three times, according to
        Prince, but somehow managed to elude its pursuers. </p>
        <p>''It seemed like forever,'' Howard said of the chase. </p>
        <p>She said she had caught animals before but ''never
        something this big.'' </p>
        <p>Prince said the rhea was calm after it was finally
        caught. </p>
        <p>''It was worn out, bless its heart,'' Prince said.
        ''And so was I.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
