<head>
	<title>UT students hold campus march for MLK Day</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>UT students hold campus march for MLK Day</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Wesley Loy, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT>ith a day off from classes, University of Tennessee student Jonathan Brown spent Monday marching to commemorate the most famous of civil rights marchers -- Martin Luther King Jr.
<P>   &#39;&#39;That&#39;s the least we can do,&#39;&#39; said Brown, a junior defensive end on the UT football team.
<P>   Brown was joined by nearly 200 other students and UT staffers in marching across campus Monday -- inauguration day for President Clinton but also the official MLK holiday.
<P>   The multiracial marchers held candles as they moved silently from the Torchbearer statue in Circle Park down Volunteer Boulevard to the University Center, where they were treated to a two-hour program of skits, singing, dancing and impassioned speeches.
<P>   A big banner bore the march&#39;s theme: &#39;&#39;There is no progress without struggle.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The event was sponsored by the Black Cultural Programming Committee, a student group that, aside from the annual march, brings speakers and entertainers to campus.
<P>   Student marchers said remembering King is vital to pushing his dream of racial harmony and justice.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I&#39;m hoping this march is a step toward realizing Dr. King&#39;s dream -- a cultural celebration, racial understanding and brotherhood, or actually brother and sisterhood,&#39;&#39; said Kathy Kaplan, a 19-year-old sports broadcasting major at UT.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think Dr. King was the great American hero,&#39;&#39; said Paul Weathers, a 22-year-old also majoring in broadcasting. &#39;&#39;I&#39;d rather be doing this than watching the inauguration on TV, watching a bunch of white liberals taking all the credit for what he did.&#39;&#39;
<P>   March coordinator Darnell Reid, speaking over a bullhorn, told marchers to &#39;&#39;imagine the hostility and pain&#39;&#39; marchers endured during the height of the civil rights movement.
<P>   In the University Center auditorium, marchers heard spirited songs by the Love United Gospel Choir, a student singing group, and racially charged skits by student actors in FOCUS -- Finding Our Common Understandings and Strengths. The skits were a raw display of bigotry -- against blacks, against gays, against foreigners, against overweight people -- to demonstrate the absurdity of prejudice.
<P>   A Carter High School student, Syreeta Dickerson, 16, also read her winning essay, &#39;&#39;The Impact of My Success in the Strawberry Plains Community.&#39;&#39; The paper told of her struggle for acceptance as the first black drum major at the predominantly white school.
<P>   Keynote speaker for Monday&#39;s event was Faye Harrison, associate professor of anthropology at UT. Harrison, saying her remarks were aimed mainly at &#39;&#39;members of the hip-hop and X generations,&#39;&#39; said global economic changes -- the displacement of jobs by technology, for example, and corporate exploitation of cheap labor -- do not bode well for the world&#39;s underclasses, including American blacks.
<P>   King, she said, progressed from the political goal of integration to the bigger goal of fundamental social change, including economic justice for all.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
