        <p align="left"><font size="2">Got a business news tip?
        E-mail it to </font><a href="mailto:biznews@knoxnews.com"><font
        size="2">biznews@knoxnews.com</font></a></p>
        </td>
        <td width="25">&nbsp;</td>
        <td valign="top" width="450"><p align="left"><br>
        <img src="../../site/images/business.gif" alt="Business"
        width="415" height="58"><br>
        <br>
<!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->        <font size="6"><b>Media analysts credit HGTV for finding
        right niche</b></font><br>
<!--SUBHEAD-->        </p>
        
        
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Duncan Mansfield, Associated
        Press</i></font></p>
        <p><font size="3"><!--dateline--></font><br>
        <font size="5">I</font>daho retiree Chris Hoobs has been
        hooked on Home &amp; Garden Television ever since it went
        on the air in December 1994. He is not alone. </p>
        <p>An avid woodworker and home remodeler, Hoobs wrote the
        Knoxville-based cable network that he and his wife ''feel
        like kids in a candy shop'' tuning in at home in Emmett,
        some 30 miles from Boise. </p>
        <p>''We don't feel that way any more,'' he says today,
        chuckling. ''It's gotten better.'' </p>
        <p>Barely two years since its launch, HGTV is being
        hailed by media analysts as ''one of the most promising
        cable networks'' in recent years. </p>
        <p>Quality programming, strong advertiser support and
        ''an attractive niche in a pretty crowded marketplace''
        are just some of the reasons, says Kevin Kupinski of A.G.
        Edwards &amp; Sons in St. Louis. </p>
        <p>Home &amp; Garden's subscriber base has nearly
        quadrupled in two years to 22 million homes -- nearly one
        out of every three cable homes in the country -- with
        commitments for 6 million more. </p>
        <p>''We have not seen networks of that size fail,
        historically,'' says Larry Gerbrandt, an analyst with
        Paul Kagan Associates Inc. in California, who considers
        expansion of cable system access a top priority for new
        networks. </p>
        <p>The network devoted to ''everything you love about
        home'' is pushing into the major markets of Chicago, New
        York and Los Angeles. Late this year, it will become 24
        hours a day in Canada. Deals for Europe and Australia
        aren't far off. </p>
        <p>''They have earned the distribution they are
        getting,'' says Mike Smith, spokesman for Colorado-based
        Tele-Communications Inc., which in December began
        aggressively promoting HGTV to its local system
        operators. </p>
        <p>TCI, the nation's largest cable company with 14
        million subscribers, is impressed that HGTV has spent a
        lot of time and money ''creating a vision and following
        that vision with original programming,'' Smith says. </p>
        <p>HGTV's list of national advertisers has grown from 40
        to nearly 700. While do-it-yourselfer chains like Lowe's
        and Home Depot and their product manufacturers dominate,
        the Big Three automakers are among those finding HGTV a
        place to be. </p>
        <p>The response from viewers continues to astonish even
        HGTV executives. One recent Saturday morning, the network
        aired its first viewer call-in show, hosted by weatherman
        and HGTV wine connoisseur Spencer Christian. HGTV experts
        took questions on everything from gardening to interior
        decorating, building to rebuilding. </p>
        <p>''We purposely didn't promote it at all,'' says Ken
        Lowe, HGTV founder, president and CEO. ''We wanted to
        make sure, since this was our first one, 'let's get it
        right.' It was almost like a dress rehearsal.'' </p>
        <p>The response? Ten thousand calls in two hours. </p>
        <p>''It was spectacular. We were truly overwhelmed,''
        Lowe says. </p>
        <p>In addition, HGTV broadcast its Internet address
        (http://www.hgtv.com) for the first time. The network's
        file server jammed with 50,000 e-mail queries from 47
        states. </p>
        <p>Lowe recalls it wasn't so long ago that he was
        peddling his concept for Home &amp; Garden Television on
        fraying poster boards to his bosses at E.W. Scripps Co.
        in Cincinnati. Scripps' holdings include nine television
        stations and daily newspapers in 16 markets, including
        The Knoxville News-Sentinel. </p>
        <p>''As Ken began to outline this idea and as we
        talked,'' Scripps senior vice president Frank Gardner
        says, ''it was clear . . . this was not some spur of the
        moment notion that he had had, but this was the product
        of several years' worth of very meticulous thought.'' </p>
        <p>Scripps gave the OK. It bought an established cable
        programming studio in Knoxville, Cinetel Productions, and
        built HGTV's new headquarters next door. It found
        executive talent from the ranks of established networks,
        such as HBO, NBC and E! And it committed $50 million to
        the project, then upped it to $75 million. </p>
        <p>Lowe and Susan Packard, HGTV's chief operating
        officer, say the network is on course to begin showing a
        profit in its fourth year. </p>
        <p>Unusual for cable television, this has been
        accomplished: </p>
        <p>Without selling off pieces to cable operators, as
        Turner Broadcasting did. </p>
        <p>Without paying for new subscribers. Rubert Murdoch
        reportedly offered $12 a subscriber for the Fox News
        Channel. </p>
        <p>Without requiring HGTV hosts use advertiser products. </p>
        <p>Without filling the schedule with reruns. Eighty
        percent of HGTV's content is original; 100 percent during
        prime time. </p>
        <p>''It really is sort of a Cinderella story,'' Packard
        says. ''Now we are at a point where we are maturing,
        where (the industry) is putting us in a completely
        different category. You know, we are now one of the
        players.'' </p>
        <p><font size="2"><strong>Copyright 1997 by the
        Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use
        is probihited. </p</strong></strong></font><strong> </strong></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
