<!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
<BASEFONT SIZE="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Planned lawsuit protests Farragut zoning</B></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Builders' group, landowners claim less affluent are hurt</FONT><P>
</basefont><FONT size="2"><I>By Bob Womack, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE="3"><!--dateline--></FONT></B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">Z</FONT>oning regulations in Farragut violate property rights granted by the Fifth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, the Tennessee Valley Home Builders Association alleges in a lawsuit expected to be filed in Knox County Chancery Court today.
<P>   Mike Carlton, president of the organization, says the laws are a deliberate attempt by the town to keep less affluent people from living in Farragut.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They have planned a community only for the affluent,&#39;&#39; Carlton said Monday in explaining the reasons behind the pending filing of the suit.
<P>   &#39;&#39;By the time you meet all the regulations, there is no way you can have the number of units (the regulations) allow.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Carlton said the average cost of a house throughout Knox County is about $107,000. In Farragut, the average cost is &#39;&#39;well over 220,000,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>   He said zoning ordinances adopted last year and another new ordinance about to be approved that regulate development of single-family homes on small lots, of condominiums, of townhouses and of apartments do not help the situation.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They tell you, &#39;We are giving you small lots and apartments,&#39; but the large print giveth and the small print taketh away,&#39;&#39; Carlton said.
<P>   The home builders are being joined in the suit by several property owners in Farragut who claim regulations have prevented them from developing a 7-acre tract they own on Kingston Pike. They are Cecil L. and Betty V. Byrd, James R. &#39;&#39;Buddy&#39;&#39; White, White Family Ltd. and White Family Partnerships.
<P>   According to the suit to be filed, they allege they submitted an application to the town in August 1996 to rezone the property for development of multifamily housing, such as apartments or condominiums. They said the town returned the application and advised them there was no such zoning as they had requested.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Thus, the property owners were deprived of the use of their property and the anticipated profits that would flow from a reasonable development of the property,&#39;&#39; the suit alleges.
<P>   The plaintiffs also said the housing was intended for &#39;&#39;the elderly, handicapped and low-income citizens who have been deprived of adequate housing within the town of Farragut.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The suit also contends the ordinances require developers to set aside a certain amount of property for buffer strips, setbacks and slope requirements. Furthermore, they must set aside land for community open space for recreational purposes and provide bicycle paths.
<P>   &#39;&#39;All of (these) are designed to discourage residential development and residential building. There is no rational basis between these ordinances and the governmental interests they seek to address,&#39;&#39; the suit contends.
<P>   It alleges the effect of the regulations is to &#39;&#39;price the land and dwelling unit out of the market.&#39;&#39;   The regulations have the effect of taking property without just compensation, the suit alleges.
<P>   The plaintiffs will ask the court to strike down the ordinances and declare that the town is not operating legally because it does not provide police and fire services, a school system, and &#39;&#39;many of the usual municipal services&#39;&#39; that other governmental entities provide.
<P>
<P>
<P>
        </p>
        <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>
