<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td colspan="4"><img src="../../images/heads/food.gif"
        alt="Food" width="400" height="244"></td>
        <td width="15">&nbsp;</td>
        <td valign="bottom" width="180" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">&nbsp;<font
        size="3"><em>Week of Wednesday, January 15, 1997<!--MENUDATE--></em></font></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td colspan="4" width="470"><font size="6"><b>Feast at
        Fest</b></font><br>
        <font size="5"><br>
        Chocoholics will wallow in sweets at Chocolate Fest this
        weekend</font><p><font size="2"><i>By Louise Durman,
        News-Sentinel Food editor</i></font></p>
        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"
        width="250" align="right">
            <tr>
                <td><img src="../images/Food3.jpg" width="250"
                height="176"><br>
                <img src="../../images/v3/credits/COcredit.gif"
                alt="Photo by Clay Owen, News-Sentinel staff"
                width="144" height="21"><p><font size="2"><strong>Winners
                in the Chocolate Fest cookie contest at East Town
                Mall are, from left, Teresa Lee, third place with
                chocolate chippers; Peter Shanklee, second place
                with cartwheels, and Barbara Tenney, first place
                with gourmet mint brownies.</strong></font></p>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">C</font>ooks came bearing cookies --
        chocolate, of course. </p>
        <p>The occasion was a cookie contest last Wednesday as a
        preview to the 11th annual Chocolate Fest. </p>
        <p>Chocolate Fest will be Saturday, Jan. 18, 10 a.m. to 4
        p.m., on both levels of East Towne Mall, regardless of
        weather. </p>
        <p>Thirty contestants brought cookies to East Towne last
        week for tasting by judges. </p>
        <p>Winners were Barbara Tenney, first place, with gourmet
        mint brownies; six-year-old Peter Shankles, second with
        cartwheels, and Teresa Lee, third with chocolate
        chippers. </p>
        <p>The Shankles family delighted contestants and others
        who stopped by Center Court at the mall to peek at the
        cookies displayed on a table. </p>
        <p>Besides Peter, his brothers, Stevie, 10, and Andrew,
        8, had entries. Mom Karen Shankles was there with the two
        other children, Molly, 4, and Jonathan, 2. She and the
        kids made the cookies together, and the boys entered the
        cookie they named. Peter named the chocolately-pecan
        cartwheels. </p>
        <p>White Lily Foods Co. was co-sponsor of the cookie
        contest, and Belinda Ellis, White Lily consumer service
        manager, judged the contest along with Walter Lambert,
        The News-Sentinel restaurant reviewer and Channel 8
        television chef; Bonnie Sheeley, Knox County agricultural
        extension service, and Ellis Bacon, owner of the South's
        Finest Chocolate Factory. Bacon has been a participant in
        Chocolate Fest since its beginning. </p>
        <p>New to Chocolate Fest this year will be a cafe for
        ''private dining'' at Center Court in the mall. Cookie
        contest winners, judges and event sponsors received
        tickets to Chocolate Fest and an invitation to dine at
        the new cafe on samples from participating chocolatiers. </p>
        <p>Thirty-one area chocolatiers will participate with
        delectables like fudge, cheesecake, ice creams, coffee,
        mousse, cake, candies and more. Those attending are
        encouraged to bring along a container to take samples
        they can't eat on the site home with them.<b> </b>Containers
        also will be available for purchase at the fest. </p>
        <p>Entertainment is planned during the day for adults and
        children at the family-oriented event. </p>
        <p>Cost is $10 and tickets will be available at the
        registration desk at East Towne Saturday. Proceeds
        benefit the National Kidney Foundation of East Tennessee.
        For information on purchasing tickets before the event,
        call 688-5481. </p>
        <p>Following are the winning recipes: </p>
        <p>Gourmet mint brownies </p>
        <p><b>Brownies:</b> </p>
        <p>1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, softened </p>
        <p>1/4 cup sugar </p>
        <p>1 egg </p>
        <p>1 teaspoon peppermint extract (not peppermint oil) </p>
        <p>4 drops green food coloring </p>
        <p>1 cup margarine or butter </p>
        <p>4 ounces (4 squares) un<b>sweetened chocolate, cut
        into pieces </b></p>
        <p><b>2 cups sugar </b></p>
        <p><b>2 teaspoons vanilla </b></p>
        <p><b>4 eggs </b></p>
        <p><b>1 cup all-purpose flour</b> </p>
        <p><b>Frosting:</b> </p>
        <p>2 tablespoons margarine or butter </p>
        <p>2 tablespoons corn syrup </p>
        <p>2 tablespoons water </p>
        <p>2 ounces (2 squares) un<b>sweetened chocolate, cut
        into pieces </b></p>
        <p><b>1 teaspoon vanilla </b></p>
        <p><b>1 cup confectioners' sugar</b> </p>
        <p><b>Garnish:</b> </p>
        <p><b>Sugared mint leaves and violets</b> </p>
        <p>Brownies: Heat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour
        9-by-13-inch pan. </p>
        <p>In small bowl, beat cream cheese and 1/4 cup sugar
        until smooth. Add 1 egg, mint extract and food coloring;
        mix well. Set aside. </p>
        <p>In large saucepan, melt margarine and chocolate over
        very low heat, stirring constantly. Remove from heat;
        cool slightly. Stir in sugar and vanilla. Add 4 eggs, one
        at a time, beating well after each addition. </p>
        <p>Lightly spoon flour into measuring cup; level off.
        Stir flour into chocolate mixture; mix well. Spread in
        prepared pan. Carefully spoon prepared cream cheese
        filling over brownie mixture. Gently cut through layers
        with knife to marble. </p>
        <p>Bake at 350 degrees for 45 to 50 minutes or until set.
        Cool completely. </p>
        <p>Frosting: In heavy saucepan, bring margarine, corn
        syrup and water to a rolling boil. Remove from heat. Add
        chocolate; stir until melted. Stir in vanilla and enough
        confectioners' sugar for desired spreading consistency.
        Beat until smooth. Frost cooled bars. </p>
        <p>Cut into 36 bars. Store in refrigerator, if desired. </p>
        <p>If desired, garnish with sugared fresh mint leaves and
        violets using egg white and superfine sugar. Tenney
        purchases boxes of Domino brand superfine sugar at Food
        Lion. </p>
        <p>Whip egg white until foamy using a fork. Use a small
        brush and brush the egg white on the top and bottom of
        mint leaves and violets. Place on a piece of wax paper
        and sprinkle superfine sugar on leaves and violets using
        a flour sifter or salt shaker. Let them dry at room
        temperature. Store in airtight container for three or
        four days. </p>
        <p>Source: Barbara Tenney. </p>
        <p>Cartwheels </p>
        <p><b>21/4 cups all-purpose flour </b></p>
        <p><b>1 teaspoon baking soda </b></p>
        <p><b>1 cup butter or margarine, softened </b></p>
        <p><b>1/4 cup granulated sugar </b></p>
        <p><b>3/4 cup brown sugar, packed </b></p>
        <p><b>1/2 teaspoon vanilla </b></p>
        <p><b>1/2 teaspoon butter flavoring (optional) </b></p>
        <p><b>1 (31/2-ounce) package vanilla flavor instant
        pudding mix </b></p>
        <p><b>2 eggs </b></p>
        <p><b>1 cup semisweet chocolate morsels </b></p>
        <p><b>1 cup pecans, coarsely chopped </b></p>
        <p><b>3 cups pecan halves </b></p>
        <p><b>12 ounces chocolate flavored bark (candy) coating</b>
        </p>
        <p>Preheat oven to 350 degrees. </p>
        <p>Combine flour and soda; set aside. </p>
        <p>In large bowl, combine butter, sugars, vanilla and
        butter flavorings and pudding mix. Beat until smooth and
        creamy. Beat in eggs. Gradually add flour mixture. Stir
        in chocolate morsels and chopped pecans. </p>
        <p>Drop by tablespoonsful about 2 inches apart on lightly
        greased baking sheet. Press pecan halves into the sides
        of each cookie so they stick out from the dough like
        spokes from the center of a wheel. </p>
        <p>Bake at 350 for 10 to 12 minutes or until dough is set
        and only very slightly browned. </p>
        <p>Cool on pan 2 to 3 minutes before removing cookies to
        a wire rack to finish cooling. </p>
        <p>Melt candy coating in microwave safe dish, according
        to package directions. Drizzle melted chocolate coating
        over cooled cookies, leaving pecan halves exposed. </p>
        <p>Store in airtight container. </p>
        <p>Yield: 4 dozen cookies. </p>
        <p>Note: The chocolate flavored bark or candy coating is
        available at Kroger's. </p>
        <p>Source: Peter Shankles. </p>
        <p>Chocolate chippers </p>
        <p><b>1 cup solid shortening </b></p>
        <p><b>1 cup granulated sugar </b></p>
        <p><b>1/2 cup brown sugar </b></p>
        <p><b>2 eggs </b></p>
        <p><b>2 teaspoons vanilla </b></p>
        <p><b>2 cups all-purpose flour </b></p>
        <p><b>1 teaspoon salt </b></p>
        <p><b>1 teaspoon baking soda </b></p>
        <p><b>1 (16-ounce) package chocolate morsels </b></p>
        <p>Beat together shortening, sugars, eggs and vanilla.
        Sift dry ingredients together and mix into sugar mixture.
        Drop from a teaspoon on ungreased cookie sheet. Bake at
        325 degrees about 15 minutes. Do not overbake. </p>
        <p>Makes 24 cookies. </p>
        <p>Source: Teresa Lee. (She uses Crisco as the
        shortening.) </p>
        </td>
        <td width="15">&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
        <td valign="top" width="180" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">&nbsp;<br>
