        width="415" height="58"></p>
        <p><br>
<!--FIRST STORY TEMPLATE-->
<BASEFONT SIZE="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>New arrivals have a stabilizing effect</B></FONT><BR><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
</basefont><FONT size="2"><I>By Bill Luther, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE="3"><!--dateline--></FONT></B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">M</FONT>OORESVILLE, N.C. -- The Sophomore Blues are no more for the Michael Kranefuss/Carl Haas Winston Cup team owners.
<P>   The arrival of driver Jeremy Mayfield in October and crew chief Paul Andrews three months later, appears to have stabilized the Ford team to the point. Kranefuss said, &#39;&#39;I firmly believe we can forget the 1996 season.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Kranefuss pulled off a swap with Cale Yarborough, another Ford owner, getting Mayfield for John Andretti. Then Tim Brewer, who ranks second in career victories for a crew chief, departed. The moves were like winning a chess match.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think the changes will pay off this season,&#39;&#39; Kranefuss said. &#39;&#39;Paul was the first crew chief I went to after Brewer and I separated. With Paul&#39;s stablizing force, Jeremy and the young guys have a good future.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Afer showing flashes of promise in 1995, Mayfield, 27, had other offers but it was Kranefuss&#39; choice from the start.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Where we are (starting the 1997 season) is high for this team. Everything is going better than I had thought,&#39;&#39; Mayfield said. &#39;&#39;We had a pretty good situation going when we got the ball going. It would have been hard to make it different.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Andrews also had the right credentials which included the 1992 Winston Cup championship for the late Alan Kulwicki. He spent five years and five races with Kulwicki, who died in a plane clash while approaching Tri-City Airport less than three miles from Bristol Motor Speedway. Andrews remained with the team through the 1996 season.
<P>   &#39;&#39;New faces and new drivers give you a real good feeling,&#39;&#39; Andrews said. &#39;&#39;The transition for me has been easy. There are a lot of good people on this team and you don&#39;t take charge over night. It has been a good job getting ready for Daytona.
<P>   
<P>   Kranefuss said, &#39;&#39;I watched Mayfield, saw a lot of things that were like Rusty (Wallace). I knew it would take a while to adjust to a different team. You can&#39;t buy wins. You&#39;ve got to be able to buy drivers with the right information.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Mayfield finished 34th in points last season and shoots for a 15th position this year.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I had to run hard and learn a lot in 1994 after I went to Cale. He was my hero when he was winning championships,&#39;&#39; Mayfield said. &#39;&#39;I had to work hard to get in with a race team when I started (1993).
<P>   &#39;&#39;Preparation for a season is a big cost so I stay out of the shop and let the crew do what they can. We work together and hope to put a good team together. I want to give them something to work with and they will try to do the same for me.&#39;&#39;
<P>   While with Kulwicki, Andrews produced five victories, two of those during the championship season. That was a huge plus when Geoff Bodine purchased the team nearly seven months after Kulwicki&#39;s death.
<P>   &#39;&#39;When we won the title in 1992, the problem was being one of the least financed teams,&#39;&#39; Andrews said. &#39;&#39;It would be hard to swallow it now. The quickest thing to do (reduce costs) is to be in the top 15 in points after the first four races. The most important thing is to start each race.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
        </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        </td>
    </tr>
