<head>
	<title>Audit: Schools&#39; outside special ed counsel OK</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Audit: Schools&#39; outside special ed counsel OK</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">S</FONT>tate auditors have agreed with what Knox County lawyers and school officials have said for months:
<P>   There&#39;s nothing illegal about hiring an out-of-state lawyer to represent the school system in special education cases, and despite legal expenses, special education funding has increased annually for several years.
<P>   Special education students range from those with minor learning disabilities to others with severe physical handicaps or behavioral problems.
<P>   The school system has retained Atlanta lawyer Charles Weatherly to help fight lawsuits that school officials said would force them to provide unnecessary and costly services.
<P>   Local lawyer Mark Jendrek has complained that $185,000 paid to Weatherly in fiscal 1994 and 1995 was improper. He made his argument ultimately to county commissioners, but school officials and the county Law Department said the spending was proper.
<P>   The Tennessee Department of Education&#39;s audit section agreed with local officials in a report issued Dec. 16. The school board received the report this week.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Based on interviews conducted with state personnel and tests of the accounting records, it appears the Knox County School System has not illegally or improperly budgeted funds for outside counsel and has not used federal funds to pay legal fees,&#39;&#39; the audit report states.
<P>   Chris Steppee, director of internal audit for the state Department of Education, said Weatherly was paid $154,600 in fiscal 1995 and $191,200 in fiscal 1996. State officials couldn&#39;t say Friday who filed the complaint that led to their audit. Jendrek said he didn&#39;t file it.
<P>   The audit examined whether:
<P>   * Funds for outside counsel were illegally and improperly budgeted. At issue was whether legal fees are properly budgeted for &#39;&#39;special education services.&#39;&#39; Auditors said budgeting was proper.
<P>   * Funds were spent on legal fees in lieu of special education services. &#39;&#39;We found that the system had consistently increased its spending each year for the Special Education Program,&#39;&#39; auditors said.
<P>   * Federal funds were used to pay legal fees. The audit found they weren&#39;t.
<P>   John McCook, director of pupil personnel for the school system, said he learned of the audit findings this week. &#39;&#39;We were happy,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;We didn&#39;t think we had done anything wrong.&#39;&#39;
<P>   School board Chairwoman Margaret Maddox said paying an expert lawyer to avoid unnecessary costs actually helps special education students.
<P>   &#39;&#39;If anything, we save money to put back in the program,&#39;&#39; Maddox said.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
