<head>
	<title>Wanted: Three bears minus wanderlust</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Wanted: Three bears minus wanderlust</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Morgan Simmons, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><FONT SIZE="+2">R</FONT>esearchers are looking for three more black bears to complete a re-introduction project in the Big South Fork National River and Recreation Area.
<P>   Dr. Joe Clark, director of the Southern Appalachian Field Laboratory for the National Biological Service, said the bears will compensate for ones that wandered off after being relocated last summer.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Right now we&#39;re locating them with telemetry so we&#39;ll know where they are when we move them in early March,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;By then, they&#39;ll still be hibernating and hopefully with cubs.&#39;&#39;
<P>   The three bears -- like all the bears used in the project -- will come from the Great Smoky Mountains National Park. The Big South Fork project is an experimental reintroduction with a limit of 12 bears. Females are being used because they have smaller home ranges and are less likely to disperse than males.
<P>   The Big South Fork bear project began last winter with the capture of six female bears -- three of them pregnant and three with cubs. Once at Big South Fork, the bears were placed in dens to resume hibernation.
<P>   Last summer an additional six female bears were taken from the Great Smoky Mountains National Park and released into a remote area of Big South Fork after spending two weeks in acclimating pens. Of the six summer-release bears, two stayed inside the 115,000-acre Big South Fork area.
<P>   Clark said the purpose of the study -- a cooperative effort between the National Biological Service, the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency, the National Park Service, and the Kentucky Department of Fish and Wildlife Resources -- is to test which technique, summer or winter, works best at minimizing the bears&#39; instinct to return home.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The distinction between the two seems clear,&#39;&#39; said Clark. &#39;&#39;The summer-release bears wandered around, and they had more mortalities.&#39;&#39;
<P>   To date, there are seven adult female black bears and a number of cubs in the Big South Fork as a result of the yearlong project. Clark said one of the summer bears has established a home range at Cumberland Gap National Historical Park.
<P>   Clark said that of the winter-released bears, the ones moved to Big South Fork with new cubs tend to stick to the area better than pregnant bears, which often wander around before re-denning for the rest of the winter.
<P>   A graduate student from the University of Tennessee is monitoring the bears&#39; movements every week. This winter he will check for cub survival, physical condition and denning preferences.
<P>   Black bears once roamed all over Kentucky and Tennessee, including the Big South Fork area, but were eliminated due to unregulated hunting and habitat destruction. Biologists say Big South Fork and surrounding woodlands, such as the Daniel Boone National Forest, offer a quarter-million acres of potential bear habitat.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Big South Fork has a much younger forest than the Smokies,&#39;&#39; said Clark. &#39;&#39;There are more roads, more openings. If we check the bears and find they&#39;re all skin and bones, we&#39;ll know they had a bad year.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
