<html>
<head>
	<title>East Tennessee briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper, Detours, Entertianment, Music, Arts">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
            <basefont size=6>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>East Tennessee briefs</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		</basefont><h3>Boyfriend faces charges after Cocke woman shot</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>   NEWPORT -- A 25-year-old Cocke County woman was placed on a life-support system Monday following an early morning shooting, authorities said. The victim&#39;s boyfriend was charged with attempted first-degree murder.
<P>   April Hawthorne was shot in the forehead with a .22-caliber rifle about 2 a.m. Monday, Cocke County Sheriff&#39;s Department officials said. Her boyfriend and roommate, Ricky Williams, 25, is accused of shooting Hawthorne inside their home in the Point Pleasant community.
<P>   Williams told investigators he and Hawthorne argued Sunday before he left for a friend&#39;s house and an evening of drinking.
<P>   After returning home, Williams told authorities, he was &#39;&#39;(fooling) with the weapon&#39;&#39; when he fired three shots.
<P>   Investigators determined the third bullet passed through a blanket that was hanging in a doorway and struck the victim.
<P>   Williams was arraigned Monday by Cocke County General Sessions Judge Marcus Mooneyham, who set bond at $100,000 and told investigators the charge may be upgraded to first-degree murder if Hawthorne&#39;s injuries prove fatal.
<P>   Detective Robert Caldwell said Hawthorne is on a life-support system in the intensive care unit of Baptist Hospital of Cocke County.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><h3>Bid-opening scheduled for Interstate 24 ramp</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>    MURFREESBORO -- The state Department of Transportation plans to open bids March 21 on a new exit ramp off Interstate 24, said state Rep. Mary Ann Eckles.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s an interchange improvement for I-24 from Chattanooga and going to Outlets Ltd. Mall,&#39;&#39; said Eckles, D-Murfreesboro.
<P>    Currently, motorists who exit I-24 North and want to go to Franklin must make a left onto Old Fort Parkway.
<P>   &#39;&#39;There are cases when trucks pull out from the access ramp turning left toward Franklin and cause congestion,&#39;&#39; said Dana Richardson, Murfreesboro traffic director.
<P>    Richardson said the turn had caused several accidents over the years.
<P>
<P>
