<P><B>BYERS, JOSEPH EDWARD &#39;&#39;JOE&#39;&#39; - </B>age 71, of West Knoxville, passed away Sunday morning, January 19, 1997, at his home. He was retired from Knoxville Truck Sales. A member of Centerview Baptist Church. A veteran of World War II, serving in th Navy. Preceded in death by: Maxey and Naomi Bartlett Byers; brothers, Billy, Robert, and William Byers. Survivors: wife of 53 years, Betty Clapp Byers; children and spouses, David and Diana Byers of Kingston, Clara Jean Byers Clapp, Maxey and Patty Byers, Linda Coker, all of Knoxville; seven grandchildren; six great-grandchildren; two step-grandchildren; and two step-great-grandchildren; sisters, Irene Bullock of Alabama, Thelma Dunnam of Texas; several nieces and nephews. The family will receive friends from 5-7 p.m. Tuesday, followed by funeral services at 7 p.m. in the Click Funeral Home Chapel, Rev. Doug Green and Rev. Ed Cagley officiating. Graveside services 11 a.m. Wednesday, Pleasant Forest Cemetery. Pallbearers: Henry Kelley, Jim McAfee, Martin Brown, Earl Childress, Jim Jenkins, and Keith Jones. Click Funeral Home, Lenoir City, in charge.
<P>
<P>CARVER, CAPTAIN MICHAEL CHIL<B>TON, USN RETIRED - </B>on Friday evening, January 17, Dr. Michael Chilton Carver expired at the ancestral home on Valley Home Road. A native son of Morristown, his family was long associated with the Carver Wagon Company, a pioneer industry that survived into the 1930&#39;s. An enthusiastic supporter of the Boy Scouts of America, Dr. Carver was among the first Eagle Scouts of Morristown. A graduate of the University of North Carolina, he attended medical school at the University of Tennessee in Memphis. Following an internship at the John Gaston Hospital in the city, he began a career in the United States Navy which spanned more than twenty years. He commenced active duty in April 1951. He reported for duty at the School of Aviation Medicine, Pensacola, Fla. and was designated a flight surgeon in September 1957. After operational tours with Fleet Aircraft Service Squadron 106, Argentia, Newfoundland, and Carrier Airwing, 10 in Is Essex (CVA-9), and later USS Shangri La (CVA-38), he entered residency training in Aerospace Medicine. Upon completion of Board Certification in this specialty, he reported as medical officer, USS Constellation (CVA-64). Following a brief tour as assisted manager officer, NAS Whidby, he was Chief, Schools Division, at the Naval Aerospace Medical Institute, Pensacola, Fla. Subsequent service was at the Naval Regional Medical Center, Pensacola. He was commanding officer of the Naval Regional Medical Center on Guam and of the Naval Regional Medical Center at the NAS Millington, Tenn., from which station he retired from the Navy with the rank of Captain. Since 1980, Dr. Carver has served as the Chief Medical Officer for the Tennessee Department of Public Health in this area, supervising several counties but stationed primarily in Hamblen County. He is past secretary of the Hamblen Medical Society and has been actively involved in all matters of public health in this area. Dr. Carver is the son of William D. and Hattie Miller Carver, and is the brother of Benjamin M. Carver, all of whom preceded him in death. Dr. Carver is survived by: his wife, Sammy Y. Carver; his daughter, Rachel C. Burleson, of Salisburg, Md.; and sons, Michael C. Carver, Jr. of Spartenburg, S.C. and Robert S. Carver of Nashville, Tenn.; he is also survived by several nieces and nephews. The family will receive friends at Stetzer&#39;s Funeral Home in Morristown from 7-9 p.m. on Tuesday evening. The funeral will be held at the First United Methodist Church, at 2 p.m. on Wednesday afternoon with interment at Jarnigan Cemetery. Memorial donations may be made to the choir of the First United Methodist Church of Morristown or to the United States Navy Memorial Foundation, Box 12728, Arlington, VA 22209-8728. Stetzer Funeral Home, in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>CLAPP, HELEN (PAYNE) - </B>age 91, of North Knoxville, died 2  p.m. Monday, January 20, 1997, at the family home. Member of Oakwood Baptist Church. Preceded in death by son, Ronnie, parents, sister and a brother. Member of the National Honor Society. Volunteer for many years with St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center Auxiliary. Survivors: husband of 65 years, Hollis W. Clapp; son and daughter-in-law, David and Margaret Clapp; granddaughters, Jennifer and Rachel Clapp; sister-in-law and brother-in-law, Eloise and Creyl Burns; brother-in-law and sister-in-law, Ed and Lucille Clapp; niece, Carolyn Justice and several other nieces and nephews. Funeral service 8 p.m. Thursday, Stevens Mortuary Chapel, Pastor Larry Young and Pastor Tim McGhee officiating. Family and friends will meet 10:45 a.m. Friday at Woodlawn Cemetery for an 11 a.m. graveside service. Pallbearers: Ben Hudson, D.K. Ford, Archie and James Bell, Herman Sloan and Charlie Ensor. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Oakwood Baptist Church Organ Fund, 111 E. Columbia Avenue, Knoxville, Tenn. 37917. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Thursday at Stevens Mortuary, Oglewood Avenue at Broadway.
