<P><B>LAMPLEY, MAYME SUE - </B>85, of Oak Ridge, died this morning, January 20, 1997, at the University of Tennessee Medical Center at Knoxville of injuries sustained in an automobile accident. Mrs. Lampley was employed with Union Carbide Nuclear Division at the Oak Ridge Gaseous Diffusion Plant, now K-25 Site. She retired as a medical technologist. She was born in Sweetwater on May 20, 1911, the daughter of Luther Presley and Ethyl White Presley. Mrs. Lampley was a member of Glenwood Baptist Church. She is survived by: a daughter, Halleen J. Liles of Kingston Springs; three granddaughters, Cathy Hinton, Leslie Maxwell and Shelly Liles, all of Kingston Springs; two nephews, Glen Lemons of Sweetwater and Bill Presley of Des Plaines, Ill.; and eight great-grandchildren. Mrs. Lampley&#39;s husband, James Arnold Lampley, died earlier. The funeral will be at 10:30 a.m. Wednesday, January 22, in the chapel of McCarty-Martin Oak Ridge Funeral Home with the Rev. Charles Clark of Glenwood Baptist officiating. Burial will be at Sweetwater Cemetery. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Tuesday, January 21, at the funeral home. The family requests any memorials be in the form of donations to Glenwood Baptist Church, Prayer Room Fund, 200 S. Alabama Road, Oak Ridge, TN 37830.
<P>
<P><B>LAW, FLORA ETTA MILLER - </B>of Louisville, died Saturday, January 18, 1997, at Blount Memorial Hospital. Survivors include: her husband, William J. &#39;&#39;Bill&#39;&#39; Law of Louisville; son, S.A. (Bill) Law of Kingsport, Tenn.; daughter, Ella Jean Helton of Hilton Head Island, S.C.; grandchildren, William A. (Andy) Law of Kingsport, Cindy Cross, and Melissa Hanna of Atlanta; great-grandchildren, Ricky and Casie Law of Kingsport; sister, Mrs. Dana Garrett of Knoxville; brother, S. Tilden Miller of Rockford; several nieces and nephews. Private funeral services will be held Tuesday. Honorary pallbearers will be Jim, Joe, and Jeff Law, Nancy Henry, Leroy and Sammy Miller. Friends may call at their convenience at McCammon-Ammons Funeral Home, Maryville.
<P>
<P><B>LOCKETT, WILLIAM EDWARD - </B>born February 3, 1922, in Jefferson City, Tenn., died Monday at Ft. Sanders Regional Hospital at age 74. Mr. Lockett graduated from McCallie Prep School in Chattanooga, Tenn. and attended the University of Tennessee where he was a member of SAE Fraternity. He then served in the infantry division of the U.S. Army during World War II in the European Theater. After returning home from the war, he was the vice president of Jefferson Woolen Mill, a family owned business until the business was sold in 1960. He then worked as an investment banke for J.C. Bradford and later Hillard Lyons Brokerage Co. Mr. Lockett served as president of the Knoxville Civitan Club and began that organizations tradition of the Claxton Fruit Cakes to benefit the Boy&#39;s Club. He was a former elder of Sequoyah Hills Presbyterian Church and served on the Board of Director of Old Gray Cemetery. He was a member of the LeConte Club, Cherokee Country Club, and The Men&#39;s Cotillion. Survivors include: his wife, Mary Dukeminier Lockett; daughter and son-in-law, Mary Ann and John Tally of Fayetteville, N.C.; daughter and son-in-law, Nina and Ray Millard of West Point, Miss.; and grandchildren, Lockett Tally, Jesse Talley, Mary Caradine Millard, and Tucker Millard. The family will receive friends 12-1:30 p.m. Wednesday at Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel, leaving the funeral home at 1:45 p.m. in procession to Highland Memorial Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside service with Dr. William Barron officiating. Pallbearers: Ray Millard, John Tally, Jim Ellis, George Ed Wilson, Dick Koella, Richard Hayes, Ed Phillips, Jim Tally. Memorials may be made to East Tennessee Historical Museum, 600 Market St., Knoxville, TN 37902 or Sequoyah Hills Presbyterian Church, 3700 Keowee Ave., Knoxville, TN 37919. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>MAYFIELD, SHELBY GAIL - </B>age 49, of Millwood, Va., died Friday, January 17, 1997 at Winchester Medical Center, Winchester, Va. She was born May 7, 1947 in Knoxville, Tenn. to E. Ray Stanfield and Eula Waggonner Stanfield. She was Director of Quality Assurance at Grafton School. Member of Grace Evangelical Lutheran Church. Was Director of the Virginia Autism Resource Center and a representative on the Northwestern Community Services Board for Clarke County. She was married to Martin R. Mayfield on August 15, 1970 in Knoxville, Tenn. Survivors: husband, Martin R. Mayfield; sons, Andrew D. Mayfield, Timothy M. Mayfield, both of Millwood, Va.; sister, JoDell Brown of Knoxville, Tenn.; brother, Dennis Stanfield of Bakersfield, Calif. Memorial service Tuesday, January 21, 1997 at 6 p.m., Grace Evangelical Lutheran Church, Winchester, Va., the Rev. Dr. James H. Utt officiating. Family will receive friends at the church fellowship hall following the service where dinner will be served. Memorial contributions to Grace Evangelical Lutheran Church, 26 W. Boscawen St., Winchester, Va. 22601 or Winchester Musica Viva, P.O. Box 345, Winchester, Va. 22604 or Grafton School, P.O. Box 112, Berryville, Va. 22611. Arrangements by Jones Funeral Home, Winchester, Va.
<P>
<P><B>MORRISON, LILLIAN SHIRLEY - </B>age 86, of Knoxville, died January 18, 1997, at East Tennessee Baptist Hospital having been a resident at Holston Health Care Center for the last year and a half. Member of Heska Amuna Synagogue, Arnstein Jewish Community Center, a three generation life member of Hadassah. Preceded in death by: husband, Sam N. Morrison. Survivors: daughter and son-in-law, Trudy Sigal and Shmuel Robinson of Ra&#39;anana, Isreal; son, Phillip Sigal of California; grandsons, Yanv Robinson of Ra&#39;anana, Isreal, and Michael Sigal of Nashville; granddaughters, Michal Robinson of Ra&#39;anana, Isreal, Barrie Sigal and husband, Michael Brown of Nashville; stepdaughters and sons-in-law, Mary Linda and Arnold Schwarzbart of Knoxville, Anne and David Tomlinson of Nashville; stepgranddaugters, Sarah Tomlinson of Nashville and Jennie and Nick Ellowitz of Knoxville. Family and friends will meet 3:15 p.m. Tuesday at New Jewish Cemetery for a 3:30 p.m. graveside service and interment with Rabbi Shlomo Levine officiating. Pallbearers: Ernie Gross, Yanv Robinson, Arnold Schwarzbart, and Michael Sigal. Contributions may be made to Heska Amuna Synagogue, Hadassah or The Marilyn Shorr Memorial Fund of the Knoxville Jewish Federation. Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel, in charge.
<P>
<P><B>NORMAN, FRANK E. - </B>age 88, of Powell, died 8:50 p.m. Saturday, January 18, 1997, at the home of his daughter. Member of Spring Hill Baptist Church. Preceded in death by by wife, Mackey Norman. Survivors: daughter and son-in-law, Margaret and Woody Trammell; grandchildren, Joey and Holly Trammell; stepdaughters and sons-in-law, Imogene and D.A. Langford, Helen and Gene Arnold; stepson, Joe Paul Head, all of Powell; nine step-grandchildren; 10 step-great-grandchildren; several nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet 9:45 a.m. Tuesday at Lynch-Bethel Cemetery for a 10 a.m. graveside service. Rev. Edwin Mitchell officiating. Pallbearers: Ron Graves, B.K. Hunter, David Johnson, Bill Langford, Cleo and Edward Norman. Arrangements by Stevens Mortuary, Oglewood Avenue at Broadway.
<P>
<P><B>PETERS, MARY WURTS - </B>age 91, of West Knoxville, died Sunday, January 19, 1997, at Little Creek Sanitarium. Member of Sequoyah Hills Presbyterian Church. Retired professor of physics and astronomy with 33 years service. Professor emeritus of University of Tennessee. Survivors: sister, Martha McClain; sisters and brothers-in-law, Helen and Charles Neas, Louise and Milo Kaderly of Knoxville; 21 nieces and nephews. Family and friends will meet at 10:45 a.m. Tuesday at the Adair entrance of Lynnhurst Cemetery for 11 a.m. graveside and interment service, Dr. Bill Barron and Dr. Dent Davis officiating. Memorials may be made to the charity of your choice. Friends may call at their convenience at Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>PETERS, MARGARET MAE - </B>86, of North Knoxville, died Sunday, January 19, 1997. She was the widow of Curtis Peters. Member of Dutch Valley Church of God and retired from Baptist Hospital. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, Claude and Juanita Peters of Nashville; daughters and sons-in-law, Ruth L. Edward Masterson, Mary Peters and James Williams, all of Knoxville; grandchildren, Kimberly Diane Peters, Valarie and Dave Parish, Dennis and Debra Masterson, Marjorie Masterson; great-grandchild, Pamela Masterson; sister, Gertrude Cox. Funeral service 8 p.m. Tuesday, Rose Chapel with Rev. Jack Dean officiating. Family and friends will leave Rose Mortuary, 10:30 a.m. Wednesday for interment at 11 a.m. at Norris Memorial Gardens. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>POTTS, LANGDON R. - </B>age 58, of Jefferson City, passed away 4:15 p.m. Sunday, January 19, 1997, at University of Tennessee Medical Center, after a sudden illness. He was a veteran, having served in the U.S. Army. He was bookstore manager of Carson-Newman College for over 30 years. He was an avid coach and umpire in the Jefferson City Softball League. Survived by: wife, Jane Potts of Jefferson City; sons and daughters-in-law, Langdon R. II and Anne Potts of Dandridge, Tenn., Michael W. and Theresa Potts of Morristown, Tenn.; daughter and son-in-law, Janie and Greg Cameron of Clarksville, Tenn.; son, Richard Alan Potts of North Dakota; grandchildren, Langdon R. Potts III, Laura Potts, Andrew Cameron, Sydney Cameron, Jenna Potts, Trey Potts; mother-in-law, Margaret Needham of Jefferson City; brother and sister-in-law, Richard and Mamie Potts of Jefferson City. Memorial funeral services will be 8 p.m. Tuesday, January 21, 1997, at Farrar&#39;s Chapel with Dr. R.R. Turner and Dr. Sherman Vanaman officiating. Interment Wednesday, 11 a.m. at Jefferson Memorial Gardens. Family will receive friends Tuesday evening, from 6-8 p.m. prior to funeral services. Farrar Funeral Home, Jefferson City, in charge of arrangements.
<P>
<P><B>RANDLES, PAUL EDWARD - </B>age 76, passed away Sunday, January 19, 1997, at the Life Care Nursing Home in Jefferson City. He was a member of Ebenezer Baptist Church. He leaves his beloved wife of 52 years, Colleen; and three children, son and daughter-in-law, Steve and Reid Randles of Strawberry Plains; daughter, Darlene Brown, Houston, Texas; daughter and son-in-law, Janette and Bob Lowe, Knoxville; and daughter-in-law, Peggy Randles, Kodak; sister and brother-in-law, Dorothy and Doyle Loveday, Kodak; five grandchildren, Glen, Scott, Sam, Carrie and Nick; many nieces and nephews. Funeral 8 p.m. Tuesday, McCarty&#39;s Evergreen Chapel, Rev. Jim Clayton officiating. Family and friends will meet at Underwood Cemetery at 1:45 p.m. Wednesday for a 2 p.m. commitial service. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at McCarty&#39;s Evergreen Chapel, 7426 Asheville Hwy.
<P>
<P><B>REAVES, CHARLES STEVE - </B>age 51, of Knoxville, passed away Sunday, January 19, 1997, at U.T. Hospital. He was a member of M.A.L.U. and K.L.U., also member of the Million Dollar Round Table. He was a member of Bearden United Methodist Church, where he served as head usher. Survivors: wife, Wanda McIntyre Reaves, Knoxville; brother, William Harvey Reaves, Bowie, Texas; several aunts. Interment service will be 11 a.m. Wednesday at Oak Grove Cemetery in Greenville, Tenn. Memorial service will be held 7:30 p.m. Wednesday at Bearden United Methodist Church, Dr. William H. Balch and Dr. Robert W. Walker officiating. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Bearden United Methodist Church, 4407 Sutherland Ave., Knoxville, TN 37919. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Broadway Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>RICE, MALCOLM HENRY - </B>age 98, of West Knoxville, died Sunday, January 19, 1997, at Ft. Sanders Parkwest. Member of Concord Presbyterian Church. A native of Connecticut and longtime resident of Concord, Tenn. A Yale University graduate. Mr. Rice worked on Jefferson Memorial, National Archives, and both National Galleries of Art, and at one time the renovation of the Capital Building, Washington, D.C., a architect for University of TN during the post WWII expansion. Preceded in death by: wife of 70 years, Helen Dowling Rice. Survivors: son and daughter-in-law, John Alan and Carolyn Rice, Knoxville; daughter and son-in-law, Joan and John J. Craig, Knoxville; seven grandchildren; and 12 great-grandchildren. Memorial service 5:30 p.m. Thursday, January 23, 1997, Concord Presbyterian Church, Rev. David Willingham officiating. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to the Friendship Fund of Concord Presbyterian Church. Arrangements by Rose Mortuary Mann Heritage Chapel.
<P>
<P><B>RICHARDSON, MRS. SUSIE LEE - </B>age 50, of LaFollette, died Thursday at U.T. Medical Center, Knoxville. Survivors: daughters and son-in-law, Angela and Gene Wilson, LaFollette; sons, Mr. and Mrs. Edward Hubbard, Caryville, Mr. and Mrs. Timothy Hubbard, LaFollette, Mr. and Mrs. Anthony Hubbard, LaFollette, Mr. and Mrs. David Hubbard, LaFollette, Mr. and Mrs. Paul Hubbard, LaFollette; sister, Mary Ann Frank, Georgia; brother, David Richardson, Georgia; mother, Delores Richardson, LaFollette; very special friend, Rev. V.H. Shears; 14 grandchildren. Services 2 p.m. Tuesday, Roach Memorial Chapel, Rev. Junior Thacker and Rev. J.B. Elliot officiating. Interment Campbell Memorial Gardens. The family will receive friends 6-8 p.m. Monday at Roach Mortuary, LaFollette.
<P>
<P><B>ROBERTS, BRENDA FAYE STEVENS WORSHAM - </B>age 50, of Knoxville, died 12:31 p.m. Monday, January 20, 1997, at Saint Mary&#39;s Medical Center after a lengthy illness. She was of the Baptist faith and retired LPN. Preceded in death by father, Thomas Claude Stevens, Founder of Stevens Mortuary; maternal grandparents, Lon E. and Ethel Dalton Cantwell of Rutledge; paternal grandparents, Oran G. and Elizabeth Mynatt Stephens of Corryton; aunt, Othello Stephens; uncle and aunt, Ken and Frances Stephens and uncle, Bud Stephens. Survivors: daughter, Dina Denise Worsham Gibson; son, Craig Steven Worsham and friend, Debbie; beloved granddaughter who called Brenda &#39;&#39;Albert&#39;&#39;, Cheri Margette Gibson; mother, Bernice Cantwell Stevens, all of Knoxville; sister, Evelyn Marie Stevens Grindstaff, Ann Arbor, Michigan; nieces, Melinda Marie Grindstaff, Franklin, Tenn., Janet Lynn Grindstaff, New Orleans, La.; nephew and wife, Edward Douglas Grindstaff II and Leslie; great-niece, Alexandra Lynn Grindstaff; great-nephew, Edward Douglas Grindstaff III, all of Lake Zurich, Illinois; aunt, Mary Evelyn Cantwell, Rutledge; aunt and uncle, Virgie and John Vandergriff; aunt, Ruth Dunsmore, all of Knoxville; many cousins and many, many, many friends. Brenda will be sadly missed, but we are comforted knowing that God needed another angel and that Brenda is now &#39;&#39;pain free&#39;&#39; and in a glorious place. Family and friends will meet at 1:15 p.m. Thursday at Stevens Mortuary to go in procession to Lynnhurst Cemetery for a 2 p.m. graveside and interment. Rev. Howard A. Field and Dr. C. Glenn Sullivan officiating. Pallbearers: The Staff of Stevens Mortuary. In lieu of flowers, memorials may be made to Smithwood Baptist Church Choir, Piano Fund, 4914 Jacksboro Pike, Knoxville, Tenn. 37918. Family will receive friends 6-9 p.m. Wednesday at Stevens Mortuary, Oglewood Avenue at Broadway.
<P>
<P><B>SEAGLE, RALPH HASKELL &#39;&#39;BABO&#39;&#39; - </B>age 62, of South Knoxville, passed away January 19, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Medical Center. He was a retired truck driver. Preceded in death by: wife, Glenda Galyon Seagle; parents, Herman and Velma Brown Seagle. Survivors: sons and daughters-in-law, Randy and Leanna Seagle, Roger and Lisa Seagle, all of Seymour; daughters and sons-in-law, Rita and Richie Tipton, Knoxville, Sharon and Carter Moulden, Sevierville; grandchildren, Bradley, Brittany, Brandy and Logan Seagle, Ryan Tipton, Shayna and Sherance Moulden; great-grandchildren, Carter and Kaylor Moulden; brothers and sisters-in-law, Earl and Hazel Seagle, Carl and Joan Seagle, Leeroy and Linda Seagle, Herman and Vera Seagle; sisters, Eleanor Cosselt, Alice Ogle, Manilla and Monroe Anderson, Nellie and Gene France; several nieces and nephews. Graveside service 2 p.m. Wednesday, at Holly Hills Memorial Park, South. The family will receive friends from 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at Berry Funeral Home, Chapman Highway.
<P>
<P><B>SMITH, BERTIE ELIZABETH - </B>age 70, of Pigeon Forge, Tenn., passed away Saturday, January 18, 1997. She was preceded in death by son, Gary Smith. Survivors include son, Darryl Dennis Smith of Atlantic Beach, Fla.; brother, Garland Jenkins of Sevierville; five grandchildren, Regina Turner, Jennifer Galyon, Kely Mason, Jeffrey Smith and Sabrina Smith; two great-grandchildren, Lance Galyon and Jessica Galyon. Funeral services will be held 7 p.m. Wednesday, January 22, 1997 at Rawlings Chapel with the Rev. Lewis Miller officiating. Interment will be 10 a.m. Thursday, January 23, 1997, at Pleasant Hill Cemetery. The family will receive friends 5-7 p.m. Tuesday and Wednesday at Rawlings Funeral Home in Sevierville. Arrangements made by Rawlings Funeral Home.
<P>
<P><B>SMITH, MRS. LUCY ROBERTSON - </B>age 90, of Halls, formerly of Luttrell, passed away Monday morning at 5:30 a.m., January 20, 1997, at St. Mary&#39;s Hospital after a lingering illness. She was a member of Cedar Ford Baptist Church. She was preceded in death by husband, Tivis Smith; sons, Sewell and J.T. Smith; one granddaughter, Patsy Griffey. Survived by daughters and sons-in-law, Ruby Donahue, Reba Peterson, Glenda (Dodie) Kirchner, all of Halls, June and Willis Hill, Wilma Wolfe, all of Luttrell; sons and daughters-in-law, Dickie Smith, Knoxville, Danny and Donna Smith of Florida; 21 grandchildren; one step-grandson; 35 great-grandchildren; eight great-great-grandchildren; three special people, Brenda Ayers, Kathleen Smith and Carl Wolfe and a host of relatives and friends. Funeral services 2 p.m. Wednesday at Ailor&#39;s Mortuary Chapel Rev. Herman Lakin officiating. Interment in Fairview Cemetery, Tater Valley Road. Pallbearers will be grandsons. The family will be at the home of Ruby Donahue in Halls. Family will receive friends 7-9 p.m. Tuesday at Ailor Mortuary, Maynardville.
