<head>
	<title>Power plant foes to get legal boost</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Power plant foes to get legal boost</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jerry Dean, News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he nonprofit Southern Environmental Law Center of Charlottesville, Va., will join the debate over a pumped-storage hydropower facility proposed for the Sequatchie Valley.
<P>   The legal group&#39;s participation is contingent on project opponents&#39; ability to raise $1,000 to match the center&#39;s offer of a $3,000 legal-services challenge grant.
<P>   Lee W. Patten, an organizer of the Save Our Sequatchie landowners&#39; group, said the SELC&#39;s 12 lawyers have pledged to aid the SOS&#39;s legal opposition to the project development plan of Armstrong Energy Resources Inc. 
<P>   Before AER can build the huge hydropower plant, its plans must be approved by several government agencies, most notably TVA, the Army Corps of Engineers and the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
<P>   AER, a firm based in Butler, Pa., late in December opted to defer the Reynolds Creek portion of the $4 billion hydropower plant. Its officials promised to continue seeking federal and state permits to build the project&#39;s larger Laurel Branch portion, which entails dams, lakes and a pumping power generation station in Bledsoe County near Dunlap. 
<P>   Excess TVA power, bought by AER during low demand periods, would be used to lift water from lower lakes to mountaintop reservoirs. Then gravity flow could be used at peak power demand periods to generate hydropower for sale to TVA and delivery to its customers. 
<P>   TVA has a memorandum of understanding with AER to aid in the environmental review phase of the project. TVA officials repeatedly have said the agency has no stake in the private power project and might not agree to buy power if the project is completed.
<P>   Patten said Rick Parrish, SELC director, met with SOS members in December and proposed that the center aid with legal services to protect Sequatchie water resources, define impacts of AER power transmission lines and seek flaws in the environmental impact statement proposed for publication this autumn.
<P>   The SELC also works in the Chattanooga area on chip mill and Lyndhurst Foundation business.
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
