<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Consumer show standouts DVD, WebTV, HDTV pricey gadgets</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper Business News">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif" alt="Knoxville News-Sentinel Online -- Business News" align=bottom border=0 width=595 height=176></a><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td align=left valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Consumer show standouts DVD, WebTV, HDTV pricey gadgets</B></font><basefont size=6><!--SUBHEAD--></basefont></FONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Pam Park News-Sentinel business writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">T</FONT>he Winter Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas can give even the technology-minded a case of sensory overload and gadget garble. This year the exhibits covered more than a million square feet.
<P>   In this crowded field, High Definition Television (HDTV), Digital Video Disc (DVD) and WebTV were prominent products.
<P>   I have to admit, HDTV is impressive. Philips Consumer Electronics Co. was demonstrating HDTV at its booth at the show, which ran Jan. 9-12. It looked better than real life. Honestly, the nature scenes made me wonder if people who saw Yellowstone Park first on HDTV might be disappointed with the real thing. In nature there&#39;s often an atmospheric haze. HDTV is such a high resolution digital product, a picture shot with the right equipment looks almost unnaturally clear and sharp on the television.
<P>   Before I get you too excited about HDTV, I need to tell you the early versions are expected to cost $10,000 each when they come out in 1998. As consumer electronics are prone to do (to the chagrin of manufacturers), they&#39;ll get cheaper over time. Within 10 years, they are expected to sell at a $200-$300 premium over other televisions.
<P>   The television manufacturers are elated about the prospects for HDTV. They see it as an opportunity to replace the<B> </B>millions of television sets in the United States. They think everybody who sees an HDTV set will want one. I think they may be right, but prices will have to come down or wages go up before many of us will be able to indulge.
<P>   The Digital Video Disc is the product the industry hopes will ultimately raise consumer electronics sales from the doldrums.
<P>   DVD is a groundbreaking digital video product that, combined with digital audio, will give a movie-theater quality experience at home.  It&#39;s billed as having a better picture than a videocassette and better sound than a compact disc. It will also offer more capacity. Disc size will drop from 12 inches to five inches, and each five-inch DVD will be able to hold a whole movie, or more than one, depending on how many layers are recorded on it.
<P>   Industry leaders expect DVD will eventually replace CD-ROMs and videocassettes and open the door to sell a lot of related products like DVD-ROM.
<P>   Perhaps so, but the demonstration didn&#39;t grab me like HDTV&#39;s did. The sound was great, but then there were about six speakers positioned around the booth. It was shown on a specially sized television, but they said you could format the picture to fit your television screen without loss of quality.
<P>    You have to buy a player expected to cost between $500 and $700 when it reaches the market this spring. It will play regular music CDs as well as DVD products, however.
<P>   Whether DVD reaches its potential will largely depend on the content -- movies and more -- that will be offered with it, industry leaders say.
<P>   The debut of the machine was delayed by lack of early commitment from content providers, but several stepped forward at the Las Vegas show. Manufacturers would like to see more enthusiasm as they prepare to spend millions on producing the hardware, but they were encouraged by Hollywood&#39;s initial commitments.
<P>   Although people tend to use the term generically, WebTV is actually a company that licensed Sony and Philips to make equipment to surf the Internet from a home television. WebTV provides the consumer Internet access after he or she buys the equipment.
<P>   WebTV targets people who don&#39;t have a computer but who want to surf the Internet and send and receive electonic mail. Only 35 percent of the public is estimated to own a computer and only 10 percent of that number are believed to be using an online service, so the industry sees a big potential market for this device.
<P>   WebTV looks pretty good and is simple to use even if you have never touched a computer.
<P>   Price is a big advantage for WebTV. A Philips Magnavox Internet TV Terminal costs about $400, including a keyboard. Compare that to purchasing a $2,500 computer and WebTV is a sensible alternative for many people. Internet access through WebTV costs $19.95 per month -- about the same as other Internet access providers.
<P>   Manufacturers estimate a million Internet TV terminals will be sold this year.
<P>   To whom?
<P>   Executives would not detail the demographics of the WebTV audience, but they did say surveys showed they look at consumer-oriented sites more than research sites on the Internet. Some use WebTV as a social activity, surfing in groups in a way that is not workable with a personal computer. One executive hinted adult sections of the Internet were important to some users.
<P>   Ed Volkwein, senior vice president of sales and marketing for Philips, told an audience at the electronics show that couch potatoes should stand proud of WebTV survey results.
<P>   &#39;&#39;They are in fact curious people, between beers,&#39;&#39; he said.
<P>
<P><B>Business writer Pam Park covers technology issues for The News-Sentinel</B>.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

