<head>
	<title>Four drivers say yes to IROC invitations</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Four drivers say yes to IROC invitations</B></FONT><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Just four selections remain to fill field</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Bill Luther, News-Sentinel sportswriter</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<P>   
<P>
<P>   Four drivers who competed in the PPG CART World Series last year have accepted invitations to participate in the International Race of Champions all-star series.
<P>   They are titlist Jimmy Vasser of Las Vegas, rookie of the year Alex Zanardi, a native of Italy, Al Unser Jr. of Albuquerque, N.M., and Robby Gordon of Orange, Calif., They join Winston Cup drivers Mark Martin, Terry Labonte, Jeff Gordon and Dale Jarrett who were selected earlier for the four-race series which begins Feb. 14 at Daytona (Fla.) International Speedway.
<P>   The final four selections are to be announced next week, said Jay Signore, the series president.
<P>   Vasser won four CART races en route to his first Indy car title. He also won five poles.
<P>   &#39;&#39;The chance to be in IROC is special because you have to earn your invitations,&#39;&#39; Vasser said. &#39;&#39;It&#39;s like another benefit that came with winning the PPG Cup.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Zanardi, a Vasser teammate with Chip Ganassi Racing, was a three-time winner in the second half of the season and won six poles.
<P>   Unser, considered the most successful driver in IROC history, will make a record 12th consecutive appearance. He has a record 10 IROC wins and won the championship in 1986 and 1988. A.J. Foyt, Dale Earnhardt and Martin are other two-time champs.
<P>   Gordon, who will run the 32-race Cup series this year, focused on CART throughout the year. His second IROC invitation was good for four race victories and the Off-Road Trophy Truck championship.
<P>
<P>   <B>CREAM OF CROP: </B>Winston Cup racing attracted a record 5,588,069 fans last season, an increase of 4.9 percent. The CART Indy series (2,366,440) and IRL Indy events (1,144,002) combined for 3,510,442.
<P>   NHRA drag racing ranked third overall with 1,869,437 and the NASCAR Busch Grand National series fourth (1,665,437). 
<P>  The Craftsman Truck competition drew (811,050) and IROC events (284,447), sanctioned by NASCAR, hiked the four-series ticket sales to 8,349,266.
<P>
<P>   <B>TOUGH ROAD: </B>The Maxwell House Award, the most recent hardware to be added to Earnhardt&#39;s Winston Cup career, came as a result of the quick recovery from a mid-season accident at Talladega Superspeedway on July 28. He suffered a broken collar bone, cracked sternum and bruised hip in the accident.
<P>   A week later he turned his Chevrolet over to Mike Skinner after six laps, but he was able to complete the remaining races.
<P>   Other nominees were Dale Jarrett, Ricky Craven and Cup champion Terry Labonte.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
