<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Reeves to control Falcons</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Reeves to control Falcons</B></FONT><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Five-year deal worth $7.5-8M</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By The Associated Press</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>TLANTA -- Having made the playoffs only five times in their 31 years, the Atlanta Falcons on Monday turned to Dan Reeves, the NFL&#39;s winningest active coach.
<P>    Reeves, who was fired by the New York Giants after the season, signed a five-year deal as coach and head of football operations. He succeeds June Jones and will be introduced at a news conference today.
<P>    The Atlanta Journal-Constitution said Reeves&#39; contract is worth $7.5 million to $8 million -- almost double what any previous Falcons coach has earned.
<P>    &#39;&#39;It&#39;s exciting, knowing he&#39;s going to be here for the next five years,&#39;&#39; said Robbie Tobeck, an offensive guard who was in the weight room at the Falcons&#39; training complex in Suwanee when the announcement was made.
<P>    &#39;&#39;We&#39;re ready to get things rolling. It gives us something to look forward to next year -- a new coach, a new system.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Reeves, 53, returns to the state where he was born and takes over a club coming off another dismal season. Atlanta, which has had only seven winning seasons in its history, slumped to 3-13 this season, a year marked by a public dispute between Jones and quarterback Jeff George.
<P>    George was released after playing only three games and Jones lost his job at the end of the season, despite having two years left on his contract.
<P>    Reeves was fired by the Giants after 31-33 record and one playoff appearance in four seasons. He has a career record of 149-113-1, making him the 10th winningest coach in NFL history.
<P>    The Falcons interviewed only two candidates to succeed Jones, both with ties to Georgia.
<P>    Bobby Ross, a former Georgia Tech coach who was ousted by the San Diego Chargers, was apparently the top choice. He took the Detroit job last week.
<P>    Reeves originally interviewed with the Falcons in 1977 while an assistant with the Dallas Cowboys. The job was given to Leeman Bennett.
<P>    &#39;&#39;This time, I don&#39;t question my qualifications or my resolve,&#39;&#39; Reeves said recently.
<P>    Reeves is the 11th coach in Falcons history, and he will have more control than any of his predecessors.
<P>    &#39;&#39;I think it&#39;s the right direction,&#39;&#39; Tobeck said. &#39;&#39;Obviously, he&#39;s shown that he can win.&#39;&#39;
<P>    Reeves faces a major rebuilding job. He&#39;s likely to bring a more traditional offense than the run-and-shoot Jones employed in his three seasons. The defense, among the worst the past several seasons, also must be upgraded.
<P>
<P>
<P><font size=2><strong><p>Copyright 1997 by the Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. Unauthorized use is probihited. </p</strong></font>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
