<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Sports briefs</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>January 21, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470><BASEFONT SIZE="6">
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B>Sports briefs</B></FONT><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<h3>Referee drops charges against basketball coach</h3> 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>   A Tennessee high school referee is dropping assault charges against a girls&#39; basketball coach he said grabbed him after her team suffered a two-point loss.
<P>   Referee <B>Mark Morrison</B> said he didn&#39;t want the publicity that would come from pressing the misdemeanor charge against Battle Ground Academy coach <B>Gretchen Eisenhauer</B>.
<P>   The incident occurred in December after BGA lost 45-43 to Brentwood High during a December tournament.
<P>   Brentwood police reports say Eisenhauer grabbed Morrison&#39;s arm outside the gym and then grabbed his shoulder to spin him around. She demanded to know why he had given her a technical foul during the game, police said.
<P>   BGA imposed a six-game suspension on Eisenhauer. The Tennessee Secondary Schools Athletic Association suspended Eisenhauer for eight games, fined BGA $350 and placed the girls basketball program on probation through the end of the 1997-98 school year.
<P>
<P><h3>Television</h3>
<P>
<P>* Beginning today, the SportSouth network becomes FOX Sports South. It is channel 19 for Scripps Howard cable subscribers. The network includes live coverage of the Atlanta Hawks, Atlanta Braves and ACC, SEC, Southern Conference, Ohio Valley Conference and Conference USA sports.
<P>
<P><h3>College football</h3>
<P>
<P>* Quarterback <B>Gary Gumm</B> of Louisville Doss high school verbally committed to play his football at Louisville. The 6-foot-4 Gumm made his decision after a weekend visit to Kentucky.
<P>* <B>Jeff Bleamer</B>, Citadel&#39;s offensive line coach the past 10 years, has resigned to take the assistant head coaching spot with East Tennessee.
<P>* Appalachian State defensive coordinator <B>Ruffin McNeill</B> has accepted the same position at Nevada-Las Vegas, the Winston-Salem Journal reported.
<P>
<P><h3>College basketball</h3>
<P>
<P>* Junior forward <B>George Cox </B>of Carson-Newman was named South Atlantic Conference player of the week. The former Austin-East standout averaged 19 points and 6.5 rebounds in the Eagles&#39; two wins last week. 
<P>* <B>Damon Flint</B>, a starting guard for No. 9 Cincinnati, has been suspended for tonight&#39;s game at North Carolina-Charlotte for being late to practice.
<P>* Wyoming guard <B>LaDrell Whitehead,</B> the Western Athletic Conference&#39;s leading scorer and fourth in the nation, could miss the rest of the season because of a dislocated left elbow.
<P>* <B>Amy Duran</B> scored 22 points and <B>Kara Wolters</B> added 19 as the top-ranked Connecticut women (17-0) remained unbeaten and handed No. 5 Georgia (12-4) its worse home court loss in 19 years, 97-65.
<P>
<P><h3>Golf</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Hale Irwin </B>birdied the 17th hole to break a daylong deadlock with <B>Gil Morgan</B> late Sunday and capture the MasterCard Championship at Kailua-Kona, Hawaii. Irwin finished the final round with a 68 to complete the 54-hole tournament at 7-under 209, while Morgan&#39;s 70 put him at 211.
<P>
<P><h3>Running</h3>
<P>
<P>* Romania&#39;s <B>Iulia Negura</B> could be banned for four years and stripped of her European women&#39;s cross country title after testing positive for steroids. The Romanian Athletics Federation said Monday that Negura failed two doping control tests last month, both times for the steroid stanozolol -- the same drug which got Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson kicked out of the 1988 Olympics.
<P>
<P><h3>Soccer</h3>
<P>
<P>* U.S. National Team forward <B>Eric Wynalda</B> became the first two-time winner of the 1996 Honda Player of the Year award when he was honored as the top player in the United States.
<P>* Barcelona&#39;s Brazilian striker <B>Ronaldo</B> was named FIFA&#39;s player of the year, edging out AC Milan&#39;s Liberian star <B>George Weah</B> and Newcastle&#39;s <B>Alan Shearer</B>.
<P>* <B>Reinaldo</B>, a forward on the Brazilian team that finished third in the 1978 World Cup, was sentenced to four years in prison on Monday for drug trafficking.
<P>
<P><h3>Figure skating</h3>
<P>
<P>* Five-time winner <B>Surya Bonaly</B> of France faltered during the European Figure Skating Championships at Paris. <B>Maria Butyrskaya</B> of Russia and <B>Elena Liashenko</B> of Ukraine were first in each of their groups.
<P>
<P><h3>Miscellany</h3>
<P>
<P>* <B>Peter Graf&#39;s</B> defense attorney asked a judge in Mannheim, Germany, to spare his client jail time for evading taxes on income earned by his daughter, <B>Steffi Graf</B>.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
