<DOCNO>WT25-B30-203</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000616-B029-171</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.knoxnews.com:80/special/ssi/3742.htm 204.78.32.16 19970122015604 text/html 11940
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 01:58:33 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 20:20:57 GMT
Content-length: 11747
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Disability payments in Tennessee are 8 times greater than welfare</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>December 29, 1996</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Disability payments in Tennessee are 8 times greater than welfare</B></font><FONT SIZE="-1"><BR> Checks to drug addicts, alcoholics end in January</FONT></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By Jesse Fox Mayshark, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">A</FONT>t the beginning of every month, the Social Security Administration mails about 300,000 disability checks worth some $136 million to Tennessee.
<P>   It&#39;s an amount that&#39;s 81/2 times greater than the $16 million or so that&#39;s doled out each month in Aid to Families with Dependent Children, the cash payment program known as &#39;&#39;welfare.&#39;&#39;
<P>   But until recently, federal disability payments have generated little discussion or debate. Now that&#39;s changing.
<P>   On Jan. 3, the most controversial disability checks -- to people certified as drug addicts or alcoholics -- will end.
<P>   That will have a big impact in Tennessee, which has nearly 9,300 addicts and alcoholics on its disability rolls, the sixth-highest number in the nation and the third-highest number per capita.
<P>   In July, another change takes effect. Children who receive disability payments because they have &#39;&#39;maladaptive behaviors,&#39;&#39; such as attention deficit disorder (ADD), will have to be re-evaluated.
<P>   Officials estimate 7,000 children in Tennessee will be re-tested, and some of them will lose their monthly benefit.
<P>   Moreover, the Social Security Adminstration is looking for ways nationwide to take more people off disability and put them to work.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We&#39;ve done a lot of things over the last few years to get people back in the work force,&#39;&#39; said Jim Rovere, Social Security district manager for Knox, Loudon, Union and Sevier counties. &#39;&#39;But my own observation is that there haven&#39;t been a lot of success stories.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>History
<P>
<P>   The first thing Rovere thinks people should know about disability payments is that there are two different kinds: Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI) and Supplemental Security Income (SSI). He said people often confuse the two.
<P>   SSDI grew out of the main Social Security system in 1954. It is a payment given to adults who have worked in the past but have become disabled.
<P>   The amount of a monthly SSDI payment depends on how long a person worked and how much he or she paid into Social Security during that time. Like Social Security payments to retirees, SSDI payments come out of the Social Security Trust Fund.
<P>   The average payment for a disabled American worker was $682 per month at the beginning of 1996, although Rovere said payments can range as high as $1,300 a month.
<P>   Supplemental Security Income, on the other hand, is essentially a welfare program administered by the Social Security Administration.
<P>   Rovere said individual states used to pay welfare checks to disabled adults with little or no income. But payments varied so much between the states that Congress decided in 1974 to have the Social Security Administration take over the program.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It provided kind of an equal floor of support that would be administered the same across the country,&#39;&#39; Rovere said.
<P>   Unlike SSDI benefits, SSI checks are paid out of the general federal budget, not out of the Social Security Trust Fund.
<P>   Monthly SSI payments range up to a maximum of $470. When children are certified as disabled, the payments go to their parents or caretakers.
<P>   Whether someone gets SSDI or SSI depends on his or her work history. Disabled people who have worked for a number of years would get SSDI, while those with little or no work history would get SSI. If someone&#39;s SSDI payment is low enough, they can get both SSDI and SSI.
<P>   Recipients of SSI also qualify for TennCare health insurance.
<P>
<P>Who&#39;s disabled?
<P>
<P>   Deciding who qualifies for disability payments is the trickiest part of the system and the one most subject to second-guessing.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I&#39;ve seen so much unfairness in the system,&#39;&#39; said U.S. Rep. John J. Duncan Jr., R-Knoxville. &#39;&#39;I&#39;ve seen people who were almost dead who have been denied (disability benefits). And yet we all know there are people out there who appear to be more healthy than I am and you are who are drawing disability.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Duncan said his office deals with a lot of disability cases, most of them people trying to get benefits.
<P>   But Rovere said the public perception that a lot of perfectly healthy people are collecting disability checks is wrong.
<P>   &#39;&#39;All the people that are approved have to have a medical diagnosis,&#39;&#39; he said. He said many disabilities -- especially mental problems like schizophrenia -- aren&#39;t visible but seriously hamper people&#39;s ability to work.
<P>   Rovere said the Social Security Administration turns down 70 percent of all disability applications.
<P>   The process works as follows:
<P>   * An applicant comes to the Social Security office to file for disability. If they have already had a medical exam, they must submit their records. If not, Social Security workers order an exam.
<P>   * The application and medical records are sent to the Disability Determination Section in Nashville, a branch of the state&#39;s Department of Human Services.
<P>   * State disability examiners review each claim and contact any doctors treating the claimant. If examiners have questions, they can refer them to medical consultants or order a second examination and diagnosis. The process takes three to four weeks.
<P>   * If the medical evidence shows a disability is severe enough to prevent &#39;&#39;substantial employment,&#39;&#39; the applicant will qualify for a monthly check.
<P>   Carroll Moore, director of Tennessee&#39;s Disability Determination Section, said the system has several checks and balances. But he admitted some people with questionable disabilities might slip through.
<P>   &#39;&#39;We try to prevent that from happening, but many times, especially with mental disorders, we have to take the information supplied&#39;&#39; from doctors and psychologists, Moore said.
<P>   Still, for many people, qualifying for a disability check is no easy task.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s hard to get certified,&#39;&#39; said Susan Chapman, a 55-year-old former nurse&#39;s aide. &#39;&#39;It took me over a year. It took me 14 months to get certified.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Chapman, a Knoxville resident, has been on disability for eight years for nervous problems. She said the monthly check has been a blessing.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It&#39;s wonderful,&#39;&#39; she said. &#39;&#39;There&#39;s some people who cannot work.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>Public outcry
<P>
<P>   But if disability payments provide a helping hand to many, critics of the program think they&#39;re also vulnerable to abuse.
<P>   That&#39;s been illustrated recently in two well-publicized aspects of the program: drug and alcohol benefits and checks to children with attention deficit disorder (ADD).
<P>   National television news reports have shown people using their disability payments to buy drugs and alcohol and parents encouraging children to act up so they&#39;ll be certified as ADD.
<P>   Rovere said both problems are relatively new.
<P>   As the medical profession began to regard drug and alcohol addiction as diseases, addicts began qualifying for disability checks. Over the past five years, Rovere said word of the payments spread among addicts and alcoholics, and many of them began to apply for them.
<P>   Tennessee saw more than its share of applications. Of the nation&#39;s 200,000 certified addicts, 9,300 live in Tennessee. Knox, Sevier, Union and Loudon counties have 1,600 certified addicts.
<P>   Rovere said the high numbers could have come about because Tennessee social workers were &#39;&#39;more in tune to the fact that drug addiction was a (certifiable) diagnosis.&#39;&#39;
<P>   But even some addicts think the policy has been a mistake.
<P>   &#39;&#39;To me, they&#39;re abusing it,&#39;&#39; said Joey Trillo, a 25-year-old Vonore native in a treatment program at Knox Area Rescue Ministries. &#39;&#39;There&#39;s a lot of really bad alcoholics that got disability from alcoholism. I&#39;m an alcoholic myself, and I&#39;m pretty bad. But I would rather work.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Trillo and others in the treatment program said they had seen fellow alcoholics buy booze, then lie to officials about how they spent their disability checks.
<P>   In response to complaints about the program, Congress earlier this year voted to end drug and alcohol benefits as of January 1997.
<P>   Attention Deficit Disorder also has become an increasingly popular diagnosis in the past decade.
<P>   &#39;&#39;As parents, especially parents with very limited income and needy families, found that the children could get disability benefits of $470 a month . . . it just became a way for families to get disability benefits,&#39;&#39; Rovere said.
<P>   Those benefits aren&#39;t ending, but all children with &#39;&#39;maladaptive disorders,&#39;&#39; which includes ADD, will have to be re-evaluated under stricter guidelines in 1997. As many as 200,000 nationwide will lose their disability checks.
<P>   Even with those issues addressed, however, broader questions about who should be on disability remain.
<P>   Tom Margenau, a spokesman at Social Security Administration headquarters in Baltimore, said only 1 to 2 percent of those certified for disability checks ever move back into the workplace, but officials say a much larger number probably could be retrained for employment.
<P>   That&#39;s borne out by Social Security fraud investigators. They often find people getting disability checks who are also working and not reporting their income.
<P>   &#39;&#39;A lot of times, people will work under a different name and Social Security number in order to conceal their wages,&#39;&#39; said James Farr, a special agent with Social Security&#39;s Office of Investigation in Atlanta.
<P>   Farr said those caught defrauding the system can be fined and jailed for up to five years.
<P>   Rep. Duncan, who voted for the drug and alcohol and ADD reforms, said he would like to see better regulation and more consistency in the system. He said the perception of abuse harms the people who are supposed to be helped by SSDI and SSI.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think it&#39;s a very serious problem for our society,&#39;&#39; he said. &#39;&#39;Obviously, when you have someone drawing disability who doesn&#39;t need it, it&#39;s taking money away from people who genuinely need it.&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<hr size=5>

	<P><center><font size=2>Return to </font><a href="/"><font size=2>Main</font></a><font size=2>. Copyright &#169; 1996 The Knoxville News-Sentinel. For comments, e-mail </font><a href="mailto:webmaster@www.knoxnews.com"><font size=2>webmaster</font></a><font size=2>.</font></center></p>
