<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Drinking, other woes dragged down ex-mechanic</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 29, 1996</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b><img
        src="../../images/ssiimages/socialsMC.jpg"
        alt="Kieth Williams" width="250" height="150"><br>
        <img src="../../images/v3/credits/MCcredit.gif"
        width="144" height="21"></b></font><p><font size="2"><strong><b>Leonard
        Keith Williams, who gets Social Security Disability
        payments will lose his benefits after the first of the
        year. Williams cannot work a regular job for 40 hours a
        week. He lives in a former motel in West Knoxville.</b></strong></font></p>
        <p><font size="6"><b>Drinking, other woes dragged down
        ex-mechanic</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        work or streets next</font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff
        writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">I</font>n a first-floor room at an old Red
        Carpet Inn in West Knoxville, Leonard Keith Williams
        strums his guitar to pass the time, singing about how it
        never rains in Southern California. </p>
        <p>''I sing it to myself sometimes, when I'm depressed,''
        said Williams, 42, as he sat cross-legged on his double
        bed while December sunlight beamed through a plate glass
        window. </p>
        <p>He rents the room -- called a ''studio apartment''
        because the hotel is closed -- for $370 a month, money
        that will disappear in 1997. </p>
        <p>Williams is one of the 1,600 people in the Knoxville
        area who will lose monthly disability payments for
        alcohol or drug problems. They face an uncertain future. </p>
        <p>''I'm gonna have to try to work,'' said Williams, who
        has been sober for about seven months. ''If I can't, then
        I have to hit the streets, stay at the mission, Salvation
        Army, somewhere. I'll have no choice.'' </p>
        <p>Williams admits he's an alcoholic. He said he's been
        in five treatment programs. But he also has two
        artificial hips and osteoarthritis. He suffers from
        depression and has trouble sleeping -- getting three or
        four hours on a good night. </p>
        <p>For all those reasons, he expects work will be hard to
        come by. Even though he's sober, employers will look
        skeptically at his past. He'll need to rest every couple
        hours if his 12-year-old artifical hips act up. </p>
        <p>''If I sit for too long, I start hurting. If I walk
        for too long, I start hurting. If I stand for too long, I
        start hurting,'' he said. ''It's all pressure on the
        hip.'' </p>
        <p>As he speaks, Williams occasionally sips from a pink
        plastic cup of iced tea. His room is pungent with the
        smoke of countless cigarettes -- GPC Approved. ''Cheapest
        things I can find. $8.69 a carton right up here at the
        Exxon. Plus tax.'' </p>
        <p>While precise dates are elusive, Williams has a
        portfolio of paperwork documenting his past. </p>
        <p>He used to make good money as a sewing machine
        mechanic. Levi Strauss &amp; Co. put him through two
        treatment programs but let him go in 1990. Williams said
        he made about $35,000 a year there as a technical
        training specialist. He still has a business card, a
        reminder of better days. </p>
        <p>Williams' problem drinking began in the early 1980s.
        He fell down the steps of a pool hall in 1984, tripping
        over a compressor on his way to the men's room after he'd
        been drinking. He sufferred multiple concussions. </p>
        <p>Doctors gave him steroids as he recovered. He was told
        the steroids might have caused his hips to deteriorate.
        His drinking continued, and he entered his first
        treatment center in 1985. </p>
        <p>After Levi Strauss let him go -- he said the firm had
        done what they could for him -- he spent most of 1991 and
        1992 homeless. He slept at shelters or outside if it was
        warm. </p>
        <p>He worked menial jobs -- selling light bulbs over the
        phone, washing dishes -- and sought help in various
        programs. But life got harder. </p>
        <p>In 1994, just weeks after finishing an eight-week
        course at Miracle Lake Christian Training Center in
        Etowah -- ''Basic Introduction to the Lifestyle of Jesus
        Christ'' -- Williams' 20-year-old son killed himself. </p>
        <p>''There's his picture over there,'' he said, motioning
        to a photograph of a handsome blond youth kneeling on one
        knee, smiling. Suicide wasn't new to Williams. His father
        shot himself on Williams' 11th birthday. </p>
        <p>The drinking started again. </p>
        <p>Williams, a Vietnam-era Marine veteran, went through a
        substance-abuse course at the Department of Veterans
        Affairs hospital in Murfreesboro, then went to a veterans
        program in Nashville. He relapsed and went to the
        Nashville VA to be treated for depression. </p>
        <p>In mid-1995, he started getting a disability check. He
        gets $1,859 a month -- $929.50 in current benefits and
        $929.50 in back pay. </p>
        <p>The current benefits end this month. The back pay will
        end this summer. </p>
        <p>''I will probably try to work before it runs out. I
        may have to swap jobs three or four times to find one I
        can work 40 hours a week at,'' Williams said, deferring
        again to his hip trouble. </p>
        <p>He'll appeal the government's decision to cut off his
        benefits. </p>
        <p>He'll explain that his physical problems make work
        difficult even without the alcoholism. But appeals can
        take years to decide. </p>
        <p>''What'll I do in between?'' Williams wondered,
        although he had a ready answer. ''I'll just hit the
        streets if I find out I can't work.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

