<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Disability payments for alcoholics, drug addicts to end Jan. 3</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 30, 1996</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><div align="right"><table border="0"
        cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="250">
            <tr>
                <td width="250"><img
                src="../../123096/images/freeMC.jpg" hspace="6"
                vspace="6" width="250" height="145"><img
                src="../../images/v3/credits/MCcredit.gif"
                width="144" height="21"><p><font size="2"><strong>F.
                Monroe Free president of Knox Area Rescue
                Ministries sitting in the dining room of the
                Knoxville Union Rescue Mission. Free believes
                changes in welfare will bring more needy families
                to the mission.</strong></font></p>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        </div><p><font size="6"><b>Disability payments for
        alcoholics, drug addicts to end Jan. 3</b></font><font
        size="5"><br>
        9,300 will be affected in Tennessee</font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff
        writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">B</font>y 9 a.m. on a cold December
        morning Eugene Blalock had already consumed a pint of
        liquor. </p>
        <p>''It gets rid of the shakes, see?'' the 50-year-old
        Army veteran explained in the smoke-filled basement
        office where he got his last monthly drug-and-alcohol
        disability check. </p>
        <p>The federal government has decided to stop giving
        money to Blalock and about 1,600 other people in the
        Knoxville area who claim to be disabled because of
        alcoholism or drug addiction. </p>
        <p>Blalock has been getting $470 a month. Some checks
        stopped in December. His last one will be on Jan. 3. </p>
        <p>Congress and President Clinton have realized what
        social workers, counselors and many addicts have said for
        years: It's a bad idea to give people money for being
        substance abusers. </p>
        <p>The ''Contract with America Advancement Act of 1996,''
        enacted March 29, ends disability payments to about
        200,000 alcoholics and drug addicts, including nearly
        9,300 in Tennessee -- the sixth-highest state total in
        the nation and the third-highest per capita. </p>
        <p>One in every 567 Tennesseans has been getting a
        disability check for alcoholism or drug addiction, based
        on figures from the Social Security Administration and
        the U.S. Census Bureau. </p>
        <p>When the money stops, the consequences could affect
        not only clients but the community as a whole: </p>
        <p>* Addicts who lose payments altogether could end up
        homeless or turn to crime to feed their addiction. </p>
        <p>''That's the talk on the street, among street
        people,'' said Barry Furches, 41, a homeless man who is
        losing some of his benefits. ''They're going to start
        taking what they want. They're too sick to work.'' </p>
        <p>* Some addicts will apply for disability benefits
        because of physical or mental impairments. If approved,
        they'll continue to get a government check to spend on
        alcohol or drugs. </p>
        <p>''They're going to be given the keys to the candy
        store once again,'' said Dan Caldwell, president of
        Cornerstone of Recovery, a drug and alcohol treatment
        center. ''It's really harmful to give an alcoholic or
        drug-dependent person money.'' </p>
        <p>* Some might go to work, thankful for the temporary
        assistance and willing to accept that it doesn't last
        forever. </p>
        <p>''I feel like I need to be working,'' said James
        Prater, a 41-year-old unemployed printer who's been
        getting $490 a month. ''I drank for 20-some years and I
        saw that I needed help and the government helped me to
        get help.'' </p>
        <p>While exact figures aren't available from the Social
        Security Administration, the agency estimates that
        perhaps $4 million a month is paid to Tennesseans who are
        disabled due to drugs or alcohol. </p>
        <p>Most get the money because they're poor. </p>
        <p>About 76 percent of Tennessee's 9,266 drug and alcohol
        recipients get Supplemental Security Income (SSI), the
        kind of disability that's paid to people with little or
        no work history. </p>
        <p>The other kind of disability is Social Security
        Disability Insurance for people who have worked. </p>
        <p>Some people get both types of checks. </p>
        <p>Although drug and alcohol checks are being cut off,
        many social workers say the government should still help
        substance abusers by getting them into treatment programs
        instead of handing them money. </p>
        <p>State and local officials are uncertain how much money
        will be made available. But even if more money arrives,
        some addicts say they've been in treatment over and over
        again without getting clean. </p>
        <p>''There's no perfect system,'' said U.S. Rep. John J.
        Duncan Jr., R-Knoxville, ''and I suppose there will be
        problems in anything that we come up with. But I think
        that cutting down on the people who are receiving this
        money because of drug and alcohol addictions will help a
        whole lot more than it will hurt. </p>
        <p>''I think it will force some of these people to take
        action to end their addictions rather than helping
        maintain the addictions that they have.'' </p>
        <p>Drunk and disabled </p>
        <p>Disability payments have been around for years, but
        Social Security officials said the idea of getting checks
        for being drunk or on drugs has gained popularity in the
        current decade. </p>
        <p>''What happened was the evaluation -- just the idea
        that that could be used (to get benefits), became
        generally known,'' said Jim Rovere, district manager for
        the Social Security Administration in Knox, Loudon, Union
        and Sevier counties. </p>
        <p>''About three years ago, that really started to get
        heavy. About four or five years ago, I'd say we had
        almost no one.'' </p>
        <p>The word on the street was that if you wanted to
        receive a disability check, drugs and alcohol provided
        the quickest route to getting it. </p>
        <p>''Historically, that's been the easiest way for them
        to get on benefits,'' said David Yoder, executive
        director of the Knoxville Legal Aid Society. </p>
        <p>''These people usually are low-income (and) don't have
        a medical history. They've not been able to afford to go
        to doctors, to get diagnosed, to undergo the examinations
        and the medical tests to document their other
        disabilities. It costs a lot of money to prove that
        you're disabled.'' </p>
        <p>Addictions can be documented more easily -- with lost
        jobs, arrests or hospital visits for public intoxication,
        Yoder said. </p>
        <p>While few observers -- advocates, social workers and
        recipients themselves -- support subsidizing addiction,
        ending the payments will bring its own set of problems. </p>
        <p>Off the dole </p>
        <p>Laquetta Ferguson's hands shook, her leg bounced and
        her Marlboro burned an inch-long ash as she talked about
        the prospect of losing her $470-a-month disability check.
        </p>
        <p>''I don't know what (will) happen 'cause I'm doing the
        best I can do right now,'' said the slight 44-year-old
        woman, who said she's suffered a lifetime of abuse
        through six marriages. She lives in an old trailer in
        Lenoir City with her 18-year-old daughter and her newborn
        grandchild. She recently had a cancerous breast removed. </p>
        <p>''We're going to be homeless,'' she said, pausing to
        let the idea sink in. She finished her thought with a
        resigned laugh. ''That's the truth, and that just about
        made me cry when I said that.'' </p>
        <p>The Social Security Administration estimates about 500
        of the 1,600 drug and alcohol cases in Knox, Loudon,
        Union and Sevier counties have appealed their
        terminations so far -- that is, they have sought money
        for other disabilities. The agency expects that about
        1,400 people still will be cut off. </p>
        <p>Ferguson missed the original reapplication deadline. </p>
        <p>''At the right date I was in the hospital getting my
        breast took off,'' she explained. </p>
        <p>Some who lose benefits will turn to the state welfare
        system for help. Charities expect more traffic. The
        homeless expect their population to grow. Ex-addicts
        expect crime to increase. </p>
        <p>''I've seen a lot of fear in people, people who are
        addicts and who are receving income,'' said Monroe Free,
        president of Knox Area Rescue Ministries, which expects
        to be providing even more food, clothing and shelter at
        its North Broadway mission. </p>
        <p>''They don't know what they're going to do with
        themselves. The ones I know do not have great skills and
        do not have great confidence in themselves and their
        ability to handle these kinds of crises.'' </p>
        <p>Crime is an option, some said. </p>
        <p>''They're going to start handling drugs, selling it,
        robbing, stealing. They're gonna go to something because
        there's just no jobs out there for them,'' said Joe
        Burkhart, a Vietnam veteran and ex-convict who has abused
        alcohol and drugs but also has other ailments. </p>
        <p>Said Sarah Sanders, 37, who will be losing $470 a
        month: ''I can't say what I'm gonna do. I don't know. I
        might have to turn into a hooker or something.'' She
        smiled. ''Seriously, you never know what you might have
        to do. I have four kids -- 16, 13, 8 and 2.'' </p>
        <p>Despite such talk, Capt. Paul Fish, east district
        commander for the Knoxville Police Department, isn't
        dreading a crime wave. </p>
        <p>''That's what they're saying, but I really can't prove
        that one way or the other,'' he said. ''There may be some
        of that, but to what rate is hard to say.'' </p>
        <p>Drunk and disabled </p>
        <p>The government will decide that some drug and alcohol
        abusers, like recovering addict Rochane Angel, have other
        disabilities that still qualify them for monthly checks. </p>
        <p>The problem is how those checks will be spent. </p>
        <p>''(A monthly payment of) $470 is a lot of money when
        you're out there using,'' said Angel, 33. Drug pushers
        are glad to take it. </p>
        <p>''Every month (dealers were) standing outside waiting,
        standing at the mailbox,'' she said. ''They'd get
        prepared for the first, second and third. That's when
        they made the money -- is on the first, and I know
        because I've been there.'' </p>
        <p>In March 1995, the Social Security Administration
        started using social-service agencies to distribute drug
        and alcohol disability checks. </p>
        <p>For a 10-percent fee with a $50 maximum, the agencies
        made sure the money at least paid for rent, utilities,
        food and other necessities. </p>
        <p>''I don't think it's kept a lot of people off alcohol
        and drugs, but at least it's kept them off the street,''
        said Gordon Acuff, executive director of the East
        Tennessee Human Resource Agency, another local payee. </p>
        <p>Angel's money is handled by Recovery Support Systems
        on Magnolia Avenue, opened by Whit and Melissa Mabry in
        May 1995. The Mabrys met while working at the
        Detoxification Rehabilitation Institute, where police
        bring public inebriates to dry out. </p>
        <p>At DRI, Melissa Mabry said: ''I just couldn't believe
        then that they were giving (alcoholics) checks. The first
        of the month would be awful, to see these people come
        back just so drunk.'' </p>
        <p>She'd ask where their money went. ''We got a hotel
        room . . . and we lived it up,'' they'd say. </p>
        <p>Payment agencies dread what happens when a drug or
        alcohol abuser -- even someone who's been clean and sober
        for months -- gets an entire monthly check in his hands. </p>
        <p>''He's not going to pay his rent,'' Acuff said. ''He's
        going to be kicked out of his apartment. He's not going
        to be able to pay his utilities. They're going to cut his
        power off. He's going to be living under the bridge. He's
        going to be bumming off somebody else, and as soon as he
        gets his check, he's going to congregate with friends he
        has who drink with him and they're going to drink it up.
        In two or three days, they're right back where they
        were.'' </p>
        <p>Said Glenda Loope, who manages ETHRA's representative
        payee program: ''Just because someone sitting in an
        office somewhere reading some files says he has another
        disability . . . does not mean that that client is still
        not an addict or an alcoholic.'' </p>
        <p>Social Security officials said some clients will still
        be required to have representative agency payees. </p>
        <p>''Their checks would be handled by a third-party payee
        if they're incapable,'' Rovere said. ''If it's just
        physical and there's not a mental impairment or an
        obvious case of still having a drug addiction, then they
        would get their own check.'' </p>
        <p>The number of drug and alcohol clients who will
        continue to get disability checks for physical or mental
        problems remains to be seen because so few have
        reapplied. </p>
        <p>Said Rovere: ''The feeling is when the checks don't
        come in January, they'll all come in here and say,
        'Where's my check and how do I get it started again?' '' </p>
        <p>Going to work </p>
        <p>Prater, the unemployed printer who feels the system
        helped him, said he applied for disability in the spring
        of 1995. </p>
        <p>''I did what I was supposed to do,'' he explained
        matter-of-factly. ''I paid my rent, my bills and tried to
        get my life back together. It's worked, by doing what I
        was supposed to do, by not drinking and going to
        meetings.'' </p>
        <p>He agreed that the government needs to look more
        closely at who receives checks so that the payments go to
        people who are staying sober. </p>
        <p>''I've got back trouble and bad knee troubles, and I
        could probably use that as an excuse not to work,''
        Prater said. ''But I know people that doesn't have legs,
        doesn't have arms. They're making a living every day. I
        feel pretty grateful.'' </p>
        <p>Not everyone shares Prater's confidence. </p>
        <p>''You can't find a job if you have a history of drugs
        and alcohol. Ain't nobody gonna hire you,'' Burkhart
        said. ''They're gonna be like hawks. Every slip-up is
        gonna be blamed on, 'You're back on drugs and alcohol.'
        '' </p>
        <p>Also, addicts typically have deeper problems. </p>
        <p>''We've got people out there who have minimal social
        skills,'' said Pete Shelton, a counselor who doesn't like
        giving checks to addicts but fears leaving them helpless.
        </p>
        <p>''We have people out there who are functionally
        illiterate. We have people out there with a plethora of
        social problems, and in essence what we're doing is
        saying, 'OK, it's time to get a job now.' </p>
        <p>''Who in the hell is going to hire these people?'' </p>
        <p>Whether they turn to charity, government programs or
        crime in order to support themselves, it will cost the
        larger society something. </p>
        <p>''Far more than giving them the $470 a month,'' said
        Charlie Parsons, a homeless outreach worker with the
        Community Action Committee. ''It's really going to come
        down on the local government.'' </p>
        <p>Congressman Duncan said state and local governments
        are in better financial shape than Washington, D.C.,
        which already funds more social programs than he can
        remember. </p>
        <p>But while congressmen, counselors, agencies and
        activists debate the issue, people like Eugene Blalock
        wonder what's coming next. </p>
        <p>Sitting at Recovery Report Systems with an Orlando
        Magic cap pulled down tightly on his head, Blalock said
        he's been grateful for the help that he has received. </p>
        <p>''They pay my rent, and I thank God for that. I really
        do. The truth's the truth,'' he said. ''But I cannot quit
        drinking. I'll drink till the day I die. Probably kill
        myself by drinking. That's it. </p>
        <p>''I hate to say that that way -- you know what I mean?
        But the truth's the truth.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

