<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<head>
	<title>Reasons are not clear why Tennessee has such a high number of substance abusers</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i>December 30, 1996</i> 
	</td>
	<td width=470>
		<basefont size="6"><FONT SIZE="6"><B>Reasons are not clear why Tennessee has such a high number of substance abusers</B></font><!--SUBHEAD--></BASEFONT><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I>By David Keim, News-Sentinel staff writer</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I></I></FONT><BR>
		<FONT SIZE="+2">E</FONT>xactly why Tennessee has had the sixth-highest number of residents getting disability checks for alcoholism and drug addiction is unclear.
<P>   &#39;&#39;It surprised us when we first heard it back in the spring,&#39;&#39; said Carroll Moore, director of the Disability Determination Section in Nashville which decides whether people qualify for disability checks.
<P>   The Social Security Administration reports 9,266 Tennesseans getting disability checks for being drug addicts or alcoholics, placing it sixth in the nation with addiction numbers exceeded only by much more populous states.
<P>   Taking population into account, one in 567 Tennesseans has gotten a drug or alcohol disability check. That puts Tennessee third in the nation on a per capita basis, behind Illnois (one in every 496 residents) and Kentucky (one in 557).
<P>   The last checks to addicts go out Jan. 3.
<P>   Only about half of those 9,000-plus clients, however, responded to notices mailed by the Social Security Administration warning them they&#39;ll lose money unless they&#39;re recertified with a different disability.
<P>   &#39;&#39;That&#39;s not surprising since these tend to be some of the most disabled and dysfunctional people on the Social Security rolls,&#39;&#39; said Jack Gustafson, executive director of the National Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors in Washington.
<P>   Jon Michael, deputy director of the Detoxification Rehabilitation Institute in Knoxville, speculated that the high Tennessee numbers started a while back.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Tennessee for some reason several years ago was selected as a pilot state when they first began monitoring drug and alcohol cases, so that might have raised the awareness (of social workers),&#39;&#39; Michael guessed.
<P>   Others said it&#39;s easier to get certified for a drug or an alcohol problem than for physical ailments.
<P>   &#39;&#39;Local attorneys were very aware of (drug and alcohol) as a valid basis of disability,&#39;&#39; said David Sewell, assistant manager of the Social Security district office in Knoxville.
<P>   David Patterson, assistant professor in the University of Tennessee College of Social Work, speculated that the state has a lot of people with little education and low levels of social support. He also said states might classify disability cases differently.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I don&#39;t think there&#39;s any one single factor going on here,&#39;&#39; said Patterson, who teaches a course in substance-abuse treatment. &#39;&#39;I think you have poverty, low education levels, low literacy rates, high smoking rates.&#39;&#39;
<P>   Social Security officials lean toward the idea that Tennessee classifies drug and alcohol cases more accurately than other states.
<P>   Sewell said drug and alcohol addicts require a little extra work. For instance, a representative payee must be found to handle their checks.
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think most of the (Disability Determination Sections) just didn&#39;t code the things,&#39;&#39; Sewell said, due to the extra work. &#39;&#39;Well, Tennessee did. . . . That&#39;s what we think it is. It&#39;s a good reflection on the Tennessee DDS all these years.
<P>   
<P>   &#39;&#39;I think any other sources . . . would bear that out -- that you don&#39;t have more drunks here, more drug addicts here, more drug usage here in Tennessee than anywhere else. I think it&#39;s just a matter of how the DDS did their (job).&#39;&#39;
<P>
<P><B>
<P>   Staff writer Jesse Fox Mayshark contributed to this report.</B>
<P>
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>
