<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Abusing the system</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>December 31, 1996</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b><img
        src="../../123196/images/drchris-mb.jpg"
        alt="Dr. Debbie Christiansen" width="175" height="220"><br>
        <img src="../../images/v3/credits/MBcredit.gif"
        width="144" height="21"><br>
        </b></font><font size="2"><strong><b>Dr. Debbie
        Christiansen. a Knoxville<br>
        pediatrician treats children with attention deficit<br>
        disorder. She believes the ADD diagnosis is made<br>
        too often.</b></strong></font><p><font size="6"><b>Abusing
        the system</b></font><font size="5"><br>
        Disability label used too often on children -- experts</font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Jesse Fox Mayshark, News-Sentinel
        staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">J</font>ohn McCook is used to anxious
        parents. </p>
        <p>As head of special education for the Knox County
        schools, he sees them every day. They ask for evaluations
        to see if their children have disabilities that might
        require special help with classwork or behavior. </p>
        <p>But sometimes school officials sense parents are less
        interested in what the evaluation means for their
        children than what it means for their checkbooks. </p>
        <p>It's one manifestation of the boom in children
        receiving federal disability checks for attention deficit
        disorder (ADD) or attention deficit hyperactive disorder
        (ADHD). </p>
        <p>''We (have seen) a definite increase in the informa </p>
        <p>tion-seeking forms that came in,'' said McCook, who
        also serves as Knox County's director of pupil personnel.
        ''It's not usually that overt. It's usually parents
        coming in and being very adamant about getting the
        certification.'' </p>
        <p>If a family's income is low enough, a child with ADD
        or another behavioral disorder can qualify for a
        Supplemental Security Income (SSI) check of up to $470 a
        month. </p>
        <p>''A lot of parents encouraged it because it was money
        to them,'' said Jim Rovere, Social Security district
        manager for Knox, Loudon, Sevier and Union counties. </p>
        <p>But concerns about abuse in the system have prompted a
        new set of rules by the Social Security Administration,
        which oversees SSI. </p>
        <p>In 1997, all children diagnosed with ''maladaptive
        disorders'' -- which includes ADD and ADHD -- will be
        re-evaluated under new and stricter guidelines. </p>
        <p>In Tennessee, officials estimate 7,000 children will
        be affected. As many as two-thirds of them will lose
        their disability checks, Social Security officials said. </p>
        <p>Advocates for disabled children say it's too early to
        gauge the impact of the changes. </p>
        <p>''Since the Social Security Administration has not
        issued any regulations yet, we're unable to get a handle
        on what it's going to mean for people,'' said Jeff
        Rosenberg, a spokesman for the national advocacy group,
        Children and Adults with Attention Deficit Disorder. </p>
        <p>But McCook said if the re-evaluations take some of the
        focus off labeling children rather than helping them, it
        will be a step in the right direction. </p>
        <p>''I don't think you (should) label students any more
        than you have to,'' he said. </p>
        <p><strong>A growing deficit </strong></p>
        <p>ADD and ADHD emerged as recognized medical conditions
        in the 1980s when they were added to the Diagnostic and
        Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, the handbook of
        psychologists and psychiatrists. They replaced older,
        vaguer conditions like ''hyperactivity.'' </p>
        <p>Both conditions are marked by difficulty in focusing
        on tasks for prolonged periods, and ADHD also includes
        hyperactive behavior. Many children diagnosed with ADD or
        ADHD are medicated with drugs like Ritalin. </p>
        <p>Medical and educational experts say the conditions are
        real and, in their most severe forms, drastically affect
        social and academic development. </p>
        <p>But many also question whether labeling children with
        minor forms of ADD is helpful. Some children who exhibit
        ADD tendencies at a young age eventually grow out of
        them. </p>
        <p>''My own opinion is I think we're diagnosing this too
        often right now,'' said Dr. Debbie Christiansen, a
        Knoxville pediatrician who treats more than 1,000
        children. ''Almost anybody who has a few attention
        problems, somebody wants them on medication whether it's
        a parent or a teacher or a doctor or a psychologist or
        whatever. I'm really uncomfortable with that.'' </p>
        <p>The problem has been partly fueled by SSI. </p>
        <p>Tom Margenau, a spokesman at Social Security
        Administration headquarters in Baltimore, said checks for
        disabled children have been part of the SSI program since
        it started in 1974. </p>
        <p>SSI money comes from general federal revenues, not the
        Social Security trust fund. </p>
        <p>Childhood disability was a relatively small part of
        the program until 1990 when a U.S. Supreme Court decision
        led to an explosion of claims. </p>
        <p>In that case, Sullivan v. Zebley, the court opened the
        way for children with behavioral disorders to qualify for
        SSI. </p>
        <p>''That essentially said Social Security had to broaden
        its definition of disability for children,'' Margenau
        said. </p>
        <p>And broaden it did. Before the Zebley decision, there
        were about 300,000 childhood SSI cases; in the past six
        years, that's grown to 1 million. </p>
        <p>McCook said the ruling gave incentives for parents to
        have children with marginal disabilities labeled. </p>
        <p>''I don't think there's any question that if money
        were available to people out there if all of a sudden
        they met a set of conditions, there would be people who
        would try to meet the set of conditions in order to get
        the money,'' he said. </p>
        <p>Not everyone has done it for the check; SSI also
        qualifies recipients for TennCare health insurance. </p>
        <p>''I know a woman who just was approved, and the only
        reason she wanted it was she couldn't afford health
        insurance,'' said Barbara Wagner, president of the
        Learning Disabilities Association of East Tennessee. </p>
        <p><strong>Making it harder </strong></p>
        <p>Margenau said the idea behind childhood SSI is that
        families with disabled children have extra expenses. But
        in many ADD cases, the only expense is medication. </p>
        <p>Even when there are other needs related to the
        disability, Christiansen said parents don't always use
        the SSI money to pay for them. </p>
        <p>''It bothers me when I see a child and say, 'This
        child needs some counseling,' and (the parents) say, 'We
        don't have the money for that,' '' Christiansen said.
        ''Well, aren't you getting that check?'' </p>
        <p>She added: ''I think that somebody ought to make a
        decision on what is the purpose of those funds.'' </p>
        <p>Wagner agreed. She said in some cases parents have
        gotten large retroactive checks because their children
        could have qualified for SSI earlier, and the money has
        been spent on luxuries rather than necessities. </p>
        <p>''I like the idea of forcing (parents) into putting
        this money into an account to pay for what the child
        needs,'' she said. </p>
        <p>That's one of the things the new Social Security
        guidelines do, at least for retroactive payments. </p>
        <p>The changes are part of the federal welfare reform
        bill Congress approved last summer. </p>
        <p>They require re-evaluations for all children
        collecting SSI for behavioral problems. Margenau said
        affected families will receive notification in February
        or March. </p>
        <p>To qualify as disabled, students will have to undergo
        a medical examination that shows their problems create
        ''marked and severe functional limitations.'' </p>
        <p>That's stricter than the current requirements,
        according to Carroll Moore, director of the Disability
        Determination Section in Nashville, which assesses
        disability claims. </p>
        <p>Moore said many claims have been approved on the basis
        of testimony from school psychologists and teachers. Now,
        applicants will need more extensive medical information. </p>
        <p>Margenau said the Social Security Administration
        estimates 260,000 of the 1 million children on SSI will
        be re-evaluated, and as many as 200,000 could lose their
        benefits. </p>
        <p>With average monthly payments of about $424, that
        could save the federal government more than $1 billion a
        year. </p>
        <p>Moreover, McCook said, it would take the label of
        ''disabled'' away from many children who might come to
        rely on it as an excuse. </p>
        <p>''Once they leave school, they're going to be in a
        society where the same rules and regulations apply across
        the board,'' he said. ''The traffic officer is not going
        to ask you, 'Were you taking Ritalin?' '' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

