<DOCHDR>
http://www.knoxnews.com:80/special/ssi/3809.htm 204.78.32.16 19970122015739 text/html 8696
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 02:00:08 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 20:21:05 GMT
Content-length: 8504
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Checks keep some afloat, sink others</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i>January 01, 1997</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="6"><b>Checks keep some
        afloat, sink others<!--SUBHEAD--></b></font><p><font size="2"><i>By
        Jesse Fox Mayshark, News-Sentinel staff writer</i></font></p>
        <p><br>
        <font size="5">A</font>t the Interfaith Health Clinic in
        the 4th and Gill neighborhood, Dr. Rob McDonald and his
        staff see 1,000 or more working poor patients a month who
        don't have health insurance. </p>
        <p>Many adults ask the doctor to give them a physical
        evaluation so they can apply for a federal disability
        check. McDonald says no. </p>
        <p>''I try to point out the importance of working and
        being productive because a lot of people I know who are
        on disability wind up becoming quite frustrated and
        depressed, and they don't know why,'' he said. </p>
        <p>''But I think it's because we were meant to work. . .
        . I have told people right to their face, 'I do not like
        disability because of what it does to you.' '' </p>
        <p>There are two kinds of disability checks: Social
        Security Disability Insurance (SSDI), paid to adults who
        have worked but become disabled, and Supplemental
        Security Income (SSI), a welfare program for disabled
        people with little or no work history. </p>
        <p>The Social Security Administration is making changes
        in both programs this year to assure the checks are given
        to people who need them, that they're spent properly and,
        when possible, that they're temporary. </p>
        <p>Starting today, the government no longer will pay
        people for being drug addicts or alcoholics. This summer,
        some children on SSI -- primarily those classified with
        attention deficit disorder or other behavioral
        disabilities -- will face re-evaluations. </p>
        <p>And with 10.8 million Americans drawing $5.1 billion
        in disability checks each month, the agency wants to do
        what it can to be sure people don't draw a check without
        trying to get better. </p>
        <p>Tom Margenau, a spokesman at the Social Security
        Administration's headquarters in Baltimore, said the
        agency is considering proposals to get more people off
        disability and back to work. </p>
        <p>''We've frankly stated that we haven't done a very
        good job of that in the past, and the statistics bear
        that out,'' he said. </p>
        <p>Will to work? </p>
        <p>Margenau said only 1 to 2 percent of people approved
        for disability leave the program because they find
        full-time work. </p>
        <p>In many cases, people are permanently disabled and
        unemployable. </p>
        <p>But officials think a lot of people currently on
        disability could be retrained for work if they're
        willing. </p>
        <p>''If they're interested, we will take them,'' said
        Bruce Brown, a field director for the state's Vocational
        Rehabilitation program. ''But 'if they're interested' is
        the $64,000 question. A lot of times they're not.'' </p>
        <p>Jim Rovere, Social Security district manager for Knox,
        Loudon, Sevier and Union counties, said his office refers
        disability applicants to Vocational Rehabilitation if
        there's a chance they can be retrained. </p>
        <p>He said many people with physical disabilities can no
        longer do manual labor but could learn other less
        strenuous skills. </p>
        <p>People on SSDI can have trial work periods of up to
        nine months during which they still receive their
        disability checks. </p>
        <p>If they are able to keep ''substantial employment''
        after nine months, the disability checks stop. </p>
        <p>But Brown said many people referred to Vocational
        Rehabilitation don't participate. He said counselors
        contact each person at least twice to offer their
        services. </p>
        <p>''Since we're completely a voluntary program, a person
        has to want our services before we provide them,'' he
        said. </p>
        <p>Last year in the entire state, Vocational
        Rehabilitation offices found full-time employment for
        just 186 people from SSI or SSDI programs, according to
        state officials. </p>
        <p>That's not to say other people on disability don't
        work. James Farr, a Social Security fraud investigator,
        said he often finds people working and not reporting it
        so they can keep their disability checks. </p>
        <p>They sometimes get caught only because they get cocky.
        </p>
        <p>''Sometimes it's a disgruntled spouse or relative,''
        Farr said. ''It could be someone working with that
        person, and they're bragging about how they're ripping
        off the government.'' </p>
        <p>Community approach </p>
        <p>Margenau said the Social Security Administration is
        looking at a number of ways to get more disabled people
        to try working. </p>
        <p>For one thing, the agency wants to raise awareness of
        the trial work period. </p>
        <p>''(People) are afraid that if they go to work, they'll
        automatically lose their benefits,'' Margenau said. </p>
        <p>Also, the adminstration recently put out a request for
        proposals to coordinate resources in communities to
        encourage retraining and re-employment. </p>
        <p>One of the companies offering a bid is Maximus, a
        for-profit social-services agency based in Virginia.
        Maximus has worked for Social Security before, most
        recently monitoring the discontinued drug and alcohol
        disability program. </p>
        <p>''We would come up with a nationwide list of clients
        who are receiving these (disability) benefits and who
        could benefit from vocational rehabilitation services,
        and then subcontractors would sign up to work with
        them,'' said Bob Muzzio, project director for Maximus. </p>
        <p>''We think that has a lot of potential because . . .
        it's trying to get people who are on disability into the
        work force. The focus would be not so much on reassessing
        (medical conditions) as on finding skills that would
        match the disability.'' </p>
        <p>Muzzio said Maximus has been successful with a similar
        program in northern Virginia which matched up welfare
        recipients with agencies that can help them find
        employment. </p>
        <p>''We've placed so many clients that we don't have any
        clients left on welfare rolls,'' he said. </p>
        <p>In addition to the money saved by putting more
        disabled people to work, Brown said a more aggressive
        rehabilitation program would lift the self-esteem of
        those receiving the checks. </p>
        <p>''Someone once said the best therapy is a job. That's
        not our official motto, but it's really true,'' Brown
        said. ''People can have a physical disability of some
        sort that they're eligible (for payments) on, but the
        real disability would be just feeling so bad about
        themselves.'' </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

