<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B30-215</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000616-B030-112</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.knoxnews.com:80/features/hunter/hunter-book.html 204.78.32.16 19970122015819 text/html 10276
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 02:00:46 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 17:34:08 GMT
Content-length: 10083
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>The Archangel Caper: Tales of a Country Cop</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--Connections 32 Template - Upfront Story Page--><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->
<p align="center"><a href="/"><img src="../../images/flag.gif"
alt="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border="0"
width="595" height="176"></a><br clear="all">
</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="150"><i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->November 12, 1996</i> </td>
        <td width="470"><font size="5"><img
        src="images/dhunter111296.gif" alt="David Hunter"
        align="left" hspace="7" vspace="7" width="312"
        height="262"></font><font size="5"><br clear="all">
        </font><font size="6"><b><img
        src="../../images/v3/credits/MCcredit.gif" width="144"
        height="21"></b></font><p><font size="6"><b>The Archangel
        Caper: Tales of a Country Cop<!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Subheadline Here--></b></font><font size="5"><br>
        Hunter's newest collection is all his own</font></p>
        <p><font size="2"><i>By Fred Brown, News-Sentinel staff
        writer</i></font></p>
        <p>He says it so cleanly, almost as if the words were
        shaped by a hand tool: When you can be brief and
        descriptive at the same time, you have a writer. </p>
        <p>He says it from experience: Write what you know. </p>
        <p>And he says it in practice: By writing short,
        descriptive sentences that are elegant and rich in color. </p>
        <p>David Hunter, 49, is a full-time writer. Once, he was
        a full-time sheriff's deputy who also happened to be a
        writer. Today, after being forced to retire because of an
        ailing heart, he is an author who writes about the men and
        women who protect us from our own worst natures. </p>
        <p>And also today, David Hunter stands at the pinnacle of
        what he always wanted to be: The warrior-poet. He is an
        effortless storyteller, who begins and ends a story with
        ease and grace. He writes like he preaches. </p>
        <p>''Good writing is not a mystical endeavor. It takes a
        whole lot more perspiration than inspiration. Anybody can
        be inspired to write or to tell a story, but that doesn't
        mean anyone is going to read it. Anytime I set down to
        read a book and the author is so clear that what he
        writes appears to be very simple, I know I'm in the
        presence of a master craftsman.'' </p>
        <p>For the past two decades, Hunter has quietly, but
        resolutely, forged a niche for himself as an author with
        a story, as a writer who has something to say. He has
        published five collections of true crime stories, two
        novels and one work in collaboration with Norma Tillman,
        a Nashville private detective. </p>
        <p>Hunter's first collection of stories, ''The Moon Is
        Always Full,'' set the pace and tone for his future
        collections. The book was packed with stories about things
        that happened to him and other police officers. In some
        instances, he changed the names. The stories, however,
        remained true to fact. </p>
        <p>He recently finished his latest collection of crime
        stories, ''The Archangel Caper,'' with a new twist. </p>
        <p>Although the stories demonstrate the unmistakable
        Hunter storytelling touch, the book is his creation all
        the way. Even his 16-year-old son, Paris, got in on the
        job by designing the attractive cover. </p>
        <p>Hunter, who is also a News-Sentinel columnist, joined
        with another News-Sentinel columnist, Don Williams, to
        create Tin Star Publishing. </p>
        <p>The two writers began with Hunter's latest work as the
        company's first venture strictly out of a sense of
        business: David Hunter's books sell. Over the years he
        has created a following that borders on cult devotion. He
        has readers from across the nation as well as fans spread
        throughout Europe. </p>
        <p>The following is so loyal, they send him old
        typewriters, which he collects. </p>
        <p>Hunter and Williams are banking on the noted author's
        appeal to launch the new publishing venture. So far, it
        is working. The book, just out, is about to break even,
        Hunter says. </p>
        <p>Hunter went from seeing policeman as part of the
        problem to being one of them. He once thought of law
        officers as evil necessities. That, he says with a smile,
        was back in his radical days. </p>
        <p>The rad days are behind him, but Hunter comes at
        writing in much the same way he did his activism, or his
        time as a policeman. He attacks. He is voracious. There
        is no mercy. </p>
        <p>He is committed. </p>
        <p>From 1980 until 1993, Hunter cruised the rough streets
        and roads of Knox County with a badge and a gun. He is
        quick to tell you that those were the tools of his trade,
        and he was an enthusiastic officer of the law. He loved being
        a cop, hauling in the bad guys. He enjoyed helping people
        in distress. He relished putting the handcuffs on evil. </p>
        <p>David Hunter was the warrior by night and the poet by
        day, writing, getting down his feelings, putting down the
        street stories. He was trying to understand the people
        with whom he worked, while at the same time following a
        high calling to keep the peace. </p>
        <p>Those diverse points have shaped him as much as
        anything. He hated leaving police work. It almost
        destroyed him, but he returned from that personal abyss
        to understand that writing was his last best calling. </p>
        <p>''Even today I think policemen are the most
        fascinating people I know,'' Hunter says while relaxing
        in his kitchen. His dog, Maxie, an expensive German
        Shepherd, wanders in with a ball in her mouth. She is
        family, Hunter says. </p>
        <p>''Policemen put their lives up for collateral every
        night. You can't talk a good game out there. You either
        do or you don't. I saw irony in abundance in police work.
        Cops are deductive thinkers, but the best also listen to
        their hunches.'' </p>
        <p>From 1979-88, he had been working and writing. It was
        good that he kept his day job, for the writing was not
        producing much results. In 1988, he began to write his
        hunches. And they have paid off. </p>
        <p>''I thought of myself as a novelist.'' </p>
        <p>That wasn't working. Then he began writing the real
        stories. He sent them off to one publisher, who turned
        them down. </p>
        <p>But Rutledge Hill Publishing in Nashville, which was
        just starting out then, said it wanted to see all of the
        stuff. </p>
        <p>The rest is history. David Hunter was launched like a
        rocket. </p>
        <p>The Nashville company published one of his novels and
        then another collection of short stories. In all,
        Rutledge Hill has published seven of his nine books. </p>
        <p>And now, he has finished one volume of an
        autobiography, also by Rutledge Hill. He says the
        autobiography became necessary because of his health
        problems. </p>
        <p>''I may not have started soon enough,'' is the way he
        puts it. He has two more volumes planned in the
        autobiographical series. </p>
        <p>The autobiography, (the first volume entitled
        ''Trailer Trash''), is about his days growing up in a
        poor section of Knoxville. Like many good writers, Hunter's
        childhood became the fuel of his pen. </p>
        <p>''I lived at the end of the line, where street cars
        turned around. It was a neighborhood full of colorful
        characters. Central Avenue back then was the only place
        in Knoxville where whites and blacks commonly mingled.
        What we had in common is that we were all poor.'' </p>
        <p>The present scene of Old City as hip-hop hangout for
        trend chasers, produces a semi-snarl-slash-smile on
        Hunter's face. </p>
        <p>''Old City today is a ghost town,'' he says. </p>
        <p>''That place had a large effect on me. You could find
        anything you wanted on Central Avenue. From
        paint-thinner, which the winos drank, to the best hot
        dogs in the world.'' </p>
        <p>Using his past as resource, David Hunter is carrying
        on that rich tradition of Knoxville writers -- from Agee
        to Madden to McCarthy to Giovanni -- who have found the
        voice of their home and their region. </p>
        <p>Hunter will sign his new book, ''The Archangel
        Caper,'' Saturday, Nov. 16, at Bookland in Maryville from
        12 noon to 2 p.m. and Sunday, Nov. 17 at Book Warehouse
        in Knoxville from 1 p.m.-3 p.m. and at Book Warehouse in
        Maryville from 4:30 p.m.-6 p.m. </p>
        <p>He will also read from the new work at the November
        meeting of the Knoxville Writers' Guild at 7 p.m. at The
        Laurel Theater, 1538 Laurel Ave. on the University of
        Tennessee campus. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr size="5">

