<title>Favorite Photos of Our Photographers</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="3" width="600">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" colspan="2" height="248"><p
        align="center">&nbsp;<img src="favorite.gif"
        alt="Favorite Frames" width="420" height="242"></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><font size="6" face="Arial,Helvetica,Frutiger"><b><tt>Click,
        click, click.<br>
        <br>
        </tt></b></font><font size="2"
        face="Arial,Helvetica,Frutiger"><b><tt><font font></tt></b>The
        shutter opens and closes exposing film to the light,
        capturing images, that will become a single photo or a
        series of photos in The Knoxville News-Sentinel. A
        variety of assignments including sports, news, features,
        fashion, and portraits give the staff of eight -- J.Miles
        Cary, Michael Patrick, Paul Efird, Clay Owen, Byron
        Small, Margaret Bentlage, Joe Howell, and Director of
        Photography Jack Kirkland -- a wide array of subject
        matter to photograph.</font><p><font size="2"
        face="Arial,Helvetica,Frutiger">&quot;I think we have one
        of the finest staffs of any newspaper our size. I enjoy
        working with each and every one of my photographers, and
        I am proud to see the quality of work they turn in on a
        daily basis. Our photographers receive regional and
        national recognition for their work, but more importantly
        they do an excellent job of visual reporting, which
        primarily benefits The News-Sentinel readers,&quot; says
        Jack Kirkland.<br>
        <br>
        Kirkland estimates his staff uses about 7,000 rolls of
        film each year. They drive and fly more than 200,000
        miles on News-Sentinel assignments. The newspaper equips
        each photographer with three Nikon cameras and an
        assortment of Nikkor lenses. &quot;This is absolutely the
        best job in the world,&quot; says Michael Patrick who is
        one of the senior photographers on staff. He has worked
        for The News-Sentinel for more than 17 years. Today, we
        pay tribute to the art and skill of News-Sentinel
        photojournalists by displaying photos on this page which
        each of them have chosen as examples of their best work
        for 1996.</font></p>
        <p><font size="2" face="Arial,Helvetica,Frutiger"><i>January
        5, 1997</i></font><font size="2"><i></font></i></font> </p>
        </td>
        <td width="235"><img src="jh/byron.gif" alt="UT vs. UK"
        align="left" hspace="0" vspace="8" width="231"
        height="183" naturalsizeflag="0"><br clear="all">
        <font size="2" face="Arial,Helvetica,Frutiger">Peak
        action is a very hard thing to capture on film, but
        Byron's picture of Kentucky's Ward Littleton breaking up
        a pass intended for UT's Troy Pratt shows perfect timing
        and focus. 1996. <b><i>Photo by Byron Small</i></b></font></td>
    </tr>
</table>
</center></div><div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="3" width="600">
    <tr>
        <td align="right" width="435" height="339">&nbsp;<img
        src="lake.jpg" alt="Glacier National Park" width="432"
        height="286"></td>
        <td><br>
        <font size="2" face="Arial,Helvetica,Frutiger">&quot;I
        took this photograph on my honeymoon in Montana's Glacier
        National Park in September. This is a Lake McDonald
        sunset. I lucked out because this was frame 38 of a 36
        exposure roll, and I did not have any more film on me at
        the time, said Bentlage. 1996. <br>
        <b><i>Photo by Margaret Bentlage.</i></b></font></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="435" height="17">&nbsp;</td>
        <td>&nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
