	<title><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->Curried tomato soup especially good this time of year</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Headline Here-->Curried tomato soup especially good this time of year</B></font><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Subheadline Here--><basefont size="6"<!--SUBHEAD--></basefont><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Byline Here-->By Louise Durman News-Sentinel food editor</I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Dateline Here--></I></FONT><BR>
		<!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><FONT SIZE="+2">I</FONT>t&#39;s a good time of year for hot soup. At Historic Rugby curried tomato soup is a special of Harrow Road Cafe.
<P>   The soup was served at a special Christmas program, and it&#39;s on the menu occasionally as one of the soup specials at the restaurant owned and operated by Historic Rugby.
<P>   Harrow Road Cafe is open for breakfast and lunch, 9 a.m. to 4 p.m., seven days a week (weather permitting) through the end of February. Beginning March 1, Harrow Road Cafe will be open 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday through Thursday, and 8 a.m. to 9:30 p.m. Fridays and Saturdays. (For information, call Historic Rugby, 1-423-628-2441.) 
<P>
<P>Curried tomato soup
<P>
<P>
<P>   1 cup chopped onion
<P>   1 cup chopped green 
<P>
<P>
<P>   Saute onion and green pepper in butter over medium heat until onion is transparent. Do not brown!
<P>   Turn off heat, and stir in curry powder and garlic powder. Transfer to large pot. Add diced tomatoes, tomato sauce and chicken stock. Bring to a slow boil or simmer, and cook for at least 30 minutes. Let cool, then run through blender on puree setting, blending just until somewhat smooth.
<P>   When time to serve, reheat and stir in sour cream. To keep sour cream from lumping, stir some of soup into sour cream, blend well, then transfer back to main pot. 
<P>   Serve in soup cups with generous sprinkle of parsley flakes or chives on top.
<P>   Makes approximately 18 soup cup servings.
<P>
<P>   For a <B>Maryville</B> resident who requested a recently published recipe for apple relish, we found the recipe in the current issue of Southern Living magazine, from Lauri Ingham, Largo, Fla.
<P>
<P>Apple relish
<P>
<P>
<P>   <B>4 apples, diced
<P>   2 dill pickles, minced
<P>   1 onion, chopped
<P>   1/4 cup apple cider vinegar
<P>   1/2 cup sugar
<P>   1/4 teaspoon salt</B>
<P>
<P>
<P>     Combine all ingredients. Cover and chill at least 2 hours. 
<P>
<P>   A chocolate sheet cake <B>Joanna Partain</B> brought to a University of Tennessee Master Gardener program was a hit with all who sampled it. 
<P>   The recipe is now making the rounds, and Partain agreed to share it with News-Sentinel readers, too.
<P>
<P>Chocolate sheet cake
<P>
<P>
<P>   1 stick margarine
<P>   1 cup water
<P>   1/2 cup solid shortening
<P> (Crisco)
<P>   4 tablespoons cocoa
<P>   2 cups 
<P>
<P>
<P>    Combine margarine, water, shortening and cocoa in a saucepan. Stirring constantly, bring to a boil. Remove from heat.
<P>   In a large mixing bowl, combine sugar, flour, buttermilk, eggs, soda, vanilla and cinnamon, if used. Pour over all the boiled mixture. Stir until mixed.
<P>   Grease and flour (or spray with vegetable coating) a 15-by-10-inch pan or 11-by-17-inch jelly roll pan. Bake 20 minutes at 350 degrees. Prepare frosting, and pour over hot cake.
<P>
<P>Frosting
<P>
<P>
<P>   <B>1 stick margarine
<P>   4 tablespoons cocoa
<P>   6 tablespoons buttermilk
<P>   1 pound confectioners&#39; sugar
<P>   11/2 cups chopped nuts
<P>   2 teaspoons vanilla</B>
<P>
<P>
<P>    Heat margarine, cocoa and buttermilk over low heat. Do not boil. Remove from heat and add confectioners&#39; sugar, nuts and vanilla. Makes 24 to 48 servings.
<P>
<P>
<P>Louise Durman is food editor of The Knoxville News-Sentinel. If you have a favorite food to serve or a request for a special recipe, write to her at P.O. Box 59038, Knoxville, TN. 37950-9038 or fax 673-3501. Please include your name, address and telephone number. If you want a recipe mailed to you, please include a stamped, self-addressed envelope.<B> We cannot accept recipes or requests by phone.</B>
<P>
<P>Recipes printed are from the sources indicated and have not been tested by The News-Sentinel.
<P><B></B>
<P>
