	<title><!--Use the Headline for HTML Page Title-->Sampler</title>
	<meta name="keywords" content="Knoxville Tennessee Newspaper">
	<meta name="GENERATOR" content="NewsView Connections32 with WebDesk">
</head>
<center><a href="/"><IMG SRC="../../images/flag.gif" ALT="A Knoxville News-Sentinel Online product" border=0></a></center><BR clear=all>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=10>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top width=150>
		<i><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Date Here-->January 15, 1997</i> 
	</td>
	<td align=left width=470>
		<FONT SIZE="6"><B><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Headline Here-->Sampler</B></font><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Subheadline Here--><basefont size="6"<!--SUBHEAD--></basefont><P>
		<FONT size="2"><I><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Byline Here--></I></FONT><P>
		<FONT SIZE="3"><I><!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Dateline Here--></I></FONT><BR>
		<!--Connections 32 with WebDesk Inserts Story Text Here--><B>Presidential fare</B>
<P>
<P>   Washington&#39;s Willard Inter-Continental is featuring presidential cuisine in The Willard Room through Monday, Jan. 20, to celebrate the upcoming inauguration. The bi-partisan menu, available at dinner only, was developed from historic White House cookbooks, according to Ann McCracken of the hotel&#39;s public relations department.
<P>   The cover of the menu is historic, too. The hotel&#39;s archives contained an old menu depicting an etching of President Abraham Lincoln viewing his inaugural parade from the old Willard in 1861.
<P>   Price range for dinner items varies from $7.50 to $9.50 for appetizers, $25.50 to $27 for entrees and $6.75 for dessert.
<P>    The Jockey Club in The Ritz-Carlton in Washington also is planning an inauguration menu through Wednesday, Jan. 22. Executive chef Hidemasa Yamamoto created the menu, inspired by the official inaugural luncheon served on Capitol Hill since President Kennedy&#39;s 1961 swearing-in. The Jockey Club opened on the eve of the Kennedy inauguration.
<P>   The three-course menu is $35 for lunch; $50 for dinner.
<P>
<P><B>Cooking classes</B>
<P>
<P>   University of Tennessee Community Programs will offer several new cooking classes this winter. Local chef Janet Powell will teach &#39;&#39;Lighter, Quicker, Better: Easy Lowfat Cooking,&#39;&#39; at Church of the Ascension, 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. Thursday, Jan. 23. Chef Eric New will teach sessions, &#39;&#39;Hearty Winter Soups and One Pot Meals,&#39;&#39; 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays, Jan. 28 and Feb. 4 at Church of the Ascension.
<P>   To register or for information on fees, call 974-0150. Space is limited, and advance registration is required.
<P>
<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
